<1ST_LINE>r i PM-HongKong-RedTide     06-13 0810</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hong Kong-Red Tide,0833</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China's Presence In Hong Kong Is Everywhere _ And Expanding</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High above Hong Kong's imposing skyline, the
final girders are swinging into place atop the Bank of China's
striking prism-shaped building.
   The 70-story glass-and-steel building, to be the local
headquarters of mainland China's official bank, is a
none-too-subtle symbol of China's unrivaled influence and growing
activity in this British colony which reverts to Chinese
sovereignty in 1997.
   Communist China's soaring presence is a result of
market-oriented economic reforms championed by Chinese leader Deng
Xiaoping in Beijing and the part of the agreement with Britain that
says Hong Kong can keep its capitalist system for 50 years after
1997.
   Chinese officials of various ranks are invading Hong Kong for a
crash course in capitalism and to secure money-making deals. The
big Chinese companies are wheeling and dealing in Hong Kong's
high-flying property market, investing in major construction
projects and even buying large blocks of local stock.
   Chinese diplomats are busy too.
   Xu Jiatun, China's top diplomat in Hong Kong, shows up at pop
concerts and cocktail parties. He heads the local branch of China's
official Xinhua News Agency but is viewed by many as the colony's
shadow government.
   Xu's main task is to promote stability and prosperity in Hong
Kong, and he is full of kind words for its capitalist society.
   ``We have some comrades who always fear capitalism, but in fact
they don't understand that the modern capitalist system is a great
creation of human civilization,'' he has told reporters.
   No official figures are available to show how many China-backed
companies are in Hong Kong, but estimates run into the thousands.
China is widely regarded as the largest foreign investor in Hong
Kong, with estimates ranging from $6 billion to $8 billion.
   The investments include department stores, factories,
supermarkets and real estate. Much of the activity is financed by
the 14-member Bank of China group, which saw profits rise by 30
percent to 60 percent in 1987, according to the Capital Information
Services financial research firm.
   China's property purchases in Hong Kong totaled about $1 billion
last year, exceeded only by Japanese and local investors, according
to William Kwan of Chesterton Petty, an international property
consulting company. China snatched up hotels, office buildings and
residential high-rises.
   ``They have to support the political confidence of people'' in
the years before 1997, Kwan said, noting that the injection of
Chinese capital creates demand and raises real estate prices.
   Some deals reflect the need for more space by expanding Chinese
companies while other deals are strictly to make money.
   China International Trust and Investment Corp., for example,
bought an office building near the central business district for
about $45 million in May 1987 and then sold it to Japanese
interests five months later for a 35 percent profit, according to
Chesterton Petty.
   Other Chinese moves that have turned heads in Hong Kong include:
   _Bailouts of financially troubled Hong Kong banks and a pledge
by the Bank of China of the equivalent in Hong Kong dollars of $128
million to save the colony's teetering futures exchange after the
global stock market crash in October.
   _The purchase by CITIC, which is China's premier international
investment company, of 12.5 percent of Cathay Pacific Airways Ltd.,
the territory's profitable flag carrier.
   _Participation of three Chinese companies in three competing
consortia bidding for a multimillion-dollar tunnel project through
the suburban New Territories.
   Matching China's flurry of economic activity in Hong Kong has
been its expanded political work.
   From the Xinhua headquarters across the street from the Happy
Valley race track, a staff of several hundred stay in touch with
nearly every sector of society.
   Hong Kong's Chinese-language Wide Angle magazine reported that
the news agency has separate departments responsible for keeping in
touch with the Hong Kong government, students, grass-root
organizations and the colony's elite.
   Joseph Y.S. Cheng, a political science lecturer at Chinese
University of Hong Kong, says China's plan to win over local
residents is ``a longtime process of befriending us, of co-opting
us, so when the Chinese come (in 1997) there's a very good chance
of us being immobilized or at least neutralized.''
   One group that China has successfully cultivated is the power
elite, who believe toeing the Beijing line is the best way to keep
their businesses healthy after 1997.
   China also can count on several local organizations to support
its policies here.
   For example, the Hong Kong Federation of Trade Unions, which
represents about 170,000 workers, mobilized its members last year
to support China's opposition to general legislative elections in
Hong Kong this year.
   This, along with the colonial government's decision to delay
elections until 1991, has led some local activists to believe China
already is calling the shots in Hong Kong.
</TEXT>
