<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Japan-Circus     06-13 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Japan-Circus,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ringling Elephants Arrive For Circus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ending a trans-Pacific boat ride, 16 bleary-eyed
performing pachyderms were greeted at a Tokyo pier by
confetti-tossing Shinto priests.
   Cranes at Tokyo Bay unloaded the Ringling Bros. and Barnum and
Bailey Circus performers on Sunday from a cargo ship that left
Oakland, Calif. June 1.
   The elephants, whose weight ranges up to 14,000 pounds,
dutifully lined up for photographers. One youngster executed a
polite bow.
   A pair of Shinto priests in ceremonial caps and robes waved
twigs at the pachyderms and threw confetti across their trunks, a
slight departure from traditional purification rites. The ritual
also bestowed hopes for success and safety for the circus' 15-week
tour of Japan.
   Ringling's lions, horses, camels, llamas and chimpanzees arrived
earlier to meet quarantine requirements. A circus official said
humans and elephants were the only animals Japanese authorities
exempted.
   The elephants continue on to the northern city of Sapporo, where
the American circus opens its first overseas tour on July 1.
</TEXT>
