<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SoftballNameGame Bjt   06-13 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Softball Name Game, Bjt,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>It's the `Gramm Slammers' vs the `Hot D'Amatos' in Congressional
Softball</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Each summer, members of Congress and their
staffs get to sum up their identities in two or three words. They
do this by naming their softball teams.
   Some of the titles are revealing.
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., calls his team ``Strom's Right
Swingers.''
   The squad fielded by Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., is the ``Buy
Americans.''
   In all, there are about 320 teams in three congressional
leagues. Many of the team titles are derived from lawmakers' names.
   There is the ``Boren To Run'' of Sen. David Boren, D-Okla.; the
``Hot D'Amatos'' of Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y; the ``Dollar
Bills'' of Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J.; the ``Bumpers Stickers'' of
Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark; the ``Graham Crackers'' of Sen. Bob
Graham, D-Fla.; the ``Gramm Slammers'' of Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas;
and ``Arlen's Darlin's'' of Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa.
   On the House side, Rep. Phil Crane, R-Ill., heads the ``Whooping
Cranes;'' Rep. Alan Wheat, D-Mo., captains the ``Wheat Germs;''
Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla., is the inspiration for the ``Hot
Peppers;'' and Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., is the mentor of the
``Congressional Franks.''
   The ``Penny Pinchers'' are named after Rep. Timothy Penny,
D-Minn.; and ``Dingell's Dingbats'' are derived from Rep. John
Dingell, D-Mich.
   The team of Rep. James Oberstar, D-Minn., is the ``Minnesota
Knee-Jerk Liberals.''
   While many of the teams are manned by congressional staffers,
the leagues are notoriously loose on who can play.
   ``We let lobbyists and trade associations in,'' said Gary
Caruso, commissioner of the 200-team Congressional ``B'' League,
which neither uses umpires nor calls balls and strikes.
   ``Sometimes we have to stretch it to, `If you pay taxes, you're
in,''' Caruso said. ``We're the `B' League _ beer-drinking league.''
   A congressional ``A'' league has about 40 teams, while a third
league fields about 80 more and consists mainly of Senate staffers.
   Former members of Congress, and even the staffs of former
presidents, are welcome.
   John Murphy, a former New York congressman from Staten Island,
still has a team called the ``Staten Island Ferries,'' according to
Caruso.
   A team of former staff members of the presidential
administration of Gerald Ford is the ``Outhouse Gang.''
   Committees and agencies also field teams. The House Select
Committee on Aging is the ``Silver Streaks.'' The Export-Import
Bank is the ``Debt Busters.''
   Some names have stories attached.
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, fields a team called ``The Right
Stuff,'' which was the title of a best-selling book and movie about
Glenn and other early astronauts.
   The ``Greatest Hits'' of Rep. Chet Atkins, D-Mass., is derived
from the congressman's country guitarist namesake.
   The team of Rep. Michael Andrews, D-Texas, is the ``No Ways, No
Means,'' reflecting his membership on the House Ways and Means
Committee. Some team members want to change the name to ``Ways, But
No Means.''
   But some names are incomprehensible, at least to outsiders.
   ``There's one team called `Shoot The Wounded,''' said Vince
Morelli, a commissioner of the ``A'' league. ``I have no reason to
understand that one.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
