<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PollMethod     06-13 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poll Method,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Poll-Presidential Choices, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Media General-Associated Press poll is
based on telephone interviews April 29-May 8 with 1,204 adults in
the continental United States. The phone numbers were selected
randomly by computer and interviews were conducted with the adult
who had the most recent birthday.
   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the
sample. The poll has a three-point margin of error, meaning the
results theoretically would be within three points of the same 19
times out of 20 if every adult American were asked the same
questions. The error margin is larger for subgroups _ five points
for Republicans, for example.
   There are other sources of potential error in polls, including
the wording and order of questions. These are the questions and
responses in this poll:
   1. Presidents now are limited to two four-year terms in office.
Do you think it should be one-six year term, stay at two four-year
terms, be three four-year terms, or four or more four-year terms?
   One six-year: 16 percent. Two four-year: 65 percent. Three
four-year: 8 percent. Four or more four-year: 5 percent. None of
these: 4 percent. Don't know or no answer: 2 percent.
   2. If Ronald Reagan could run again, would you vote for him for
a third term as president?
   Yes: 32 percent. No: 64 percent. Don't know or no answer: 4
percent.
   3. I'm going to read a few attributes that might be found in a
candidate for president. Tell me if each would make you more likely
to vote for that candidate for president, or less likely to vote
for that candidate, or if it wouldn't matter.
   a. A woman. More likely: 10 percent. Less: 25 percent. Not
matter: 64. DK-NA: 2 percent.
   b. A black. More likely: 5 percent. Less: 27 percent. Not
matter: 66 percent. DK-NA: 3 percent.
   4. Would you be more likely or less likely to vote for a ticket
that has a woman candidate for vice president, or wouldn't it
matter?
   More likely: 10 percent. Less: 14 percent. Not matter: 75
percent. DK-NA: 1 percent.
   5. Would you be more likely or less likely to vote for a ticket
that has a black candidate for vice president, or wouldn't it
matter?
   More likely: 6 percent. Less: 18 percent. Not matter: 75
percent. DK-NA: 1 percent.
   6. Do you think it matters who's elected president?
   Yes: 89 percent. No: 9 percent. DK-NA: 2 percent.
   7. Would you want the job of president?
   Yes: 11 percent. No: 89 percent. DK-NA: 1 percent.
   8. Would you want your child to grow up to be president?
   Yes: 41 percent. No: 46 percent. DK-NA: 13 percent.
   9. Do you think it's possible your child could grow up to be
president?
   Yes: 59 percent. No: 34 percent. DK-NA: 8 percent.
</TEXT>
