<2ND_LINE>PM-White House-Tennis,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Celebrities Turn Out for White House Tennis Benefit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennis balls zoomed like missiles over the
White House lawn, causing even President and Nancy Reagan to duck,
but it was all for a good cause as some $500,000 was raised to
combat drug abuse.
   Celebrities, tennis pros and administration officials gathered
Sunday at the White House tennis court for the fourth annual
fund-raising event.
   The president and first lady joined a crowd of several hundred
guests and corporate sponsors, watching tennis stars Tracy Austin,
Vince Van Patten Jimmy Arias and Dennis Ralston compete in a match
that had no winners _ local sportscaster and master of ceremonies
Glenn Brenner got the score mixed up.
   The first couple also saw Secretary of State George Shultz and
GOP Chairman Frank Fahrenkopf go down to defeat at the hands of
Treasury Secretary James Baker III and Wilhelm Wachtmeister, the
ambassador of Sweden.
   Shultz, just back from his round of travels to the Soviet Union,
Middle East and Spain, appeared to fall victim to jet lag with his
double faults.
   Old and new CIA hands faced off when current CIA director
William Webster and newsman Morton Kondracke opposed former CIA
director Richard Helms and actor Dick Van Patten.
   Helms, resplendent in traditional men's long slacks, was
declared by Brenner to be the winner of the day's ``sartorial
award,'' but he also managed to scoop up a win with a number of
tough lobs and strong net play.
   Other participants included actresses Dina Merrill, Catherine
Oxenberg and Tracy Scoggins, actor Chuck Norris, singers Lee
Greenwood and Larry Gatlin, boxer Sugar Ray Leonard and football
player Herschel Walker.
   At the end of the tournament, Mrs. Reagan presented $50,000
checks to two anti-drug abuse groups, the Target Interactive
Project of Kansas City, Mo., and Wally's Club and Frontline Foster
Grandparents Program of Nashville, Tenn.
   ``Because of their work, the lives of many parents and children
will be much brighter,'' Mrs. Reagan said.
</TEXT>
