<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-NetWorth     06-13 0938</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Net Worth,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Has Net Worth Of At Least $500,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, who once described himself as a
``man of few wants,'' lives in a duplex he bought 17 years ago for
$25,000, drives a 5-year-old Dodge, buys his clothes at a bargain
basement and generally vacations at the homes of friends or family.
   Despite his frugal lifestyle _ or perhaps because of it _ the
apparent Democratic presidential nominee has a net worth of at
least $500,000 in property, investments and salary and is the
potential beneficiary of about $1 million controlled by trusts,
according to his financial disclosure forms and statements made by
his presidential campaign aides.
   James Dorsey, the governor's Statehouse press secretary, said
the Dukakises ``live comfortably,'' but added: ``Nowadays there
isn't much time to spend money on anything.''
   The last time the Democratic presidential nominee-to-be took a
financial risk was 25 years ago when, following the lead of two
uncles in Haverhill a half century before, he took out two
mortgages to buy the six-apartment building he was living in for
$55,000.
   The investment proved successful. In 1971, eight years after
buying the apartment building in the Boston suburb of Brookline,
Dukakis sold off the apartments as condominiums _ one of the first
condo conversions in the state _ for a reported $26,000 profit.
   Earlier that year, he and his wife, Kitty, moved out of the
apartment building and bought half of a side-by-side brick duplex
down the street for $25,000.
   The Dukakises still live in that modest, three-story duplex _
since Massachusetts is one of only three states that doesn't
provide a governor's residence. But as a result of New England's
inflated real estate climate, the Dukakis home now carries an
estimated value of $367,400.
   Like many Americans, the Dukakis' home is the governor's single
largest investment. Unlike many Americans, Dukakis has paid off the
mortgage. Indeed, the governor, who refuses to use credit cards,
has no reported debts.
   His only independent stock investment totals less than $1,000 in
a small Massachusetts-based robotics manufacturer, Automatix Inc.,
which brought him less than $100 in income last year, according to
his financial disclosure forms.
   The governor has no vacation homes _ his vacations are usually
mixed with family visits to a cousin's home in Ft. Lauderdale,
Fla., to Mrs. Dukakis' sister's home on Cape Cod or to her father's
summer home in the Berkshires.
   He has no airplanes, boats or a garage full of cars. The only
car owned by the man who likes to ride the subway to work is a 1983
Dodge valued last year at $2,750.
   Dukakis, 54, has put his money into long-term investments aimed
at retirement or benefiting his three children. After 25 years in
state politics, first as a legislator and now as a three-term
governor, Dukakis has built his state retirement account up to
$49,494.
   If the governor has taken out life insurance, his federal and
state financial disclosure forms don't reveal it and his
presidential campaign staff won't discuss it.
   He and Mrs. Dukakis have $44,610 in various savings, Individual
Retirement Accounts and checking accounts, some of which are
considered trusts for his children, the campaign staff said.
   The governor and his wife reported total income last year of
$108,957. Virtually all of it was from his $85,000-a-year
governor's salary and Mrs. Dukakis' $20,000 as a part-time director
of the Public Space Partnership Project at Harvard University's
Kennedy School of Government and the $2,000 she earned as director
of a college textbook publisher. The Dukakis' interest income
amounted to $1,445.
   Dukakis also is the potential beneficiary of money from two $1
million trusts set up by his late father, Panos. However, half the
money in those trusts is slated to go to Bates College in Maine,
where Dukakis' father went to school.
   Dukakis has reported two additional trusts, valued at a total of
$110,000, which were set up by Mrs. Dukakis' late grandmother,
Mabel Williams, and her father, Harry Ellis Dickson. But only the
governor's wife and children are potential beneficiaries.
   Dukakis has no direct control over or involvement in any of
these trusts.
   It was one of the trusts set up by Dukakis' father that drew
attention last year when the governor filed a report with the
Federal Election Commission revealing that until 1986 _ when he was
running for re-election _ the trust included stocks in companies
doing business in South Africa. In 1983, Dukakis vocally supported
and signed legislation to divest Massachusetts pension fund stocks
with South African ties to protest that country's system of racial
segregation.
   Dukakis, before withdrawing as a trustee of the trust last year,
told the State Street Bank & Trust Co. of Boston, which manages the
trust, to divest any South African-tied stocks. Stocks in 10
companies were immediately sold.
   Today the trust, in which Dukakis' mother, Euterpe, and his
campaign chairman, Paul Brountas, are trustees, has holdings in 21
companies, including IBM, several of the so-called ``Baby Bells''
spawned by the breakup of American Telephone and Telegraph Co. and
The Washington Post Co.
   So, could Dukakis be called a millionaire? ``It's not accurate
to say that, no,'' campaign spokesman Steve Akey said. ``Potential,
yes.''
   It was during discussion last year over raising the governor's
salary from $75,000 to an advisory board's recommendation of
$125,000 that Dukakis described himself as a ``man of few wants.''
   Dukakis, who eventually agreed to a $10,000 raise in governor's
pay, balked at the board's further recommendation for a
$25,000-a-year housing allowance, saying he could live on almost
any salary, ``within reason.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
