<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Democrats-Excerpts     06-13 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democrats-Excerpts,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Platform Drafters Stake Out Preliminary Positions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Democrats-Platform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MACKINAC ISLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from the issue
working papers released by the Democratic platform drafting
committee. They were written by staff and Dukakis and Jackson
campaign officials.
   Rep. William Gray III, D-Pa., the panel's chairman, said Sunday
they represent ``a collection of preliminary working papers ... not
a platform plank or draft yet.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DRUGS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   It calls for mobilizing ``every arm and agency of government ...
under the direction of a `National Drug Czar' to halt both the
international supply and the domestic demand for illegal drugs now
ravaging our country.'' It suggests enlisting ``every useful
military'' means and strengthening the Coast Guard and U.S.
Customs, as well as bolstering drug education.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>EDUCATION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``The education of our citizens, from Head Start to institutions
of higher learning, deserves our highest priority,'' it says. It
promises to expand pre-school for the poor, create a National
Teacher Corps, increase aid for bilingual education, and provide
``incentives to equalize funding for school districts.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CIVIL RIGHTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``We will rebuild the civil rights enforcement machinery, combat
the recent surge in hate violence and cease the discriminatory
English-only movement,'' it says. It calls for adoption of an Equal
Rights Amendment and, avoiding the word abortion, says, ``Freedom
of reproductive choice should be guaranteed regardless of ability
to pay.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HOUSING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``A Democratic administration is committed to ending
homelessness, expanding the supply of affordable housing, providing
assistance to first-time homebuyers and preserving and expanding
the inventory of public and subsdized housing.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HEALTH CARE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``The Democratic Party is committed to the goal of providing,
through federal coodination, universal access to comprehensive
health services, including pre-natal care for pregnant women at
risk, long-term care and basic insurance for all citizens.'' It
promises more support for AIDS research and ``measures to prevent
discrimination and stigmatization of those testing positive for the
HIV antibody.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ECONOMY, JOBS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Reasserting progressive values, with a strong commitment to
fiscal responsibility, it is time for our government to invest in
new priorities, to achieve a better balance of fiscal and monetary
policy and to put forth policies which ensure that we export more
American goods and fewer American jobs.'' It says, ``Advance notice
of plant closings and major layoffs is not only right, it is
economically sound.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ENERGY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``We will increase cooperation with our hemispheric neighbors,
fill the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, provide targeted incentives
for new oil and gas drilling, and aggressively develop clean coal
technology'' to help combat acid rain. ``We must halt reliance on
all those nuclear power plants which are unsafe or environmentally
unsound.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ENVIRONMENT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``The federal government will vigorously promote recycling,
aggressively enforce toxic waste laws and require polluters to be
responsible for future clean-up costs.'' The Democrats ``strongly
oppose offshore oil drilling in environmentally sensitive areas.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ARICULTURE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   After ``the disastrous Republican farm policies of the last
seven years,'' it says, ``the best support for family farmers is a
fair price from the market.'' The Democrats' policy ``will include
supply management, credit and foreclosure relief, the return of
federally held foreclosed lands to beginning, minority and
restarting farmers and the development of new uses and markets for
American farm products.'
</TEXT>
