<HEAD>Dukakis Hopes To Bring People Together Like RFK</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis said in an interview with British
broadcasters that he's not ``a razzle-dazzle performer'' but still
hopes to unite Americans the way the late Sen. Robert F. Kennedy
did.
   The Massachusetts governor said in the interview broadcast
Sunday that Kennedy had an unusual ability to bring blacks,
Hispanics, the elderly and white ethnic communities together.
   ``People saw him as being somebody who cared about people
everywhere _ and I'd like to think I'm that kind of person and
that's the kind of leadership I want to bring to the presidency,''
he said in an interview on the Channel 4 television program ``The
World This Week.''
   Dukakis, who was interviewed last week in California, appeared
unconcerned about criticism that he lacks charisma.
   ``I must be doing something right if I've been able to come
through this 15 months successfully,'' he said.
   ``I'm not a razzle-dazzle performer on the stage. I think I give
a reasonably decent speech, but my strength is in working with
people, in bringing people together, in my love of public service,
in the importance that I place on building coalitions,'' he said.
   ``I think people are ready for somebody who comes to the White
House, sure with warmth and feeling _ obviously I have that _ but
with the ability to get the job done. And I think that's what the
American people are looking for. It's certainly my great strength
and it's the reason that we've done as well as we've done,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Schroeder Criticizes Bush, Dukakis for Avoiding Domestic Issues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Rep. Pat Schroeder says both national
party front-runners have failed to take a stand on domestic issues
including child care.
   ``We need to find out what their (Republican George Bush and
Democrat Michael Dukakis) vision for the 21st century is,''
Schroeder, of Colorado, told the 38th national convention of the
League of Women Voters here Saturday.
   She urged the members to bring greater attention to family,
child care, economic and nuclear issues, citing a recent poll that
listed those as the top concerns of Americans.
   ``A very sensible list. But these are not the `power issues' in
Washington,'' she said, taking a slap at a presidential campaign
she considered joining last year.
   ``We have so stylized the campaigns anymore (that) we're going
to have to outlaw decaffeinated coffee (until after the election)
or we'll all fall asleep,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Takes Humorous Jabs At Bush And Himself At Press Roast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis responded with a bit of
mimicry when he received a mock congratulatory telegram from
President Reagan and his wife, Nancy, at a press roast.
   ``Thank you, Dan,'' said the straight-faced recipient.
   Dan? Yes, Dan, as in CBS anchorman Dan Rather, who had an
infamous interview with Dukakis' Republican opponent, George Bush.
And ``Dan'' as in the name Bush repeatedly used to refer to his
interviewer, Ted Koppel, on ABC-TV's ``Nightline'' program last
week.
   It was a night of lampoons Saturday as Dukakis was honored by
the Boston Press Photographers Association. The Massachusetts
governor, who has rarely strayed from his straightforward delivery
on the campaign trail, poked fun at his chief rival, selection of a
running mate and even himself.
   Dukakis told the gathering he took a break that afternoon to go
``to a Harvard boutique to pick up my speech for tomorrow,'' a jibe
at Bush's characterization of Dukakis as an elitist.
   Master of ceremonies Bob Warren presented him with a cardboard
presidential seal with a likeness of a cod in place of the bald
eagle.
   He laughed again when another seal was attached to the podium;
the sign said the official seal of ``The Next President of the
United States.''
</TEXT>
