<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     06-13 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Focuses On Anti-Drug Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic nominee-to-be Michael Dukakis says as
president, he would wage a ``real war on drugs'' _ something he
says the Reagan administration has failed to do.
   Dukakis was focusing on drug issues today. He had meetings set
with leaders of his state anti-drug program and with members of
Congress to discuss national efforts to fight drugs.
   A day earlier, Dukakis was in Utah to address the nation's
mayors, and was harshly critical of the administration's dealings
with Panama's Manuel Antonio Noriega, who is under indictment on
drug charges.
   If elected, Dukakis told the U.S. Conference of Mayors in Salt
Lake City on Sunday, he would tell the CIA and other agencies:
``Never again, never again are you going to bankroll a drug peddler
who's poisoning our society and killing our children.''
   Dukakis also chided Reagan for ignoring efforts by Latin
American leaders to get Noriega to step down.
   ``They tried to go it alone and they fell flat on their face,''
Dukakis said of administration efforts to oust Noriega.
   Dukakis said he would direct more foreign aid to anti-drug
efforts, including support for drug-crop eradication and step up
protection of officials in drug-producing nations who have ``the
guts to join us in this war.''
   He said the military should be prepared to assist those efforts.
   Dukakis outlined a domestic anti-drug effort he said would
include tougher drug laws and stiffer fines, property seizures and
sentences, along with increased cooperation between federal, state
and local law enforcement agencies. He called for expanded drug
education for students and teachers, and guaranteed access to drug
treatment.
   ``For us, the stakes are clear,'' Dukakis said in a speech well
received by the mayors, a largely Democratic group. ``The war is
on.''
   Dukakis did not mention his certain Republican challenger, Vice
President George Bush, by name. But he attacked administration
anti-drug efforts, in which Bush played a part when he headed an
anti-drug task force.
   ``What we have today is chaos,'' Dukakis said of the
administration's anti-drug effort.
   Dukakis picked up endorsements from more than 500 Democratic
mayors and vice mayors.
   Dukakis held a private gathering with several black mayors who
support Jesse Jackson's presidential campaign. Several described
the meeting as a positive step toward building black support for
Dukakis, but added that how he resolves differences with Jackson
will be a crucial factor.
   Before leaving for Boston, Dukakis met with leaders of the
Church of Latter Day Saints and separately with actor Robert
Redford.
</TEXT>
