<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0808 06-13 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0808,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stock Prices Rise Moderately</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with closing figures, picks up
graf 3 pvs ```Led mainly'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo stock market's key indicator on Monday
closed at its second highest level ever, while the U.S. dollar
gained ground against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 151.66-point
loser on Friday, bounced back 117.14 points, or 0.41 percent, to
close at 28,037.50 points. It had closed at a record 28,072.02
points on Thursday.
   The dollar finished at 125.19 yen, up 0.34 yen from Friday's
close. It had opened at 125.07 yen and ranged between 125.00-125.20
yen during the day.
   ``Led mainly by large-capital issues, the index rose following
last Friday's rise on Wall Street,'' said an official of a major
securities firm, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He added that stock prices were mixed in part because some
investors took to the sidelines prior to the release of April U.S.
trade figures, due out Tuesday.
   The dollar moved little in sluggish trading, dealers said.
   ``The market is holding steady as participants are waiting for
the U.S. trade figures,'' said an official of a major Tokyo
commercial bank, who requested anonymity.
   An exchange dealer at another commercial bank said the dollar
``was strengthened'' after a weekend remark by U.S. Federal Reserve
Board Vice Chairman Manuel Johnson that there was room for the U.S.
currency to rise.
   Johnson, speaking to reporters Saturday in West Germany, said he
thought ``there would be a certain tolerance for (the dollar to
rise).''
</TEXT>
