<2ND_LINE>BC-Runway Accident, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0482,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Repeating</HEAD>
<HEAD>Boeing 727 Goes Off Runway, Minor Injuries Among The 82 Aboard</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with plane on grassy area, investigators
checking possible causes of accident. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Alaska Airlines plane went off a runway after
landing late Sunday at Seattle-Tacoma International Airport, and
minor injuries were reported among the 82 people aboard, officials
said.
   Neither the number hurt nor the nature of their injuries was
immediately known, said Port of Seattle spokeswoman Margo Spellman.
   The Boeing 727 was carrying 75 passengers and seven crew members
from Tucson, Ariz., said Spellman.
   The extent of damage to the airplane was not immediately known.
Ms. Spellman said the passengers were evacuated from the plane via
emergency chutes.
   The accident occurred after Flight 187 landed at about 10:20
p.m., she said.
   The jetliner veered off a runway while landing and came to a
rest on a grassy strip dividing Sea-Tac's two parallel runways,
said Port Police spokesman John Eliadis.
   He said investigators were checking to see whether the plane
might have blown a tire upon landing or had struck debris on the
runway.
   Eliadis said the airport was closed to aircraft for about 15
minutes after the accident, but subsequently was re-opened to
departing traffic.
   Alaska Airlines officials were not immediately available for
comment.
</TEXT>
