<DOCNO> AP880613-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 0350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-CityCelebrates Bjt   06-13 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-City Celebrates, Bjt,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Celebrity Capital Celebrates Diamond Jubilee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA WOLFSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city that boasts the highest
average income in the country and attracts more tourists than
Disneyland is preparing to celebrate the 75th anniversary of its
sprouting from a lima bean field.
   And as one would expect from this capital of conspicuous
consumption, the 14-month-long extravaganza will be on a grand
scale, starting with a July 3 musical extravaganza, followed by an
ABC-TV special and a float in the Rose Parade.
   Former talk show host Merv Griffin, who owns the Beverly Hilton
Hotel, and singer Dinah Shore are the hosts of the musical, which
will include performers Jimmy Stewart, Betty White, Robert Stack
and Dick Van Patten.
   Merchants also are getting into the act, as only Beverly Hills
merchants can. Harry Winston, one of its more exclusive jewelry
stores, is crafting a slice of birthday cake iced with real
diamonds, said to be worth millions of dollars.
   The Labor Day weekend 1989 grand finale will bring together the
world's top fashion designers in what's touted as the world's
largest fashion show. More than 1,000 models will promenade along a
2{-block runway down Rodeo Drive.
   ``We want to attract as many people as possible,'' said event
chairman George Fenimore, who estimated the 14-month celebration's
cost at $1.6 million.
   Throughout much of its history, Beverly Hills, with its lavish
mansions and fashionable boutiques, has attracted worldwide
interest.
   ``It's just the fame of it,'' said tourist Sue Brown of
Doncaster, England. ``It's all very exciting. Most people know
Rodeo Drive, even in our little town.''
   The Los Angeles Visitors and Convention Bureau estimated that
between 16 million and 18 million tourists last year ambled through
the Golden Triangle, Beverly Hills' downtown district, compared
with 13 million at Disneyland.
   No wonder Beverly Hills is celebrating. The average annual
income in the 5.6-square-mile city is $125,000. There are more
licensed gardeners per capita than in any other U.S. city and more
Rolls Royces per capita than in London.
   There are more than $8 billion in deposits at its 100 financial
institutions, making it the nation's richest banking community
after New York. There's also a doctor for every 52 residents.
   Beverly Hills High School students watch from their football
field as an oil derrick pumps black gold from the school's 17 oil
wells.
   But what really separates Beverly Hills from other wealthy
communties is it's association with the entertainment industry.
   In 1920, Mary Pickford and Douglas Fairbanks built their
legendary home, Pickfair, in the northern reaches of the city. The
home has since been owned by Los Angeles Lakers owner Jerry Buss
and most recently by Meshulam Riklis and his singer-wife, Pia
Zadora.
   It all began in 1912 when developer Burton Green built a pink
and green palace, the Beverly Hills Hotel, above a bridal path
called Sunset Boulevard, on 12 acres of a lima bean field.
   The hotel was built at a then-staggering $500,000, today just a
fraction of home prices in the city.
   It was, and still is, the focal point of the city's social life.
In 1923, Will Rogers was inaugurated as the city's first honorary
mayor there, and its famous polo lounge is the site of the ultimate
power breakfast.
   In 1942, Billionaire Howard Hughes lived in four of the hotel's
famous bungalows, two used as decoys from reporters.
   Stewart, who filmed part of the 1946 classic ``It's A Wonderful
Life'' at Beverly Hills High, moved here with his family in 1948.
He often walks his two golden retrievers through his neighborhood.
   ``I wave to the tourist buses and sign people's maps to the
star's homes,'' said Stewart, who was honored by the five-member
City Council earlier this month as Man of the Year.
   ``A lot of people come up to me and say, `That guy looks like
Dean Martin,''' said Joe Patti, whose La Famiglia restaurant is a
popular celebrity hangout. ``And I say, `That IS Dean Martin.'''
   All the hoopla aside, Beverly Hills is a thriving city of
33,000, known for its community-oriented government.
   New commercial developments are limited to three stories and
fast food chains are banned. Its schools are among the nation's
best, with 93 percent of its students going on to college.
   ``I have great affection for Beverly Hills,'' Stewart said.
``It's a city built for the benefit of the community itself, not
just for a small group of celebrities.''
   ``Some people say, `Oh, you're just a snob from Beverly Hills,'
'' restaurateur Patti added. ``Well, they're just jealous.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
