<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Terrorism     06-13 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Terrorism,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Embassy Cancels Terrorist Warning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Embassy has begun notifying American
residents that they no longer need limit their movements to avoid a
possible terrorist attack. On Thursday, the embassy warned the more
than 1,500 Americans living in Beijing to take precautions. The
Chinese government had told it unidentified terrorists from a third
country might attack U.S. citizens in the capital.
   On Sunday, the embassy canceled its warning after the Chinese
assured U.S. officials the danger was over.
   ``The Chinese government informed us today that it has taken
effective action to ensure that persons who intended to harm
American citizens will not be able to do so,'' Embassy spokesman
McKinney Russell said Sunday.
   Late Saturday, the official Xinhua News Agency issued a
statement by the vice minister of public security, Gu Linfang,
saying ``necessary measures'' had been taken and ``the problem has
been solved.'' Gu did not elaborate.
   Xinhua quoted Gu as saying that ``some persons recently
attempted to harm Americans in China,'' but Russell said he was not
aware of any attempted attack.
   Russell said the Chinese government did not tell the embassy the
nationality of the alleged plotters. A U.S. official in Washington
who spoke on condition of anonymity said last week that there was
Middle Eastern involvement.
   Several Western hotels increased their security staff in
response to the warning. The International School run by the United
States and four other foreign governments blocked off its road and
tightened security.
   The embassy also recommended that Americans avoid restaurants or
bars known to be gathering points for Americans and avoid wearing
clothing that clearly identified them as American.
   U.S. officials refused to say what steps were taken to increase
security on the four compounds that house embassy offices and
Ambassador Winston Lord's residence.
</TEXT>
