<DOCNO> AP880613-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 0508EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam     06-13 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Retiring 70 Army Generals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam is retiring more than 70 army
generals and about 3,000 colonels this month as part of its policy
of reducing one of the world's largest armies, a Vietnamese
newspaper editor said today.
   Bui Tin, a deputy editor in chief of the official Communist
Party newspaper Nhan Dan (The People), said younger officers will
fill some vacated posts but other posts will be eliminated. Many of
the officers have stayed on despite having passed retirement age,
he said.
   Some of the retiring officers, including the commander in chief
of Vietnamese forces in Cambodia, will return home when Vietnam
begins withdrawing troops from that country later this month, Tin
told reporters in Bangkok. He declined to name the commander.
   Vietnam has said it will withdraw 50,000 troops from Cambodia
this year as part of its plan for a total withdrawal by 1990. It
says the entire military command will be transferred to the
pro-Vietnamese Cambodian government.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978. By U.S. estimate, it
maintains 120,000 troops there to combat guerrillas.
   Vietnamese officials have said their army must be reduced so
resources can be concentrated on economic development, which the
party has set as the country's top priority.
   Tin compared the campaign to a simultaneous effort to streamline
the government to promote greater efficiency.
   According to London's International Institute of Strategic
Studies, Vietnam's army of 1.1 million men is tied with India as
the world's third largest, behind China and the Soviet Union.
   Tin noted that as a proportion of the total population,
Vietnam's army is much larger than that of China and India.
   He said Vietnam's serious unemployment problem will worsen as
soldiers return to civilian life.
</TEXT>
