<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     06-13 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARREN, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three minutes and 2} pounds of pink tomatoes
later, 10-year-old Danny Orton was the newly crowned champion of
the annual tomato eating contest at the Bradley County Pink Tomato
Festival.
   ``I'm hungry. I didn't eat since dinner last night,'' Orton said
before chomping and chewing his way past two-time defending
champion Chuck Allen and two other adults Saturday for the title
and the $50 prize.
   Orton, of Hermitage, was the first contestant to take his seat
before a heap of tomatoes, and he listened attentively as the
referee explained the rules, including the three-minute time limit.
   Allen, who won last year by tossing down more than 5 pounds of
tomatoes, had been the odds-on favorite to repeat this year. He
said before the contest that he did not feel well. He came out slow
and finished in a three-way tie for second place with Jay Wisener
and Dallas Davis.
   ``I think it messed me up on tomatoes,'' Davis, who works in a
tomato shed, said of the experience.
   The youngest contestant, 7-year-old Daniel Tucker of Star City,
said he entered because, ``I wanted to get some money and I like
eating good tomatoes.''
   He paused at intervals during the contest and used his T-shirt
to wipe tomato juice from his chin.
   More than 20,000 people attended this year's festival, which
also featured the popular all-tomato luncheon, where every item on
the menu except coffee and tea had tomatoes as an ingredient.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AMARILLO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fast talking and an eye for cattle paid
off for a Texas man who beat out 65 other livestock auctioneers to
win the $1,000 prize at the 25th annual World Livestock Auctioneeer
Championship.
   Joe Don Pogue of Sulphur Springs also took home a championship
ring. Jerry Welschmeyer of Vienna, Mo., was reserve champion,
followed by Sam Teply of Lexington, Neb., in the contest sponsored
by the Livestock Marketing Association.
   The contestants Saturday each sported their own particular
calling style, ranging from low-key and straightforward to flashy
and loquacious.
   And they did run on.
   ``Here they come. They're good ones,'' called Keith Dinwoodie of
Armstrong, British Columbia, as a group of cattle was driven into
the ring. ``Look at the legs on 'em. The quality's here. Just the
way you want to buy 'em, fellas.''
   Dinwoodie, a former winner in the world all-around competition,
said his natural propensity to babble led him into livestock
selling.
   ``I grew up in Alberta on a ranch. I was kind of a mouthy kid,
and one day my dad and uncle said, `Why don't you be an
auctioneer?'''
   The tricky part of selling livestock, auctioneers say, is
keeping a close eye on buyers, whose bidding motions sometimes
merely resemble nervous tics.
   ``The bidders out here today have been super,'' said John Tarter
of Smiths Grove, Ky., one of 15 finalists. ``When they bid you can
really see it. Sometimes you get the eye winkers and finger
wigglers.''
   Along with sharp eyes, auctioneers have to talk fast and still
be understood, and that takes practice.
   Many participants attended auction school, but they said
practice makes perfect.
   ``I practice while I'm driving,'' said Duane Baxley from Paso
Robles, Calif., another finalist. ``Some people sing or talk to
themselves while driving _ I practice selling.''
</TEXT>
