<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Airport-Weapons     06-13 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airport-Weapons,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Teen-Ager Arrested After Weapons Found In Luggage At
Airport</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER SHINKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese teen-ager was arrested after he
tried to sneak explosives, a dismantled rifle, a pellet gun and
dummy hand grenades aboard an airplane, authorities said.
   Sunday morning's discovery of the weapons in the youth's luggage
led authorities to close and evacuate one of five terminals at
Philadelphia International Airport for several hours.
   Yoshino Kosugi, 18, of Yokohama, Japan, was charged with
attempting to board an aircraft with firearms, explosives or
incendiary devices, said FBI agent John Kundts.
   Kosugi, a student at Drexel University, was scheduled to appear
before a federal magistrate today, Kundts said. Upon conviction,
the maximum sentence for the charge is five years in prison and a
$25,000 fine.
   Kosugi collects military paraphernalia, said Kundts.
   ``Contact with foreign authorities had determined at this time
no known association with a terrorist organization,'' Kundts said.
   Police detained Kosugi shortly after he tried to check in at the
last minute for an early morning Northwest Airlines flight to
Tokyo, said Detective Warren Rosen.
   When Kosugi's baggage was examined, the rifle and grenades were
found along with the pellet gun, carbon dioxide cartridges,
fireworks and flares, police Capt. Stanley Puchalski said.
   Also found was explosive black powder and some unspecified
ammunition that police were checking to determine whether it was
live, he said.
   Police bomb squad officers were called in and ordered the
evacuation of the terminal, Puchalski said. Departures were
delayed, but after nearly 3{ hours, the terminal began operating
normally, he said.
   Kundts said Kosugi was in the United States on a student visa,
but he did not know if Kosugi was leaving the country permanently.
   In April, Yu Kikumara, a Japanese national with links to the
terrorist Japanese Red Army, was arrested at a New Jersey Turnpike
rest stop after explosives were found in his car.
</TEXT>
