<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 0602EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CBSAffiliates     06-13 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CBS Affiliates,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS President Vows To Return Network to No. 1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS President Laurence Tisch admits making
mistakes that led to the network's slump to third place in the
ratings, but vows to make changes to return it to the top spot.
   ``I have heard your concerns and disappointments loud and
clear,'' Tisch said at Sunday's opening session of the three-day
CBS affiliates conference.
   CBS fell to third place in the A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings last
season for the first time in its history.
   ``We share your disappointment with our prime-time ratings last
season,'' he said. ``We will not settle for third or even second
place. Our highest priority is to restore CBS to No. 1. We will use
every resource and we are committed to that goal.''
   Tisch said the network would improve programming and the
promotion of that programming.
   ``We must be more aggressive in bringing our programming to the
attention of the public through promotion,'' he said, adding that
the network was putting new people in charge of on-the-air
promotion.
   Asked to identify an area where he had specifically made a
mistake, Tisch said he felt he should not have encouraged the
entertainment division to drop the Tuesday night movie and put in a
block of four comedies.
   ``I think if we had not done that and I had not encouraged them
to do that, we would not have ended up in third place,'' he said.
   In addition to its ratings woes, CBS has been beset by
programming delays resulting from the 14-week writers' strike, news
budget cuts and buyout rumors.
   ``There is one thing I want to make clear,'' said Tisch, who is
also chairman of Loews Corp. ``Despite rumors, CBS and Loews stock
is not for sale. The network is not for sale.''
   The estimated 800 people attending the luncheon burst into
applause.
   Tisch said he believed the price tag of $243 million for the
1992 Winter Olympics was a smart investment. He said he had been
criticized for the bid but said it was the first time anyone had
accused him of overspending.
   ``We have seen how two weeks of Olympic coverage can raise an
entire network and boost the ratings of its schedule,'' he said.
   Tisch said he didn't plan to put CBS into the cable business, as
ABC and NBC are, saying he felt ``the American public would be
better served by strengthening over-the-air broadcasting.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
