<DOCNO> AP880613-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 0604EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PAM-MylarSculpture     06-13 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PAM-Mylar Sculpture,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mylar Tape Sculpture Removed From Aspen Mountain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASPEN, Colo.(AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six miles of shimmering Mylar tape, described
as a sculpture, has been removed from Aspen Mountain and wrapped
around the entrance to the Aspen Art Museum, sponsor of the exhibit.
   The tape exhibit, named ``Beacon Interrogator,'' was completed
last week for an art show entitled ``Sculpture-Aspen 1988.''
   When construction began on Thursday, protests started coming in
and one resident suggested in a letter to the editor of an Aspen
newspaper that the town should ``can the glitter or move it to
Vail.''
   Aspen and Vail are rival ski spas in the Colorado Rockies.
   ``There's always been security in the mountain, white in the
winter, brown in the spring, green in the summer,'' said Bill
Drueding, a town zoning official. ``Now I look up there and see
something I've known for 15 years and it's changed.''
   ``It's surprising to me that people feel as strong as they do
about me decorating their mountain,'' said New York artist Donald
Lipski, designer of the tape display. ``My guess is that there is
some complex sociology underneath that has nothing to do with my
piece.''
   The tape was removed from the mountain secretly early Saturday
and carried to the art museum. It had been scheduled to remain on
the mountain through Sept. 25.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
