<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Rumble Through Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms rumbled across the Midwest today, bringing
much-needed rain but flooding parts of Nebraska and pelting some
areas with hail. A high pressure system kept much of the nation dry.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered from northwest
Minnesota through western parts of Nebraska into eastern Colorado
late Sunday and early today. Besides the rainfall, the storms
brought hail and gusty winds. Showers and a few thunderstorms also
hit southern Montana and northern Wyoming.
   Thunderstorms were heaviest across Nebraska, where heavy rain
caused local flooding late Sunday. Hemingford was drenched by 2
inches of rain, while part of the Nebraska Highway 92, west of
Scottsbluff, was flooded by 6 to 18 inches. More than an inch of
rain was measured at Crawford, which also was blasted by hail
one-inch in diameter.
   Meanwhile, the rest of the nation was dry as a high-pressure
system remained anchored over the central Appalachians. Dry weather
also covered parts of the West from the Pacific coast into the
inter-mountain areas.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms scattered
from the Rockies and the High Plains into the upper Mississippi
Valley; thunderstorms through Montana, Wyoming, eastern Colorado
and western South Dakota; showers and thunderstorms scattered
across the southern half of Florida; showers widely scattered
through New England; and sunny skies over the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures were forecast in the 80s and 90s across most of the
nation; in the upper 60s and 70s along the Pacific coast and the
northern and central Rockies, the northern Plains, northern Arizona
and Maine; and in the 90s to around 100 across the desert Southwest
and the Texas Rio Grande River.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 40
degrees at Lake Yellowstone, Wyo., to 82 degress at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 70 fair; Boston 77 cloudy; Buffalo 65 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 63 foggy; Cincinnati 63 fair; Cleveland 65 fair;
Detroit 67 fair; Miami 77 partly cloudy; New York 74 fair;
Philadelphia 67 fair; Pittsburgh 67 fair; Portland, Maine 73 partly
cloudy; Washington 68 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 58 partly cloudy; Chicago 72 fair;
Dallas-Fort Worth 75 fair; Denver 62 fair; Des Moines 70 fair;
Indianapolis 66 fair; Kansas City 72 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 80
fair; Nashville 69 fair; New Orleans 72 fair; St. Louis 74 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 70 fair; Anchorage 58 cloudy; Las Vegas 83
fair; Los Angeles 59 fair; Phoenix 87 fair; Salt Lake City 66
partly cloudy; San Diego 61 cloudy; San Francisco 56 fair; Seattle
57 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 73 partly cloudy; Toronto 66 fair.
</TEXT>
