<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDS-Benefit 1stLd-Writethru a0486 06-13 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Benefit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0486,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stars Pitch In For AIDS Education at Gala Benefit Concert</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to delete garble.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TONY WINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Dionne Warwick brought together her
show business friends in a benefit concert that capped a weekend of
events organizers expect to raise $1 million for AIDS education.
   The four-hour, $100-a-seat concert at the John F. Kennedy Center
for the Performing Arts Sunday night reunited Ms. Warwick, Elton
John, Stevie Wonder and Gladys Knight for a live rendition of their
hit song, ``That's What Friends Are For'' _ a plea for help in the
fight against the deadly virus.
   Frank Sinatra was to have joined the stars on stage, but son
Frank Sinatra Jr. told the audience the singer had ``taken ill''
and would not perform.
   A spokesman for The Warwick Foundation, Roy Betts, declined to
specify the nature of Sinatra's illness, but said he would not be
hospitalized. Susan Reynolds, Sinatra's publicist, said from Los
Angeles only that Sinatra was returning to California.
   Ms. Warwick, who organized weekend events that included a
special dinner and AIDS education workshops, cried as she made an
plea for more funds to educate the public about AIDS.
   ``We've got a big fight on our hands,'' she told the audience.
``And we know that with the help of people like you, we're going to
win that fight.''
   Elton John and Stevie Wonder made the longest trip for the
benefit, arriving Sunday after performing Saturday at the
FreedomFest anti-apartheid concert in London.
   ``That is what friends are for,'' Wonder said of his
cross-Atlantic journey to stand with Ms. Warwick.
   Betts said ticket sales for the concert, a sale of rights to the
concert to cable television and other proceeds should bring the
weekend's receipts to close to $1 million.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious
disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it
incapable of resisting other diseases and infections.
</TEXT>
