<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SAfrica-SharpevilleSix 4thLd-Writethru aukee3130.5088oReopenTrialofSixCondemnedBlacks
06-13 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Sharpeville Six, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0529,0802</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Bid to Reopen Trial of Six Condemned Blacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with time limit on appeal, defense
reaction, more reaction from friends and family, TRIMS. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today rejected a bid to
reopen the trial of the Sharpeville Six, and the blacks convicted
for a mob murder once again faced hanging unless President P.W.
Botha intervenes.
   The judge gave the defendants 35 days to appeal to Botha or the
chief justice.
   The president already has turned down an appeal for clemency. In
doing so, he spurned an international campaign to spare the six,
who were found guilty in the mob killing of a black town councilor.
   Pretoria Supreme Court Justice Willem Human, who presided over
the original trial in 1985, rejected an application by defense
lawyers to reopen the case to consider allegations that police
coerced two state witnesses.
   The defendants _ five men and a woman _ were convicted of
complicity in the 1984 death of black town councilor who was stoned
to death and burned during riots provoked by a rent increase.
   Human, who had granted a stay of execution hours before the six
were to hang in March, said today the request to review the case
was ``frivolous and absurd.''
   But he extended the stay of execution, which would have expired
today, until July 19, giving defense attorneys 35 days to appeal
once again to Botha and ask Acting Chief Justice P.J. Rabie to
overrule the court's decision.
   However, Human indicated he felt the chief justice would not
overturn his decision by telling the lawyers that their only
remaining hope lay in petitioning Botha again.
   Several dozen friends, relatives and diplomats crowded into the
courtroom did not react immediately to the reading of the decision,
but some broke down and wept in the corridor when attorney Prakesh
Diar explained the ruling to them. They then went to Pretoria
prison to visit the six convicts.
   Diar said, ``It's a bit surprising that he would give a time
limit'' on when the chief justice would have to make a decision.
``Our experience when you petition the chief justice (is that) it
takes many months. He's giving us a deadline for the chief justice
to make up his mind. I think I'm losing a little extra hope with
the judge's attitude.''
   Human said apart from allegations that two witnesses were
coerced, there was ample uncontested evidence to implicate all six
defendants and he would not extend the stay of execution beyond
July 19.
   Diar said he would try to appeal to the chief justice. But he
said the fate of the six was really in Botha's hands.
   ``I hope and I pray that the state president will reconsider his
previous decision. This is a politically related case. (Botha's
decision) may be based on political considerations.''
   Diar said he spoke to his clients last week and described them
as ``hopeful, but not confident.''
   Prosecutors argued during a hearing last week that Human had no
jurisdiction to reopen the case because an appeal has been rejected
by the country's highest court, the Appeals Court.
   Defense lawyers had said Human could reopen the case if he
determined the trial court was defrauded by false evidence obtained
through coercion.
   But Human said today that further questioning of a state witness
who recanted part of his incriminating testimony would be ``an
exercise in futility.''
   The six were granted a stay of execution March 17, one day
before they were to hang.
   Their case has generated controversy in part because they were
not convicted of contributing physically to the councilor's death.
They were convicted under the doctrine of common purpose, which
held them responsible because they actively participated in the mob
which killed the councilor.
   The government has contended that the six have been unfairly
portrayed abroad as innocent victims of an unjust law. Authorities
say evidence at the trial showed that each played an active part in
the killing, through such actions as making firebombs to burn the
victim's house and slapping a woman who pleaded for the councilor's
life.
   The defendants are Mojalefa Sefatsa, Reid Mokoena, Oupa Diniso,
Duma Khumalo, Francis Mokhesi and Theresa Ramashamola, the only
woman on Death Row for what activists say is a politically related
crime.
   Through the policy of apartheid, the white minority government
has established a racially segregated society and denies the
country's 26 million blacks a vote in national affairs.
   The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate
districts, schools and health services. Black officials in the
government's employ are thus often resented by other blacks.
</TEXT>
