<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Greece-US     06-13 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-US,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Suspected Of Bombing Two U.S. Jets Faces Passport Charge In
Greece</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian suspected of placing bombs
aboard two U.S. jetliners that killed five people will be tried in
Athens on charges of entering Greece on a forged passport, a
security official said today.
   The Palestinian, Mohammed Rashid, 34, has been held at Greek
security police headquarters since a tip from the U.S. Embassy led
to his arrest June 1 at Athens Airport.
   The United States is seeking Rashid's extradition for his
alleged involvement in the bombings of the U.S. jets over Hawaii in
1982 and over Greece in 1986.
   ``We understand that Rashid is to be tried for coming into
Greece with false travel documents. The question of his extradition
therefore doesn't arise at this stage,'' said the official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   According to police, Rashid entered Greece on a fake Syrian
passport. If convicted, he could receive an 18-24 month sentence
for traveling on forged documents, the security official said.
   ``Under normal practice, it would be possible for extradition
proceedings to be started after he has finished serving the prison
term,'' the security official said.
   The official said he was not aware that any date had been set
for Rashid's trial. In the crowded Athens judicial system, suspects
may be held for up to 10 months before their case is heard.
   Greece has followed similar procedures in the past when faced
with extradition requests for alleged terrorists.
   A Jordanian arrested in Greece in 1982 is still awaiting
extradition to Italy, where he is wanted for allegedly plotting an
attack against the Rome synagogue that killed a small boy.
   Rashid, believed to be an explosives expert, is suspected of
placing a sophisticated device that went off aboard a TWA jet on a
Rome-Athens flight in April 1986 as it flew over southern Greece.
Four people, including a baby, died when they were blasted out of
the aircraft.
   Rashid also allegedly placed a bomb aboard a Pan Am jumbo jet
that exploded as the plane was coming in to land at Honolulu on a
flight from Tokyo in 1982. A Japanese teen-ager was killed and 15
passengers were injured.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
