<1ST_LINE>r a PM-YoungGraduate 1stLd-Writethru a0525 06-13 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Young Graduate, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0525,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lonely 11-Year-Old College Grad Ponders Cosmic Riddles</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 4th graf, `Our system ...,' to UPDATE
with quotes from CBS program today. Picks up in 5th graf, `The
father ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After graduating from college in three
years, 11-year-old Adragon Eastwood De Mello faces a mind-boggling
choice: Should he pursue the answer to cosmic riddles? Or should he
go to junior high?
   Like most boys his age, the freckle-faced lad with a Prince
Valiant haircut would rather not go back to junior high. ``I
already know that stuff,'' he lamented Saturday as he received his
bachelor's degree in mathematics from Cowell College at the
University of California, Santa Cruz.
   But, unless Adragon is admitted to a graduate program, he will
be required by state law to go to junior high this fall. His
father, Augustin De Mello, is prepared to send his son abroad to
escape that fate.
   ``Our system is not equipped to deal with children like him,''
said the proud father, a single parent who started Adragon on a
special learning program at an early age by hanging space mobiles
over his crib.
   On CBS' ``This Morning'' program today, Adragon said, ``I'm not
sure what graduate school I'll go to.'' However, he said, going
back to junior high school ``won't do me any good.''
   The father said he introduced Adragon to sophisticated books
before he was a year old and that Adragon uttered his first
``Hello'' at 6{ weeks. ``When he was a little older than 1, he
strapped on a guitar and started singing,'' the father said.
   Adragon knew the alphabet at age 2, could read and write by 3,
and received an associate degree with highest honors from a
two-year junior college by 10, the father said. Adragon spent just
one year at the university.
   Adragon would like to continue his studies at the Santa Cruz
campus, but has not yet heard whether he's been accepted in the
graduate division for the fall.
   ``I want to start learning scientific programming next year,''
he said. ``I want to go into astrophysics or particle physics,
which hopefully will lead to the discovery of the creation of the
universe, which is what I'm interested in.''
   He says he wouldn't mind picking up a Nobel Prize along the way.
   Cowell College Provost John Lynch said he had mixed feelings
about Adragon's rapid progress. ``It's quite an achievement, and he
earned his degree. But I hope he will go on and be educated in life
as broadly as he was in math,'' said Lynch.
   Adragon's father is concerned his son made no friends at Santa
Cruz.
   ``I kept questioning myself: Was this the right way to go? It
gets harder and harder for him,'' said De Mello. ``He isolated
himself. ... His computers were his friends. It was very lonely for
him.''
   Although he's confident about his abilities to grow
intellectually, Adragon himself worries about his social life.
   ``It is strange having everyone so much higher than you,'' he
says. ``And in elementary school they have a recess. I once asked a
student at Santa Cruz where the playground was and he laughed.
   ``I finally found the playground in my computer.''
</TEXT>
