<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LostMan     06-13 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lost Man,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lost Man Identified </HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy Moses had gone by the name John
Jackson since he walked into a pizza parlor six weeks ago and said,
``Help me, I don't know who I am.''
   The amnesia victim, who spent recent weeks in a city mission,
celebrated his 33rd birthday Sunday after two friends identified
his picture in a local paper.
   He had picked the name Jackson because he believed he may have
spent some time in Jacksonville, Fla. It turns out that's where
he's from.
   ``I saw the picture in the paper and said, `That's Mo,''' said
Duffie Swartz of Columbus, Ohio. Swartz was in Huntington with her
sister, Connie Hughes of New York, when they saw the newspaper.
   Moses said he was told, after the women identified him, that
Sunday was his 33rd birthday.
   Moses knew little about himself other than he remembered being
in Jacksonville, that he was a Cleveland Indians fan and traveled
frequently.
   Moses said the women look familiar and that he probably was in
nearby Kenova, where Swartz used to live, on May 3 looking for them
when he lost his memory.
   ``I was going to see my grandmother in Cleveland,'' Moses said.
``And I stopped in Kenova and something must have happened.''
   Moses said he awoke in a field in Kenova without his wallet. He
said he believed he was either robbed or the wallet fell out
somewhere.
</TEXT>
