<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 0936EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-France-Election 2ndLd-Writethru a0524 06-13 0849</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Election, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0524,0877</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Socialists, Short of Majority, Look To Form Coalition</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 20 grafs to UPDATE with final election results
from Sunday, reax from financial markets. Pickup 19th graf pvs,
``In 1986...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market and the franc dropped today after
voters denied Socialist President Francois Mitterrand a legislative
majority and created the prospect of an unstable governing
coalition.
   The Socialists emerged from Sunday's second round of voting with
the biggest bloc of votes, but must now look to the Communists or
the centrists for a coalition partner to form a National Assembly
majority. Just a few weeks ago, the Socialists were widely expected
to gain an absolute majority.
   Also, the extreme-right National Front all but vanished from the
legislature, winning just one seat against 35 two years ago. Among
the casualties was party leader Jean-Marie Le Pen.
   Some commentators said the political landscape could remain
unsettled for weeks or even months. Such uncertainty would be
unusual in France, which has known only stable government
majorities since Charles de Gaulle founded the Fifth Republic in
1958.
   Share prices declined on the Paris Stock Exchange today in
reaction to the prospect of instability, retreating an average of
more than 2 percent. The franc fell to 3.38 against the Deutsche
mark, compared to 3.39 at Friday's closing. ``The market hates a
vaccum,'' said one trader at the Paris exchange.
   Mitterrand's premier, Michel Rocard, tried to put the best face
on the party's disappointment. ``You have chosen prudently,'' he
told voters Sunday night in a television address. ``It will take
several days to draw the appropriate conclusions of all these
choices.''
   However, others were more pessimistic.
   ``It will be the most subtle and complex situation you could
imagine,'' said political commentator Alain Duhamel.
   The Socialists could put together a majority in the 577-seat
National Assembly either by joining with the Communist Party or by
enticing some centrist members of the conservative coalition to
change sides.
   Neither path looked easy.
   It also was possible that the Socialists would set up a minority
government with Rocard or someone new as premier. They would then
try to win by seeking votes to the left or the right, depending on
the issue.
   The Communists said they would not consider forming a coalition
with the Socialists unless Mitterrand reverses his movement toward
the center and launches radical new economic policies to fight
unemployment and poverty.
   Centrist leaders said they would not abandon their conservative
allies. But they also indicated the time has come for right and
left to find a way to work together.
   Sunday's election filled 575 seats in the National Assembly; the
final two seats will be determined in French Polynesia on June 26.
   It takes 289 votes to form an absolute majority in the assembly.
   The Socialists had 276 seats.
   Just barely behind, the conservative alliance had 271. The
conservative Rally for the Republic won 126, the center-right Union
for French Democracy took 129, and smaller rightist parties
collected a total of 16.
   The Communists had 27.
   The National Front salvaged one seat. Its leaders said it fell
victim to the replacement of a proportional electoral system by a
system of majority vote in two rounds, which favors larger parties.
The first round was June 5.
   Sunday's runoffs were in the 453 districts where no candidate
won a majority the first time, and voter turnout was estimated at
71 percent.
   In 1986, the conservatives won control of the legislature and
Mitterrand was forced into an uncomfortable ``cohabitation'' with
the right.
   But following Mitterrand's solid re-election victory May 8 with
54 percent of the vote over then-Premier Jacques Chirac, it was
widely expected that the Socialists would win a handy absolute
majority in the assembly.
   But the pre-election polls proved wrong.
   Mitterrand met late Sunday night with Rocard but made no
immediate public statement. The new National Assembly is to meet
for the first time June 23.
   After Mitterrand was first elected in May 1981, he called
legislative elections and won a clear majority for his Socialists.
He named four Communists Cabinet ministers, but they later quit
when the government switched to an economic policy of austerity.
   Recently, Mitterrand said the Socialists should pursue an
``opening'' toward the center, although exactly what he means has
been the most-debated question in recent French politics.
   Georges Marchais, head of the Communist Party, said his forces
would vote for any Socialist proposals ``favorable to popular and
national interests,'' but not commit them in advance to backing the
government unless Mitterrand changes course.
   Marchais called for ``a policy of effective struggle against
unemployment, poverty and social inequality, an increase in
purchasing power, salaries, pensions and welfare payments, a policy
of new growth in the economy, a policy of freedom preserving the
rights of wage-earners and the independence of France, a policy of
peace and disarmament.''
   Mitterrand's policies by now may be closer to those of the
centrists. However, the centrists have longstanding ties to their
conservative partners that will not be broken easily.
</TEXT>
