<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Fraud     06-13 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Fraud,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Will Rule in New York Medicare Fraud Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether the government may use a 19th Century anti-fraud law to
impose stiff civil fines on top of criminal penalties assessed for
the same offense.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by Reagan administration
officials seeking to fine the manager of a New York medical
laboratory $131,170 for defrauding the government of $585 on
Medicare bills.
   The government imposed the penalty against Irwin Halper, who
runs New City Medical Laboratories.
   Halper was convicted criminally of submitting inflated claims
for Medicare reimbursement. He was sentenced to two years in prison
and fined $5,000.
   Government officials then also fined him $131,170 under the
False Claims Act, a civil statute enacted in 1863 to combat fraud
against the Union army by Civil War defense contractors.
   The civil fine was based on $2,000 for each of 65 separate
charges of overbilling plus $1,170 for double the actual loss
suffered by the government.
   The government said Halper billed Blue Cross and Blue Shield of
Greater New York at $12 per patient for a service that Medicare
reimburses at $3.
   U.S. District Judge Robert W. Sweet in New York City originally
reduced the civil fine to $17,170 and subsequently cut it to $1,170
when the government protested the first reduction.
   Sweet said the stiff fine the government wants ``amounts to a
criminal penalty for violations for which Halper has already been
punished.'' He said the original fine ``bears no rational relation
to the government's loss.''
   The judge said the civil fine violated Halper's double jeopardy
protection against being punished twice for the same offense.
   In the appeal filed today, government lawyers pointed out that
Congress in 1986 increased the fines so that offenders now may be
penalized from $5,000 to $10,000 per offense, plus triple the
actual government loss.
   ``Congress strengthened the government's civil remedies because
it determined that more severe sanctions were needed in order to
stem the tide of rampant fraud inflicted on the government,''
Justice Department lawyers said.
   Such a stiff penalty ``is reasonable and well within Congress's
legislative power,'' they said.
   The case is U.S. vs. Halper, 87-1383.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880613-0080 </DOCNO>
