<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Peru-RebelLeader     06-13 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peru-Rebel Leader,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No. 2 Leader Of Shining Path Guerrillas Captured In Peru</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have captured the No. 2 leader of the
Shining Path, a fanatical Maoist group that has waged a guerrilla
war against the government for eight years, a government minister
said today.
   Osman Morote, 42, was arrested by counterinsurgency police
Sunday at a house in downtown Lima along with two women, Deputy
Interior Minister Agustin Mantilla said. He declined to name the
women.
   Morote had fake identification papers but was identified by his
fingerprints, Mantilla said.
   The capture is considered the most important since the Shining
Path launched its guerrilla war in May 1980. Since then the
violence has claimed more than 10,000 lives and cost this
impoverished nation $5 billion in damage to its economy, according
to government figures.
   Morote, known within the rebel band as ``Comrade Remigio,'' is
second in importance only to Abimael Guzman, a former professor of
philosophy who founded the Shining Path in 1970 as a splinter group
of the Communist Party.
   The Shining Path is seeking to overthrow Peru's elected
government and install a peasant and worker state patterned after
the ideas of China's Mao Tse-tung.
   Guzman is the ideologist of the organization, but Morote is
considered the military strategist of the guerrillas and the
advocate of attacks against peasant communities in the highlands
that have formed civil defense units on the orders of the military.
   Intelligence sources said the capture is the most important
achievement so far in the government's efforts to halt the advance
of the rebel movement, which has spread from its base in the
highland state of Ayacucho through much of the country.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Morote's
capture will create a power vacuum within the central committee of
the Shining Path and cause tension until a replacement is decided
upon.
   There have been reports in recent months of a growing rivalry
between Morote and Guzman, 53, and Mantilla said he did not
discount the possibility that Guzman had betrayed Morote to get him
out of the way.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
