<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Intellectuals     06-13 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Intellectuals,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli and Palestinian Artists Sign Peace Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli and Palestinian intellectuals did today
what their political leaders have been unable to do for 40 years _
they signed a peace accord.
   The ``treaty,'' written in Hebrew, Arabic and English on
parchment-like paper, was signed by about 25 Israeli and
Palestinian writers and painters during a news conference at which
foreign reporters far outnumbered local journalists.
   The document calls for the establishment of an independent
Palestinian state _ called ``Falastin'' _ in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, which Israel captured during the 1967 Mideast war.
   The treaty recognizes the right of Israel and Falastin to live
in peace and security within their own borders. It designates
Jerusalem a demilitarized city with open borders, which would serve
as the capital of both states.
   Israeli author Yoram Kaniuk described the signing as an
``historic moment.''
   ``We hope this will have some kind of influence (on politicians)
who say there is no one to talk to and nothing to talk about,'' he
said, claiming the document represented the first treaty ever
successfully negotiated by Israelis and Palestinians.
   Kaniuk is one of the leaders of the Israeli and Palestinian
Writers, Artists and Academics Committee Against Occupation, the
only professional group that represents both Israelis and
Palestinians from the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The group includes left-wing Israeli artists, among them poet
Nathan Zach.
   He recently canceled an international poetry festival to protest
allegedly harsh measures by the army to quell the 6-month-old
Palestinian uprising in which 207 Palestinians have been killed and
about 5,000 injured. Two Israelis also have been killed.
   Asad El Asad, head of the Palestinian Writers' Association in
the occupied territories, said the Palestine Liberation
Organization favors the terms of the artists' treaty.
   ``We feel we are transmitting clearly and honestly the message
of our represenatives, the PLO,'' said El Asad.
   Israel, which is celebrating its 40th anniversary, refuses to
recognize the PLO, saying it is a terrorist organization. The PLO,
which has called for the destruction of Israel, has also refused to
accept U.N. resolutions recognizing Israel's right to secure its
borders.
   Kaniuk said that Israeli and Palestinian ``negotiators'' often
disagreed about the terms of the treaty and each side eventually
had to ``give up dreams and accept reality.''
   Zach said he would now extend his appeal beyond the circle of
the committee and ask all like-minded artists, writers and
academics in Israel and the occupied territories to sign the treaty.
   ``If clods like us, who are not always very good at taking
action, can do it, so can politicians,'' said Zach. ``If they
don't, it's because they don't want to or are afraid to.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
