<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-DuPont-LaRouche     06-13 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-DuPont-LaRouche,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Incompetancy Ruling Left Intact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected the appeal of
a DuPont family fortune heir declared mentally incompetent after he
lent $212,000 to a group linked to political extremist Lyndon
LaRouche.
   The court, without comment, let stand rulings that control of
Lewis duPont Smith's $8 million estate properly was taken from him
in 1985 under Pennsylvania's guardianship law.
   Smith's appeal contended that his freedom of political
expression and association had been violated.
   Smith, 31, lives in Chester County, Pa. He is the son of E.
Newbold and Margaret duPont Smith, and is heir to a significant
portion of the family fortune.
   In 1985, Smith had access to about $1.5 million in assets and
marketable securities. He also received substantial income from
trusts.
   Smith lent $212,000 in early 1985 to Caucus Distributions Inc.,
an affiliate of LaRouche's organization.
   Learning of his intention to lend an additional $75,000 to
Caucus Distributions, Smith's family on April 11, 1985, asked a
judge to appoint a financial guardian for him.
   After several hearings, the judge ruled that Lewis was
incompetent within the meaning of Pennsylvania's guardianship law
because he was ``liable to dissipate his assets and become the
victim of designing persons.''
   The judge appointed the Wilmington Trust Co., a financial
institution, as guardian of Smith's estate.
   Smith's free-speech challenge to finding him incompetent because
he contributed to LaRouche's political efforts was rejected by the
judge. ``It is not that kind of case ... Lewis' First Amendment
freedoms remain intact, and he may exercise them as foolishly as he
wishes,'' the judge said.
   His ruling was upheld by a state appeals court. ``We agree ...
that (Smith's) mental illness has resulted in producing a condition
that has made him a victim of the LaRouche organization,'' the
appeals court said.
   The Pennsylvania Supreme Court refused to hear Smith's appeal
last Jan. 21.
   The case is Smith vs. Smith, 87-1753.
</TEXT>
