<HEAD>Azerbaijani Policeman Killed by Armenian</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to ADD quote from Gerasmiov about police
who was shot and rumors of Armenian deaths. Pickup 3rd graf pvs,
``The policeman...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman said today a
policeman in the Azerbaijani capital of Baku was killed by a
shotgun blast fired by an Armenian during an ethnic protest.
   Gennady I. Gerasimov, the Foreign Ministry spokesman, also told
a news briefing that rumors saying two Armenians had been killed in
Baku led to a protest march in Moscow on Sunday. He said a general
strike had been called in Yerevan, the Armenian capital, to demand
the disputed Nagorno-Karabakh region be turned over to Armenia.
   ``We have received the information from Baku that the
information about the murder of two Armenians is false,'' Gerasimov
said. ``In fact, there was a shooting in Baku from a shotgun ...
and the bullet killed a militia sergeant.''
   The policeman, identified as a Sgt. Izmailov, was killed by a
shot fired by an Armenian with the last name of Aganbegyan,
Gerasimov said. Izmailov was born in 1951 and Aganbegyan in 1932,
the spokesman said. He provided no other information about the men.
   ``The bullet was deflected from some kind of surface,''
Gerasimov said. Police had not yet determined whether the killing
was premediated, he said.
   The shooting occurred ``during a demonstration for retaining the
Nagorno-Karabakh region in Azerbaijan,'' he said. He did not say
when the policeman was killed.
   Armenians gathered in a Moscow cemetery on Sunday and marched to
the offices of the official Tass news agency because of rumors that
two Armenians had been killed in Azerbaijan. He said the rumor was
false.
   Gerasimov also said that Armenians gathered in the central
square of Yerevan on Sunday and called a general strike until
Wednesday, when the Presidium of the Armenian Supreme Soviet is to
meet. Armenians are demanding that the republic's nominal
legislature go on record in support of annexing the
Nagorno-Karabakh region.
   He said a sit-in, meetings and demonstrations were continuing in
Yerevan.
   Nagorno-Karabakh is part of Azerbaijan, a Soviet republic
located south of the Caucasus Mountains and next to the Caspian
Sea, that is dominated by ethnic Armenians.
   They began demonstrating in mid-February to press their demand
to be annexed to neighboring Armenia.
   In February, violence erupted in Sumgait, a city in Azerbaijan.
The government says 32 people, 26 Armenians and six Azerbaijanis,
were killed.
   The government several weeks later turned down the demand to
allow Armenia to annex Nagorno-Karabakh and ethnic unrest has
continued since then.
   In May the Communist Party leaders of both Armenia and
Azerbaijan were replaced on the same day, an indication of Moscow's
displeasure with their inability to cope with the unrest.
</TEXT>
