<HEAD>Court Refuses To Reinstate Cocaine Conviction In Texas Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to reinstate
rock star David Crosby's cocaine conviction and five-year prison
sentence, overturned by a Texas court only after Crosby spent five
months in prison.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that Dallas
police unlawfully searched Crosby's nightclub dressing room.
   A state appeals court ruled that evidence gathered by police in
the unlawful 1982 search _ including cocaine and a pistol
confiscated from Crosby _ should not have been used as evidence at
Crosby's trial.
   Crosby, who gained fame as part of the group called Crosby,
Stills and Nash, was convicted of unlawfully possessing cocaine and
carrying a handgun in a tavern.
   A state appeals court overturned the conviction and prison
sentence last Nov. 12. Crosby was freed after having served five
months of the sentence.
   In the appeal acted on today, Dallas County prosecutors argued
that the state court wrongly found that Crosby enjoyed a
``reasonable expectation of privacy'' in the dressing room of a
``closely regulated, state-licensed, liquor-selling establishment.''
   The case is Texas vs. Crosby, 87-1640.
