<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Soviets     06-13 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Soviets,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Claim Property In Jerusalem, Expected To Demand Rent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union claims it owns a government
building and a downtown parking lot in Jerusalem and is expected to
demand several million dollars in back rent, Israeli officials and
media said today.
   The Soviets also are expected to claim other property in
Jerusalem, most of it believed acquired decades ago through the
Russian Orthodox Church.
   Israeli government officials declined to comment on specific
Soviet claims, but Jerusalem city spokeswoman Sivana Meryn said the
city acknowledged a paved parking lot on King George Street in
downtown Jerusalem was built on Soviet property. She said Israel
would be willing to negotiate rental payments.
   The Soviet Union says the building which currently houses the
Agriculture Ministry also belongs to the Soviets.
   Israeli officials said they were ready to discuss the claims but
hoped the talks would be friendly and would not disrupt a movement
toward improved ties between the Soviet Union and Israel.
   The Soviet Union severed ties with Israel to protest the Israeli
capture of lands from Egypt, Jordan and Syria in the 1967 war.
   Last July, for the first time since then, Moscow sent a consular
delegation to Israel to examine property holdings and speak to the
estimated 2,500 Soviet passport holders in Israel.
   Israel in return has asked that it be allowed to send a
delegation to Moscow, and Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said last
week that Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze told him
the Israeli delegation would receive Soviet visas next month.
   On Sunday, the head of the Soviet delegation, Georgi Martirosow,
informed the Israeli Foreign Ministry that the delegates had
completed a survey of property owned by the Soviet Union and
currently being used by Israel.
   Martirosow recently returned from Moscow where he spent several
weeks combing Soviet archives for deeds and other documents showing
Soviet property holdings in Israel, a Foreign Ministry official
said.
   The Soviet delegates are expected to present a detailed list of
their holdings along with demands for rental payments in the next
several weeks, the official said, requesting anonymity.
   A spokesman who answered the telephone at the Soviet
delegation's office declined comment.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev said two weeks ago that the
Soviet Union would be willing to renew ties with Israel once all
parties in the Middle East conflict agreed to participate in an
international peace conference.
   Shamir, however, has rejected Israeli participation in such a
conference.
</TEXT>
