<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Monet     06-13 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Monet,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Turns Aside German Woman's Effort To Recover Stolen Painting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German woman's effort to recover the
Claude Monet painting stolen from her sister's home during World
War II ended unsuccessfully in the Supreme Court today.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that Gerda
Deweerth waited too long before trying to recover the painting from
Edith Marks Baldinger, who bought it in New York City in 1957.
   The painting, Monet's ``Champs de Ble a Vetheuil,'' is one of a
series of impressionist landscapes painted near the town of
Vetheuil in Northern France.
   The oil painting shows a wheat field, a village and trees. It is
signed and dated ``Claude Monet '79.''
   Monet is one of the best known members of the school of
impressionistic artists active in France in the late 19th and early
20th centuries. It was from his early work, ``Impression: Sunrise,
La Havre,'' that the term impressionism was coined.
   The painting at issue is valued at more than $500,000, according
to the appeals court that ruled against Ms. Deweerth.
   She inherited the painting in 1922, and kept it in her home at
Wuppertal-Elberfeld, West Germany. In 1943, Ms. DeWeerth sent the
painting to her sister's home in southern Germany for safekeeping
during the war.
   When American troops quartered in the house departed in 1945,
the painting disappeared. Lower courts assumed it was stolen.
   Ms. Baldinger was a good-faith purchaser of the Monet 12 years
later.
   U.S. District Judge Vincent Broderick in New York ruled that the
painting must be returned to Ms. DeWeerth, but the 2nd U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals reversed his ruling.
   The appeals court said Ms. DeWeerth ``failed to exercise
reasonable diligence in locating the painting after its
disappearance'' and therefore had waited too long, under New York
law, before suing its current owner.
   The case is DeWeerth vs. Baldinger, 87-1752.
</TEXT>
