<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Beauties, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0552,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winner Of Moscow Beauty Pageant Rushes Back To School For Final
Exams</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS38</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with reax from winner, her
taking exams today, program watched on TV by millions. Pickup 4th
graf, ``Ms. Kalinina...''
^By BRYAN BRUMLEY</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old student who praised Mikhail
Gorbachev's reform movement won Moscow's first beauty pageant and
walked away with a wealth of prizes that drew a gasp of amazement
from the audience.
   ``I felt exactly like Alice in Wonderland,'' Maria Kalinina said
Sunday after her warm smile and svelte figure won over the 12
judges, who chose her from six finalists in a contest that
emphasized bathing suit competition.
   Photographers were waiting for her as she arrived at school
today and hurried to a second-floor classroom to take the
equivalent of her high school final examinations.
   Izvestia, an afternoon paper, reported with almost unbelieveable
speed for the normally slow Soviet press that Ms. Kalinina received
the highest mark in her Spanish test and top grades in literature
and math exams as well.
   Like the other finalists, Ms. Kalinina is very thin, in contrast
to the common perception in the West that Soviet women are stout.
   The ``Moscow Beauty '88'' contest, made possible by Gorbachev's
more tolerant policies, was the first of its kind in the Soviet
capital. Millions of Soviets watched a live television broadcast of
the pageant.
   Although similar pageants have been staged in several other
Soviet cities, such contests are still a new phenomenon in a
socialist society which long disdained them as bourgeois. It was
not clear yet whether the new beauty queen would compete in
nationwide or international pageants.
   Ms. Kalinina was the youngest contestant in a field of 36 that
included an accountant, two librarians and two actresses. The
oldest was Yelena Baranova, 26, a doctor who did not reach the
final round Sunday night.
   During the question-and-answer competition, practically the only
event in which the finalists wore more than a tiny scrap of
clothing, Ms. Kalinina was asked what made the Moscow contest
different from beauty pageants in the West.
   ``Ours is different because we have `perestroika,''' she
replied, using the Russian word for Gorbachev's policy of economic
and social reforms.
   The third and final night of what was gala event by normally
austere Soviet went smoothly until the glittering crown was placed
on Ms. Kalinina's head.
   At that moment, long-stemmed red roses began to rain from the
ceiling, knocking off the crown and causing the beauty queen to
duck and dodge, although she never lost her smile. The next shower
of roses was aimed a little in front of the beauty queen, and did
not disrupt the ceremonies.
   As the master of ceremonies read out the list of prizes for Ms.
Kalinina, the crowd of 11,000 in the Palace of Sport sighed in
amazement. The prizes included: a cruise on the Adriatic Sea, a
trip to Austria, a television and mounds of cosmetics from the
Western and Soviet sponsors of the event.
   The other finalists, and some of the other contestants, received
cosmetics and trips inside the Soviet Union for categories such as
the ``most photogenic'' and ``most athletic.''
   Trips abroad are rare for Soviet citizens, and Western cosmetics
of the types distributed to the finalists are highly prized in this
country.
   Some of the loudest applause of the evening went to writer
Mikhail Zadurnov, who performed comedy routines satirizing consumer
shortages and the bureaucrats that are blocking Soviet reforms.
   At the end of an evening dominated by rock music by Soviet
bands, Zadurnov said: ``And we Muscovites would like to thank
Ronald Reagan,'' alluding to the facelift Moscow received for the
recent superpower summit.
   The parting line brought gasps of surprise from the crowd, then
thunderous laughter and applause.
</TEXT>
