<HEAD>Bush Getting Plenty of Veep Advice</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 6 grafs with Bush comment on vice presidential selection;
picks up 3rd graf pvs, bgng, ``I think...; editing thruout to
tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush said today he has ``no long list,
no short list'' for the vice presidential spot on the Republican
ticket, adding that he has only now started to consider a process
to choose a running mate.
   Bush, who clinched the presidential nomination two months ago,
told reporters that he and his aides are ``getting a little
procedure worked out'' for winnowing the field of prospects for the
No. 2 spot on the ticket.
   ``I've enjoyed all the fabulous speculation,'' about whom he
might select, the vice president told reporters called to his
office in the Old Executive Office Building.
   Bush announced the hiring of two new top-level campaign aides to
deal with the press. Sheila Tate, who was spokeswoman to first lady
Nancy Reagan from 1981-85, was named press secretary, and Jim Lake,
who held previous press roles in the 1980 and 1984 Reagan-Bush
campaigns, was named as a senior communications adviser.
   Pressed to say how close he was to picking a vice presidential
running mate, Bush said, ``No list. ... We're getting a little
procedure worked out. So there literally is no long list, no short
list.''
   Bush reiterated that he will not seriously consider the question
until after the Democrats put together their ticket in Atlanta next
month. Meanwhile, he continues to get advice from party activists.
   ``I think we need an exciting vice presidential candidate,''
said Gov. Garrey Carruthers of New Mexico. ``We need someone,
certainly, who is a good communicator, like Ronald Reagan.''
   ``I recommended to Bush that he choose Elizabeth Dole,''
Carruthers said in an interview.
   He wasn't alone in offering advice to Bush and the vice
president's aides. It's apparent the suggestion box at the Bush
campaign is packed.
   Bush and his aides have been reluctant to talk about what
selection process they'll use, how long a Bush short-list of
candidates might be, or when the choice will be made known.
   But the jockeying to have an impact on this decision was evident
at the ``Unity '88'' weekend conference put on by the Republican
National Committee.
   Former Secretary of State Alexander M. Haig Jr., who joined Sen.
Bob Dole, R-Kan., Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., and former Delaware Gov.
Pete du Pont in saluting Bush, joked about the speculation the
also-rans in the GOP competition came to Denver to protect their
prospects for the spot on the ticket.
   Haig said that since he had run for president, and been defeated
by Bush, he had no interest in seeking the second spot. ``I'm
content,'' he said.
   The list of names has lengthened in recent weeks, including
speculation about potential women candidates such as Mrs. Dole,
former U.N. ambassador Jeane Kirkpatrick and Sen. Nancy Kassebaum
of Kansas, along with Senator Dole, Kemp, du Pont. Plus Govs. Jim
Thompson of Illinois, George Deukmejian of California and John
Sununu of New Hampshire.
   ``I would like to see somebody that would be just a little bit
more conservative (than Bush), just to satisfy the right wing of
the party,'' said Bill Hughes, a Bush campaign chairman from
Vancouver, Wash.
   Joy Wood of Denver, who is trying to unseat Rep. Patricia
Schroeder, D-Colo., said ``I'm pushing for a very experienced
person. I think the Republican Party has very qualified women at
the top. But I, as a woman, want the strongest vice presidential
candidate.''
   ``I suspect it will be a man, but I just hope it will be a very
qualified person,'' she said.
   Barbara Campbell, state Republican Party chairwoman in Montana,
said ``I think it's a possibility'' that Bush will select a woman.
   But she also said that ``I have stated that it's important to
look to someone who understands the West.''
   Punch Green, Bush's campaign chairman in Oregon, said, ``I want
him to pick a guy or a gal who will be a vice president just like
George Bush has been for Ronald Reagan _ a person who will disagree
with him at times in the Oval Office, but then stand by the
president when he makes the decision.''
   Carruthers, however, said he hoped Bush wouldn't make the choice
based mostly on the basis of perceived loyalty.
   ``Loyalty is one condition, but I would hope that it would not
be the first-order condition,'' he said.
   ``What I would concern myself with most is the selection of a
winner,'' Carruthers said.
</TEXT>
