<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Refugees     06-13 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Refugees,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Will Aid Afghan Refugees: Reagan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan assured a top U.N. official
today that the United States intends to ``contribute
significantly'' to the international relief effort aiding Afghan
refugees, the White House reported.
   Reagan discussed the matter with Sadruddin Aga Khan, who is the
U.N. coordinator for humanitarian and economic assistance,
presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said.
   The official, who is from Pakistan, asked the president for
assistance in helping the 5 million refugees to return to their
homeland, Fitzwater said. The refugees fled to neighboring Pakistan
following the Soviet incursion into Afghanistan in 1979.
   ``The president urged other countries to also contribute,
including the Soviet Union,'' Fitzwater said.
   Reagan assured the official ``that the U.S. will continue to
contribute significantly in assisting the Afghans adversely
affected by the war and would support strongly his efforts to
mobilize the international community to respond to the
repatriation, resettlement and subsequent reconstruction needs of
the Afghan people,'' the spokesman added.
   Fitzwater, who said the United States has budgeted $119 million
to aid the refugees, called America ``the leading country in terms
of assistance at this point.''
</TEXT>
