<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Restrictions     06-13 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Restrictions,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Limits on ANC Leader And Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   African National Congress
leader Govan Mbeki, freed from a life prison term last year, has
been banned from being in the company of more than 10 people at a
time, his attorney said Monday.
   The government order against Mbeki, 77, will keep him from
attending any large rallies or meetings supported by the ANC, the
main guerrilla group fighting the South African government.
   Mbeki had already been prohibited from addressing meetings,
giving interviews or leaving the area near the city of Port
Elizabeth, where he lives. The new order limiting the number of
people he can be with is a common measure used by the government to
censure anti-apartheid activists.
   Mbeki's attorney, Priscilla Jana, said another of her clients,
United Democratic Front co-president Albertina Sisulu, was served
with similar new orders.
   Mrs. Sisulu, wife of imprisoned ANC official Walter Sisulu, was
one of 18 black activists whose movements and speech had already
been restricted in February.
   Also in February, the UDF, a coalition of anti-apartheid groups,
was banned from all activity, along with 17 other anti-apartheid
organizations.
   Mrs. Jana said Mbeki filed a court challenge to the first
restrictions placed on him but will have to refile the appeal under
the new regulations.
   Mbeki was freed last August after serving 23 years for a 1964
conviction on charges of sabotage.
   Under South African apartheid, the nation's 26 million blacks
have no voice in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the
economy and maintain separate schools, districts and health
services.
</TEXT>
