<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Presbyterians 1stLd-Writethru a0499 06-13 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presbyterians, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0499,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0626 to fix location of editors note</HEAD>
<HEAD>Presbyterians Consider Nuclear Arms Statement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with subcommittee agreeing to
adopt policy statement on nuclear war. Picks up 8th graf: ``We
Presbyterians ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A subcommittee of the nation's largest
Presbyterian body today voted overwhelmingly to recommend adoption
of a major policy statement on nuclear war.
   The revised paper on ``Christian Obedience in a Nuclear Age''
was scheduled to be considered later today by a full committee of
the 200th General Assembly of the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.)
   The subcommittee of the Committee on Peacemaking and
International Relations ended almost four days of at-times
contentious debate with a 15-1 vote to recommend adoption of the
statement.
   The subcommittee revised the original proposal to make it clear
Presbyterians considered obedience to government the normal course,
and to soften language that now declares nuclear deterrence
immoral. The subcommittee adopted a writing team's fine-tuning of
the policy to agree with earlier changes in recommendations.
   Meanwhile, the full assembly today took up some internal issues,
including commissioning of missionaries.
   Other issues remaining for discussion by the denomination's
highest body include pornography, abortion and Israel's treatment
of Palestinians in its occupied territories.
   On Sunday, the statement on nuclear war was revised to say a
Christian ``normally'' should support the government, and nuclear
deterrence is immoral ``as an end in itself.'' The 630 delegates
are scheduled to take up the report Tuesday evening, the day before
the assembly ends.
   ``We Presbyterians will study this issue to death, while the
rest of the world moves on,'' said subcommittee member J. Leslie
Reindl, an elder from Minnesota.
   Sue Anderson, an elder from Tennessee, however, said the paper,
and the five-year process that preceded its writing, had led to
much debate in the 3 million-member denomination.
   If the intent is to make peace, especially within the
denomination, Ms. Anderson said, ``then let the people sitting
beside me in the pew have a chance to look at this.''
   Reservations in the subcommittee centered around fears the paper
elevated tax resistance and civil obedience above obedience in the
church's eyes and promised financial support to those who engage in
resistance.
   However, the revised paper retains declarations that nuclear war
is immoral, and says, ``The policy of nuclear deterrence has been
in danger of becoming an end in itself rather than an interim
measure of self-defense. Such a policy as an end in itself is not
morally defensible. The work for peaceful alternatives needs to be
vigorously pursued.''
   Supporters of the original paper expected the full committee to
restore some of the recommendations, including discussions of
corporate support, financial and otherwise, for tax resisters.
   Other issues awaiting assembly action included a recommendation
that the church call for Israel to end its ``repressive''
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip and that the church ask
the U.S. government to stop aid to Israel that subsidizes
settlements in the occupied territories.
   Also Tuesday, commissioners face what is expected to be a hotly
contested election for stated clerk, the officer responsible for
the operation of the assembly.
   The Rev. James E. Andrews, 60, has been stated clerk or interim
co-stated clerk of the denomination since it was formed in 1983 by
the reunion of the Northern and Southern branches of the
Presbyterian church. Previously, he held the office in the
Presbyterian Church (U.S), the Southern church, for 10 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
