<DOCNO> AP880613-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1334EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Nunn-Veep     06-13 0961</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nunn-Veep,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nunn Cautious on Democrat's No. 2 Spot; Party Leaders Mixed on
Candidacy</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: One of a series of occasional stories about vice presidential
prospects.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Sam Nunn overcame his reluctance to talk
about the possibility of being Michael Dukakis' running mate, the
Georgia senator gave the interview to a newspaper he is sure the
Massaschusetts governor reads every day _ The Boston Globe.
   Frequently mentioned in speculation about the Democratic vice
presidential nomination, the chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee has been cautious in indicating his interest _ but he is
interested.
   His response to the question of whether he would even accept the
offer is delicately phrased: ``I probably would not accept,'' he
told the Globe.
   Nunn earns a spot among possible nominees because some judge him
the perfect balance on a ticket with Dukakis:
   _ A conservative Southerner with the liberal Northeasterner.
   _ An expert on defense with an expert on domestic policy.
   _ A senator with a governor.
   ``The best in Louisiana would be Nunn,'' said state party
chairman Jim Brady. ``He's strong on national defense ... and he's
perceived to be very intelligent.''
   Because of Nunn's expertise in defense and foreign policy,
former Virginia Gov. Charles Robb and others have even talked of
Nunn being vice president and secretary of defense, an
unprecedented double role in U.S. government.
   ``That would be the only reason that he would want to give up
the chairmanship, a major substantive role ... to basically sit
around an inquire into the health of both his own president and
leaders of other countries,'' Robb said.
   Nunn carefully encourages that by contrasting his clout in the
Senate with the vice president's role: ``You have tremendous
potential power, but you don't have power ... Unless you had some
unusual understanding as to what you're going to be _ which I don't
think would be easy to work out for me or anyone else _ I think
there's just a very definite problem there.''
   But there is a long list of reasons cited by critics that Nunn
should not be on the ticket. In general, positions he has taken
have caused consternation among various Democratic groups.
   Civil rights is at the top of the list, and has become a
particularly thorny matter with Democratic runner-up Jesse Jackson
pressuring Dukakis on the issue every day.
   ``Sam Nunn represents the Old South,'' said Patricia Ireland, a
vice president of the National Organization for Women from Florida.
   Nunn voted in 1975 against bringing up the legislation to renew
the Voting Rights Act. When the law was up again for a vote in
1982, Nunn voted for amendments that critics said would weaken the
legal protections. In 1980, he voted to continue a filibuster that
killed new federal powers to fight housing discrimination.
   He voted against an extension of time to ratify the Equal Rights
Amendment. He supported a constitutional amendment that would
overturn the Supreme Court decision legalizing abortion and leave
the matter up to each state.
   Such criticism irritates Nunn.
   ``I don't enjoy it. I don't like it. I don't want my children to
read 10, 15, 20 years from now that Sam Nunn was against civil
rights. That's just absolutely false,'' he told the newspaper.
   Nunn's aides say that each of his votes was on the specific
matter at hand, and often dealt with procedural considerations.
   For example, aides said Nunn voted against the ERA extension
because it would not allow states to withdraw a previous
ratification vote. On the fair housing bill, Nunn argued he didn't
want the federal government being both judge and jury on alleged
violators.
   Whether or not Jackson would object to Nunn on the ticket is not
known, but his aides quickly started boosting Ohio Sen. John Glenn
as an alternative choice when Nunn's name was first mentioned.
   Nunn also has a long record of support for many of President
Reagan's policies. Congressional Quarterly, an independent
magazine, ranked Nunn as the most frequent supporter of the
president among Senate Democrats in 1983 and 1985, never dipping
below a 58 percent level in votes on Reagan issues.
   ``He's too conservative for me,'' said Colorado Democratic Party
Executive Director Sigrid Freese of Nunn. ``He's more Republican
than Democrat.''
   And there are a series of specific issues on which Nunn and
Dukakis disagree.
   Nunn voted for aid to the Contra rebels in Nicaragua, while
Dukakis says that policy is illegal. Nunn voted for the MX missile,
which Dukakis opposes. He voted for a balanced budget amendment and
the Gramm-Rudman law requiring automatic spending cuts in 1985.
   In 1986, the liberal Americans for Democratic Action gave Nunn a
30 percent rating, while their counterpart, the American
Conservative union gave him a 55 percent mark.
   A thoughtful and careful politician, Nunn has sometimes been
called dull, a word applied to Dukakis as well. Nunn has little use
for such criticism.
   ``It would bother me if I felt audiences I spoke to felt that
... I never had that impression,'' Nunn told the newspaper. ``I
could become very controversial by just saying a lot of stupid
things and the media would say, `Where did you get all that
charisma?' But then, in two years I wouldn't be back up here.''
   There is also the question of just what Nunn could bring the
Democrats in the South. One poll in Florida suggested adding Nunn
to the ticket was worth only one precentage point of the vote in
the fall.
   A Charlotte Observer poll in North and South Carolina found a
Dukakis-Jackson ticket trailing a George Bush-Bob Dole GOP team by
five percentage points. But a Dukakis-Nunn ticket trailed by 13
points.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
