<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Extradite     06-13 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Extradite,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Belgian Extradicted to California Also Held Liable to Lawsuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People extradited from foreign countries to
face criminal charges here cannot avoid defending themselves
against related civil lawsuits filed in U.S. courts, the Supreme
Court ruled today.
   The justices ruled unanimously against Wilfried van
Cauwenberghe, a Belgian citizen who is trying to avoid having to
defend himself against a $19 million lawsuit in California.
   The court said Van Cauwenberghe has no right to appeal, before
any trial is held, the authority of a Los Angeles-based federal
court to preside over the lawsuit.
   Van Cauwenberghe was sued by another Belgian, Roger Biard, who
lent $1 million to a California real estate partnership engaged in
renovating a Kansas City townhouse complex.
   According to court papers, Biard was repaid $800,000 of the loan
and accused Van Cauwenberghe of fraud.
   Van Cauwenberge also was convicted in federal court in
California of wire fraud and related charges. He was sentenced to
time already served in pretrial confinement and was ordered to pay
Biard $34,501 in restitution.
   Van Cauwenberghe had been arrested while on a trip to
Switzerland and was extradited to Los Angeles.
   In seeking to have Biard's civil lawsuit dismissed, Van
Cauwenberghe argued that the Belgian courts are a more convenient
forum for the civil case, and also that extradited individuals are
immune from such suits.
   A federal judge refused to dismiss the suit and the 9th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals said it was premature for it to hear Van
Cauwenberghe's appeal.
   The Supreme Court today agreed that any such appeal by Van
Cauwenberghe can wait until after the trial is completed.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall, writing for the court, said Van
Cauwenberghe's freedom is not at stake in the case.
   Van Cauwenberghe cannot be imprisoned or required to post bail
in a civil suit and, in fact, is not even required to be present at
the civil trial.
   Van Cauwenberghe's right to challenge the outcome of the lawsuit
can be vindicated after there is a judgment in the suit, Marshall
said.
   The case is Van Cauwenberghe vs. Biard, 87-336.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
