<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Obit-Drozak     06-13 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Drozak,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seafarers Union President Frank Drozak Dead of Brain Cancer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Drozak, president of the 80,000-member
Seafarers International Union since 1980 and a vice president of
the AFL-CIO, died at his home from brain cancer, labor officials
said Monday.
   Drozak, 60, who had been hospitalized several times in the past
18 months for cancer treatments, died Saturday.
   Despite his illness, he had remained active in the union. Just
last fall, he had lobbied extensively for legislation that would
have required 11 Kuwati tankers operating under the U.S. flag in
the Persian Gulf to be manned by American crewmen.
   Congress passed the measure. But the Reagan administration,
citing national security interests, used an exemption in it to
allow the reflagged tankers to be staffed mostly with Filipino
crews who are paid about one-fourth the $30,000 to $35,000 annual
wage of U.S. seamen.
   Drozak assumed the leadership of the Seafarers Union at a time
when its membership was suffering large layoffs due to an
overcapacity of ship bottoms in the world, new technologies that
reduced the size of crews needed on each vessel and a large decline
in the size of the U.S. merchant marine fleet.
   Of the union's 14,000 active deep sea seamen, only about 7,000
hold active jobs now, according to union officials.
   Beginning as a shipyard worker at the age of 16 in Mobile, Ala.,
Drozak worked his way up the union's heirarchy in the 1950s and
1960s, first as an organizer in Mobile and then as a port agent in
Philadelphia and San Francisco.
   He was elected a vice president of the union in 1965 and was put
in charge of its contracts covering the Atlantic and Gulf coasts,
Great Lakes and inland waterways in 1972.
   In 1980, Drozak was elected to succeed Paul Hall as the
Seafarers' president and also as head of the 44-union AFL-CIO
Maritime Trades Department.
   A year later, he was named an AFL-CIO vice president and to one
of the 35 seats on the labor federation's policymaking executive
council.
   Drozak is survived by his wife, Marianne; a daughter; a sister;
a brother; and three grandchildren.
   Funeral services will be held Thursday at the Seafarers' School
of Seamanship at Piney Point, Md.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
