<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SwaggartInvestigation     06-13 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Swaggart Investigation,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DA Reopens Murder Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WACO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors have reopened their investigation
into the murder of a 70-year-old woman who left most of her estate
to the ministry of Louisiana television evangelist Jimmy Swaggart.
   McLennan County District Attorney Vic Feazell said Sunday that
his office renewed the investigation because of a reporter's new
information that could help him resolve what he called ``unanswered
questions'' about the December 1983 slaying.
   The inquiry into the murder of Ida Lee Baugh was not targeted at
Swaggart but could involve ``one or more individuals connected with
the Jimmy Swaggart Ministries at that time,'' said Feazell.
   Ms. Baugh was found stabbed and beaten with a wheelchair
footstool and died later at a Waco hospital. Her husband, Maurice
Patrick Baugh, died of heart failure five days after her death.
   The couple, in their will, left all but 25 percent of their cash
only, not to exceed $25,000, to the Baton Rouge, La., television
minister.
   A Swaggart spokesman estimated the estate's size at between
$500,000 and $800,000.
   In April 1984, Jacqueline Euna Warren was convicted of murder in
the case and sentenced to 99 years in prison.
   Baugh's son contested the will, charging that associates of
Jimmy Swaggart ministries exercised ``undue influence'' on his
parents to change their will. Larry Neale Baugh said two men
working on behalf of Swaggart Ministries had recommended Ms. Warren
to take care of Mrs. Baugh.
   Larry Baugh later dropped his charges. A source familiar with
the case told the Waco Tribune-Herald a settlement was reached
between Baugh and Jimmy Swaggart Ministries.
   A reporter for the National Enquirer approached Feazell with new
information he had developed independently, said the prosecutor,
adding that parts of it ``have been substantiated.''
</TEXT>
