<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mayor'sHusband     06-13 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mayor's Husband,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Husband Of Tampa's Anti-Drug Mayor Defends Work For Convicted
Smuggler</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The husband of this city's anti-drug
crusading mayor says there is nothing wrong with his handling
real-estate affairs for a convicted drug smuggler.
   Attorney Michael J. Freedman, husband of Mayor Sandy Freedman,
set up a corporation for convicted smuggler Kenneth M. Kiken in
1985 and served as the corporation's registered agent.
   Kiken, who was twice convicted on federal marijuana imporation
charges in 1974, is awaiting trial in U.S. District Court on new
drug charges in the attempted importation of 165,000 pounds of
marijuana in 1985.
   Freedman's former law partner, Arnold D. Levine, represented
Kiken after his 1974 convictions. Since then, Levine has been a
trustee for property Kiken owned in nearby Odessa, has arranged a
loan for Kiken and later handled the sale of the property, the St.
Petersburg Times reported Sunday.
   Freedman, a corporate and real estate lawyer, prepared financial
and legal documents that named Levine the trustee for the Odessa
property, and prepared the papers for the sale of the property.
   Both Levine and Freedman say they knew of Kiken's 1974
convictions, but said they were unaware of any activities alleged
in the latest indictment. Both defended their roles in helping
Kiken manage his business affairs.
   ``I don't see anything wrong with it,'' Freedman said in a
telephone interview Friday from Bermuda, where he and the mayor are
vacationing. ``Just as I have no hesitation in saying to you that
someone accused of criminal conduct is entitled to representation,
if an individual wants to buy a piece of property or set up a
corporation, I've never felt it appropriate to inquire whether it
was going to be for a legitimate purpose or if that person had some
ulterior motive.''
   Said Levine, ``It looked like the guy had turned legitimate and
was successful in that regard and there was no reason to question
it.''
   Mrs. Freedman, who has been mayor since July 1986, has made a
war against drugs one of the hallmarks of her administration. Last
month she announced ``Operation Crackdown,'' the bulldozing and
burning of 50 rundown buildings that attracted crack dealers.
   Mrs. Freedman said her husband would never knowingly represent a
drug smuggler in business transactions.
   ``My husband's integrity, his ability to tell right from wrong,
certainly makes me very confident that he's going to do the right
thing in every circumstance,'' she said from Bermuda on Friday.
   Kiken was arrested March 30. A federal indictment accuses him of
conspiracy and aiding and abetting the attempted importation of
165,000 pounds of marijuana aboard a barge in October 1985. The
load was worth an estimated $50 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
