<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PioneerAnniversary     06-13 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pioneer Anniversary,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Observe Fifth Anniversary of Spacecraft's Departure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists are observing the fifth
anniversary of Pioneer 10's departure from the solar system today
as the spacecraft continues collecting data about the sun and
searching for a tenth planet.
   Signals from the 570-pound Pioneer _ slightly more than 4
billion miles away from Earth _ are scheduled to be transmitted
over telephone lines from the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration to the California Museum of Science and Industry in
Los Angeles.
   Officials from the museum and TRW Inc., the Redondo Beach
company that built the spacecraft, were to unveil a refurbished
engineering model of the probe to go on public display on Tuesday.
   Scientists assembled here at a NASA facility to outline
Pioneer's most recent accomplishments and celebrate the craft's
role as one of the United States' most successful space missions.
   Pioneer is the first spacecraft to fly by Jupiter and return
pictures, chart Jupiter's intense radiation belts, measure the mass
of Jupiter's four planet-sized moons, locate the giant planet's
magnetic field and discover Jupiter is primarily a liquid planet.
   It's expected to transmit information until its power source
diminishes toward the end of the 1990s.
   The spacecraft was launched March 2, 1972 from Florida and made
its closest approach to Jupiter _ 82,000 miles _ on Dec. 3, 1973
after traveling an arc-shaped 620-million-mile path from Earth.
</TEXT>
