<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Singleton 1stLd-Writethru a0604 06-13 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Singleton, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0604,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Rapist Registers With Florida Officials</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Singleton registering with
authorities, other new details. No Pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted rapist whom outraged Californians
fought to keep out of their communities during his yearlong parole
there has come back to his hometown and registered with Florida
authorities today in Tampa.
   Lawrence Singleton gave his address to the Florida Department of
Law Enforcement to comply with a law requiring convicted felons
entering the state to register their address.
   ``He's met all the requirements of the statutes. As far as we're
concerned, we have no further involvement in this matter
whatsoever,'' said Jack Espinosa, spokesman for the Hillsborough
Sheriff's office.
   Sheriff's Col. Cal Henderson said Singleton received his Florida
driver's license last week.
   Singleton was convicted of raping a 15-year-old hitchhiker,
chopping her arms off with an ax and leaving her for dead along a
roadside near San Francisco in 1978. The 60-year-old former
merchant seaman spent eight years of a 14-year sentence in a
California prison.
   His parole ended in April, and Singleton soon surfaced in the
Tampa area, where he grew up and still has family.
   Singleton's relocation to the Forest Hills section in northwest
Tampa has some area residents worried.
   ``We don't want that type of individual living here. We're
concerned about the young children and we're concerned about the
young girls living in the neighborhood,'' said Audrey Grimes, a
neighbor.
   The owner of the home listed as Singleton's address told The
Tampa Tribune, ``I don't know anything about it.''
   In California, residents mounted campaigns when their communites
were mentioned as possible homes during Singleton's parole. One
town even filed a lawsuit.
   Last year, Florida corrections officials refused a request from
California officials to supervise Singleton's parole while he
stayed with relatives in the Tampa area.
</TEXT>
