<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Norway-Cabinet     06-13 0126</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Norway-Cabinet,0132</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Shuffles Cabinet In Norway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland
reshuffled her 2-year-old Cabinet on Monday.
   Mrs. Brundtland replaced three ministers and swapped two
portfolios but kept seven women in her 17-member Labor Party
government.
   Jan Balstad replaced Kurt Mosbakk as minister of trade and
shipping. Kirsti Kolle Groendahl took over for Vesla Vetlesen as
mininster for foreign aid.
   Einfrid Halvorsen replaced Anne-Lise Bakken as minister for
consumer and public administration affairs. The post of church
minister, which was surrendered by Groendahl, was assumed by Mary
Kvidal.
   The minister of communications, Kjell Borgen, switched posts
with William Engseth, minister for municipal affairs and labor
relations.
   The reshuffle was to prepare for a general election scheduled
for September 1989.

</TEXT>
