<DOCNO> AP880613-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w BC-ScotusAt-a-Glance     06-13 0850</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance,830</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
taken Monday by the Supreme Court.
   
   VACCINE
   
   The court ruled the government may be forced to pay damages when
a vaccine it licenses causes the disease it was intended to prevent.
   By a 9-0 vote, the justices rejected Reagan administration
arguments that the government always should be shielded from
lawsuit in such cases.
   The case is Berkowitz vs. U.S., 87-498.
   
   SENTENCING
   
   The court agreed to judge the constitutionality of a new
sentencing system for people convicted of federal crimes.
   At issue in the sentencing case is whether the U.S. Sentencing
Commission's rules that took effect Nov. 1 may stand or must be
thrown out. The validity of the commission itself is at stake, also.
   By the time the court announces its decision, expected sometime
in 1989, thousands of defendants will have to be resentenced _
regardless of which way the court rules.
   The case is U.S. vs. Mistretta, 87-1904.
   
   POLICE AUTHORITY
   
   The court armed police with new authority, ruling that officers
sometimes may chase someone who starts running at the sight of them
even though they have no reason to suspect criminal conduct.
   It unanimously ruled that Michigan prosecutors may use as
evidence the drugs dropped by a man who started running when he
spotted a police cruiser on a Detroit street.
   The case is Michigan vs. Chesternut, 86-1824.
   
   RACIAL DESEGREGATION
   
   The court declined to study an unprecedented
racial-desegregation case, refusing to free Yonkers, N.Y.,
officials from having to integrate city schools and build
subsidized housing to overcome decades of discrimination.
   The court, without comment, left intact rulings that Yonkers
must build subsidized housing in predominantly white sections of
the city and create ``magnet'' schools to reduce segregation.
   The cases are Yonkers Board of Education vs. U.S., 87-1632, and
Yonkers vs. U.S., 87-1686.
   
   FRAUD
   
   The court agreed to decide whether the government may use a 19th
Century anti-fraud law to impose stiff civil fines on top of
criminal penalties for the same offense.
   The court said it will hear an appeal by Reagan administration
officials seeking to fine the manager of a New York medical
laboratory $131,170 for defrauding the government of $585 on
Medicare bills.
   The case is U.S. vs. Halper, 87-1383.
   
   POSTAL SERVICE
   
   _ The court ruled that the Postal Service is similar to a
private business and said the service must pay interest on back pay
owed to a worker who won a lawsuit charging it with illegal
discrimination.
   By a 5-3 vote, the court ordered interest on back pay for a
letter carrier in Chesterfield, Mo., who was fired and later
ordered rehired.
   The case is Loeffler vs. Frank, 86-1431.
   
   DIRECT MAIL
   
   The court barred states from banning all direct mail
advertisements sent by lawyers to potential clients.
   The court, by a 6-3 vote, ruled in a Kentucky case that states
violate free-speech rights when prohibiting lawyers from soliciting
business by sending truthful and non-deceptive letters to people
they know face particular legal problems.
   The case is Shapero vs. Kentucky Bar Association, 87-16.
   
   DUPONT-LAROUCHE
   
   The court rejected the appeal of a DuPont family fortune heir
declared mentally incompetent after he loaned $212,000 to a group
linked to political extremist Lyndon LaRouche.
   The court, without comment, let stand rulings that control of
Lewis duPont Smith's $8 million estate properly was taken from him
in 1985 under Pennsylvania's guardianship law.
   The case is Smith vs. Smith, 87-1753.
   
   HUMANIST
   
   The court turned down the appeal of a philosophy professor
denied an opportunity to address Congress about secular humanism
during the lawmakers' daily moments of opening prayer.
   The court, over one dissenting vote, refused to hear arguments
that the professor's rights were violated.
   The case is Kurtz vs. Baker, 87-1581.
   
   CHILD SUPPORT
   
   The court told Wisconsin's highest court to restudy the case of
a teen-ager born out of wedlock who says she should be allowed to
seek support payments from her father's estate.
   The justices said the Wisconsin Supreme Court should review its
ruling that a $4,600 settlement between Heather Jo Krueger's
parents after she was born bars her from seeking any additional
money.
   The case is Gernardt vs. Moore, 87-1103.
   
   ANTITRUST LAW
   
   The court ruled that companies may violate antitrust law when
they lobby private organizations that play a prominent role in
influencing business legislation.
   The 7-2 decision upheld a $11.4 million jury award against a
company accused of ``packing'' a meeting of the National Fire
Protection Association when the organization adopted a safety code
for electrical wiring.
   The case is Allied Tube vs. Indian Head, 87-157.
   
   EXTRADITION
   
   People extradited from foreign countries to face criminal
charges here cannot avoid defending themselves against related
civil lawsuits filed in U.S. courts, the Supreme Court ruled today.
   The justices ruled unanimously against Wilfried van
Cauwenberghe, a Belgian citizen who is trying to avoid having to
defend himself against a $19 million lawsuit in California.
   The case is Van Cauwenberghe vs. Biard, 87-336.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
