<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ByrneExecution     06-13 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Byrne Execution,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State High Court, Federal Appeals Court Refuse to Stay La.
Execution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANGOLA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louisiana's Supreme Court and a federal
appeals court both refused today to stop Tuesday morning's
scheduled execution of convicted murderer Edward Byrne Jr.
   The decisions were released as Byrne, his attorneys and
prosecutors gathered at the state prison in Angola for a hearing
before Louisiana's newly appointed Pardon Board on Byrne's pleas
for a reduced sentence of life in prison. Gov. Buddy Roemer,
however, has the final say.
   Byrne is scheduled to die in the electric chair at the state
prison in Angola between 12:01 and 3 a.m. Tuesday. If he's executed
Tuesday, it would be the 100th execution nationwide since capital
punishment was reinstituted more than 10 years ago.
   The state Supreme Court gave no reason for its unanimous denial
of Byrne's appeal. The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeal, in a
12-page opinion, denied Byrne's petition for a stay of execution.
The petition claimed the execution would be unconstitutional
because it failed to give Byrne 60 days to appeal an earlier
decision by the U.S. Supreme Court.
   Officials at the 5th Circuit offices in New Orleans said another
Byrne appeal was pending there. Byrne's attorneys were expected to
appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court if that appeal failed.
   Byrne, 28, was condemned for killing Roberta Johnson, who he
said he began dating because he planned to rob the Bossier City gas
station where she was manager. She was fatally bludgeoned with a
ballpeen hammer on Aug. 14, 1984, as she prepared to take more than
$7,000 to the bank.
</TEXT>
