King Juan Carlos and Queen Sofia, who kissed and chatted with the
children for several minutes after being greeted by Queensland
state Governor Sir Walter Campbell.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethel Bradley remembers the good old days
when she had her husband of 47 years, Mayor Tom Bradley, all to
herself. Now she competes with one of the busiest social schedules
around.
   ``I didn't realize it, but I guess the best years of my life
were the years we spent together before he was an elected
official,'' Mrs. Bradley, 69, said in an interview Monday in the
Los Angeles Times.
   The wife of the four-term mayor, who is seeking an unprecedented
fifth term next year, said she's lucky to dine with Bradley once a
week, and catches up on his well-being by watching local television
news.
   After years of following in his footsteps, she said, she grew
weary and gave it all up.
   ``I get tired of meeting these same people after 25 years ...
People talk to him all the time,'' she said.
   The mayor admitted time with his wife is limited, but said he
sets aside three special nights every year.
   ``Her birthday, my birthday, the Academy Awards,'' Bradley said.
``Those are absolutely inviolate dates.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Playing the role of tomboy Elly May
Clampett on ``The Beverly Hillbillies'' wasn't hard for actress
Donna Douglas.
   ``I never claimed to be an actress,'' Ms. Douglas, 49, said.
``I'd only been in acting school one week. They asked me if I could
play that part, and I said sure. It was like a slice out of my
life. It was a piece of cake.''
   Since Ms. Douglas gained fame in the sitcom that was canceled in
1971, she has played parts on television and recorded albums of
country and gospel music.
   On Sunday, she sang gospel songs and preached for 67 people at a
small Pentecostal church in Frankfort.
   Ms. Douglas is now working on a children's show and a
feature-length cartoon.
   ``The Beverly Hillbillies,'' a comedy about a Tennessee family
that moved to Beverly Hills, Calif., after oil was discovered on
their land, was rated No. 1 for two seasons during its nine-year
stint.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock star David Crosby was upheld by the the
U.S. Supreme Court Monday in his claim that Dallas police
unlawfully searched his night club dressing room leading to a
cocaine conviction.
   The court refused to reinstate the conviction and five-year
prison sentence that a Texas court overturned after Crosby already
had spent five months in prison.
   The justices, without comment, let stand the ruling last
November by the state court that cocaine and a pistol confiscated
from Crosby in 1982 should not have been used as evidence at his
trial.
   Crosby, who gained fame as part of the group called Crosby,
Stills and Nash, was convicted of unlawfully possessing cocaine and
carrying a handgun in a tavern.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Frank Sinatra, stricken
with a mild bout of food poisoning that forced him to cancel an
AIDS benefit performance, was recuperating at his desert home, his
publicist said.
   ``He had a touch of food poisoning and he's returned home,''
spokeswoman Susan Reynolds said Monday. ``It was apparently
something he ate en route to Washington aboard a private jet.''
   The illness caused Sinatra to bow out of a performance Sunday
night. The $100-a-seat concert at the John F. Kennedy Center for
the Performing Arts featured Dionne Warwick, Elton John, Stevie
Wonder and Gladys Knight.
   Frank Sinatra Jr. told the audience his father had ``taken ill''
and would not perform. The elder Sinatra returned to California to
recuperate.
