<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1500EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Shultz-Arms     06-13 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Arms,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Warns of Buildup in Gulf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz expressed
concern today about the introduction of advanced missiles into the
Persian Gulf war, saying that countries far removed from the
conflict may be put at risk.
   Shultz said use of these advanced missiles in the Iran-Iraq war
has led to the ``indiscriminate slaughter'' of civilians and made a
peace settlment more difficult.
   ``We are already seeing signs of a dangerous new arms race which
will put at risk countries far removed from the gulf region
itself,'' he said.
   Shultz's remarks were prepared for a special U.N. session on
disarmament at U.N. headquarters in New York.
   Shultz also said the United States considers nuclear
proliferation the most important item of the U.N. session.
   ``Does anyone doubt that the spread of nuclear weapons threatens
regional and global security?'' Shultz said. ``What state believes
that, if it now acquired nuclear weapons, its rivals would not do
the same?''
   He said that at the moment that the United States and the Soviet
Union have agreed to reduce their nuclear arsenals, ``it would be
tragic for other countries to pursue the capability to cross the
nuclear threshhold.''
   Apparently alluding to India and Pakistan, Shultz said South
Asia is the area of greatest danger.
   ``We encourage the states of South Asia to take concrete steps
to meet this urgent challenge. The U.S. is prepared to work with
countries inside and outide the region to find a lasting solution
to the danger of proliferation that satisfies all parties,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
