<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1541EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Wiarda     06-13 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Wiarda,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Of European Human Rights Court Dies At Age 81</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerardus Wiarda, a Dutch jurist
who was president of the European Court for Human Rights, died at
his home here, a relative said Monday. He was 81.
   The cause of his death Saturday was not immediately available,
but Wiarda had been in ill health over the past few years, the
relative said. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Born in Amsterdam in 1906, Wiarda finished his legal studies at
Amsterdam's Municipal University in 1929.
   After practicing law in Rotterdam and serving as a judge at
Amsterdam's district court, Wiarda was appointed a member of the
Dutch Supreme Court, the highest in the land, in 1950.
   During his 26-year tenure there, the last four of which he
served as the court's president, Wiarda earned a reputation of a
progressive in social and judicial issues.
   After his retirement from the bench in 1976, he was appointed as
a judge at the European Court for Human Rights in Strasbourg. In
1981, he was named president of the 18-member human rights panel
for the 21-nation Council of Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880613-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1505EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush     06-13 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Denounces South Africa as ``Racist State''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush denounced the
government of South Africa on Monday as a ``racist state,'' using
the strongest language yet of any high Reagan administration
official toward the apartheid regime.
   His remark, which came a day after Democratic platform writers
agreed to castigate South Africa as a ``terrorist state'' in their
1988 party document, seemed calculated to put distance between Bush
and administration policies on the subject.
   However, Bush, like President Reagan, said he does not favor
breaking diplomatic ties with Pretoria.
   It was the second day in a row that Bush sought to highlight his
views on civil rights issues.
   In a speech Sunday at predominently black Central State
University in Wilberforce, Ohio, Bush said he would campaign for a
``positive civil rights agenda'' and suggested that his priorities
would be different from those of the administration _ including
more federal support for minority businesses and more assistance
for the disadvantaged.
   Bush, talking Monday to reporters in the Executive Office
Building adjacent to the White House, was asked if he agreed with
the Democrats' decision to brand South Africa a terrorist state, a
characterization sought by defeated Democratic presidential
candidate Jesse Jackson.
   ``I think it's a racist state, regrettably, and I think we ought
to do what we can by staying engaged and trying to figure if the
U.S. can use its moral influence to change that situation,'' Bush
replied.
   ``I don't favor breaking diplomatic relations,'' he said.
   The Democrats, who held a platform-drafting session over the
weekend in Mackinac Island, Mich., have not indicated whether they
would seek to break relations with South Africa.
   In the past, Reagan has said he personally considered the system
of apartheid, or white minority rule, in South Africa ``repugnant.''
   But the president initially resisted imposing economic sanctions
on that nation, going along with the sanctions only after they won
wide bipartisan support in Congress.
   On Monday, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
administration disagreed with the description of South Africa as a
terrorist state.
   ``We believe the best way to influence policy in South Africa is
to stay engaged,'' Fitzwater said. He briefed reporters at the same
time that Bush was answering questions, and the subject of Bush's
comments did not come up.
   Bush, who is spending this week in Washington and has no
campaign appearances planned, met with reporters to announce the
naming of two senior aides, James Lake as communications consultant
and Sheila Tate as campaign press secretary.
   Lake, a Washington political consultant, was the campaign
spokesman for the Reagan-Bush ticket in 1984. Ms. Tate is a former
spokeswoman for Nancy Reagan.
   After announcing the appointments, Bush stayed on to answer a
wide range of questions and even joked that he had offered a spot
on his ticket to Jackson, whose Democratic vice presidential
thoughts have been a hot topic.
   ``I saw Jesse the other day. ... I said, `Jesse, I don't think
you're going to make it on the Democratic ticket. Are you
interested?'''
   ``And he turned to his mother, and he said, `George Bush has
done a good job as vice president. I might keep him on.' And that's
all I know about the Jesse Jackson situation.''
   On possible Democratic platform fights, Bush said: ``That's
their problem. That's the problem of the Democrats. The issues,
regardless of what happens, are going to be so clear in the fall _
the differences _ that I think what I've got to do is do my part
... and not intervene in that Democratic convention process at
all.''
   ``I don't think it would be right for me to get involved in the
Democratic convention and to say what ought to be done about Jesse
Jackson. He ran a good race. He stayed in there. He came up when
there was a lot of feeling that he wasn't going to do as well as he
did, and I'll give credit for that,'' Bush added.
   Bush also said there were no immediate plans for Treasury
Secretary James Baker to join his campaign team. ``I'm comfortable
with the situation at present,'' Bush said. ``He and I have been
friends for so long. I see him a lot, so I'm getting the benefit of
his advice as it is.''
   Republican sources have said they expect Baker to join Bush's
campaign this summer. However, Baker, a longtime Bush supporter,
told The Associated Press in an interview on Friday that no
decision would be made at least until after the economic summit in
Toronto later this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
