<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GNCClaims     06-13 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GNC Claims,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Nutrition To Pay $600,000 To Settle Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Nutrition Corp., the national health
food chain, has agreed to pay $600,000 to three health research
groups to settle allegations that it made false claims for diet
supplements, the Federal Trade Commission announced Monday.
   Under terms of a consent agreement, GNC agreed to the payment to
be divided equally among the American Diabetes Association,
American Cancer Society and American Heart Association, the FTC
reported.
   The agreement settles charges brought in 1984 that GNC falsely
claimed its Healthy Greens diet supplement was effective in
reducing the risk of cancer, and that other food supplements would
promote weight loss, help muscle growth and retard aging, according
to the trade commission.
   GNC, based in Pittsburgh, operates some 1,100 stores across the
nation selling health food products and various vitamin and mineral
supplements. It had sales of more than $300 million in 1986.
   The $600,000 payment for health research is in lieu of paying
redress to consumers in the case, the FTC reported. In signing the
consent order, GNC did not acknowledge wrongdoing.
   Healthy Greens, pills containing vitamins, minerals and
dehydrated vegetables, are no longer sold by the company, the FTC
noted.
</TEXT>
