<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EnergyEfficiency     06-13 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Energy Efficiency,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Votes to Set Efficiency Standards for Lamp Devices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House completed congressional action
Monday on legislation to set efficiency standards for fluorescent
lamp ballasts, a move proponents say can produce energy savings
equal to seven large power plants.
   The bill covering the ballasts that start and operate
fluorescent lights was given voice-vote approval and sent to the
White House, where it is being opposed as unnecessary.
   The measure is an amendment to the 1987 law that required
efficiency standards for a variety of large household appliances.
The administration also opposed that legislation, but President
Reagan signed it following its overwhelming approval by Congress.
   The American Council for an Energy Efficient Economy estimates
that with at least 50 million fluorescent ballasts sold annually,
more efficient units could save 7,000 megawatts of electricity by
the year 2000 along with $11 billion in lower lighting costs to
consumers.
   The president's Office of Management and Budget said many
ballasts already meet the proposed standards and the bill would
impose unnecessary burdens on industry and force consumers to pay
more for ballasts.
   The bill and the 1987 law resulted from a coalition of energy
conservation advocates and electrical and appliance manufacturers,
who began backing national standards after a handful of states
began setting their own.
</TEXT>
