<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ChildCarePoll     06-13 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Care Poll,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most Voters Polled Favor $2.5 Billion Expansion of Child Care</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three out of five voters favor a massive $2.5
billion expansion of federal aid for child care, according to a
poll released Monday by two leading proponents of the legislation.
   Of the 901 voters sampled in the nationwide telephone survey, 60
percent said they favored the Act for Better Child Care proposal of
Rep. Dale Kildee, D-Mich., and Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., and
32 percent said they opposed it.
   The survey by Marttila & Kiley Inc. of Boston was conducted from
May 31 through June 5 and carried a margin of error of 3.2
percentage points.
   The poll was commissioned by the Children's Defense Fund and the
American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees, two
of the leading lobbying forces behind the Dodd-Kildee bill.
   Three-fourths of the money in the legislation would provide new
child care subsidies to families making up to 115 percent of a
state's median income. Federal aid for child care through tax
credits and grants currently totals some $6.9 billion a year.
   Business groups and the Reagan administration oppose the
Dodd-Kildee bill and have united behind a smaller $375 million
counterproposal authored by Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and Rep.
Nancy Johnson, R-Conn.
</TEXT>
