<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--Geothermal     06-13 0129</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Geothermal,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Orders Study of Geothermal Development Impact on Yellowstone
Park</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Monday passed legislation to
require the U.S. Geological Survey to study the impact of
geothermal development on Yellowstone National Park, home of the
nation's most famous geothermal sight, the Old Faithful geyser.
   The provision, in a bill sent to the Senate by voice vote, is a
response to complaints from conservationists that proposals to tap
underground steam deposits near the park could disrupt Old Faithful
and other geothermal features.
   The bill would amend a 1970 law that permits the government to
lease land to people trying to convert geothermal steam into
electricity. The bill would extend beyond 15 years the amount of
time a leaseholder has to develop a project.
