<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Intellectuals     06-13 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Intellectuals,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab And Israeli Intellectuals Sign `Peace Treaty'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli and Palestinian intellectuals signed a
``peace treaty'' in a symbolic ceremony Monday after months of
arguments and said their example shows that gaps between the two
sides can be bridged.
   ``If clods like us, who are not always very good at taking
action, can do it, so can politicians,'' said one of the
signatories, Israeli poet Natan Zach.
   They said the agreement, written in Hebrew, Arabic and English,
was the first of its kind to be negotiated by Israelis and
Palestinians.
   It was signed by about 25 Israeli and Palestinian authors and
artists during a news conference. Foreign reporters far outnumbered
Israeli and Palestinian journalists.
   ``The agreement was reached after many arguments,'' said Nissim
Kalderon, an Israeli poet. ``After 40 years of war and brutality,
there is bitterness on both sides and demands on both sides that
the other finds hard to cope with.''
   The pact calls for the establishment of a Palestinian state, to
be called Falastin, in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip. ``Falastin'' is how the word ``Palestine'' sounds in Arabic.
   Jerusalem, a key point of dispute, would be demilitarized and
serve as the capital of both states. Israel and Falastin would
recognize each other's right to live in peace and security.
   The signatories are members of the Israeli and Palestinian
Writers, Artists and Academics Committee Against Occupation, the
only professional group that includes both Israelis and
Palestinians from the occupied territories.
   Most of the Jewish members are left-wing activists.
   Zach, for example, recently canceled the International Poetry
Festival, which was to be held in Israel this month, to protest the
army crackdown on the Palestinian uprising in the occupied lands.
   Asad el Asad, head of the Palestinian Writers Association in the
occupied territories, said the Palestine Liberation Organization
favored the terms of the treaty. ``We feel we are transmitting
clearly and honestly the message of our representatives, the PLO,''
Asad said.
   Israel refuses to negotiate with the PLO, saying it is a
terrorist organization. The PLO covenant calls for the destruction
of the Jewish state, and the PLO has refused to accept
unconditionally U.N. resolutions guaranteeing Israel's right to
secure borders.
   Zach said the group would now seek the signatures of additional
intellectuals in Israel and the occupied territories.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
