<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AIDS-InfectionRate     06-13 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Infection Rate,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says 3 of 1,000 Hospital Patients Infected With AIDS Virus</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AIDS Meeting, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About three of every 1,000 patients at
six U.S. hospitals are infected with the AIDS virus, but it has not
spread extensively in the past year, according to a study released
Monday.
   It indicated the infection rate among hospital patients is about
five times higher than that among military recruits from the same
cities but has not changed over the first 15 months of the study.
   ``The importance is that there has been a slowing in the rate of
new infection,'' said Dr. Timothy J. Dondero. ``The stable rate
means it is not exploding.''
   Dondero, a researcher at the U.S. Centers for Disease Control in
Atlanta, heads the study program called the U.S. Sentinal Hospital
Surveillance Network.
   He said the infection rate seen at the six hospitals, four of
them in the Midwest, probably is lower than the rate nationwide.
   If the rate at the hospitals were the same as the national
figure, that would mean about 700,000 Americans carry the AIDS
virus. The CDC officially estimates between 1 million and 1.5
million Americans are infected, and Dondero said he believes the
true figure ``is closer to 1 million.''
   Figures are based on anonymous blood testing of 18,809 hospital
patients.
   Excluded from the tests was anyone who might already have the
disease, acquired immune deficiency syndrome, including patients
hospitalized for infections or cancer. Many of those tested were in
the hospital for accidents, surgery or childbirth.
   The CDC plans to expand the program to 40 hospitals across the
country.
   Dr. George Grady, the Massachusetts state epidemiologist, said
the CDC study may have missed an increase in the infection rate
because it did not sample enough people and did not choose a truly
representative sample of the population.
   ``There is a feeling across the country that the infection rate
in gay men is stabilizing and that it is still going up in
intravenous drug users,'' he said.
</TEXT>
