<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1612EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PlantBlast     06-13 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Blast,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chemical Production Resumes Under Watchful Eye</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Production of a vital oxidizer for the
fuel of the space shuttle booster rocket resumed Monday, five weeks
after the only other plant in the nation that made the chemical
blew up a mile away.
   Fire inspectors were on hand at the Kerr-McGee Corp. plant in
nearby Henderson when workers began filling vats with chemicals to
produce ammonium perchlorate, an oxidizer used in the solid-fuel
shuttle boosters and some military rockets.
   Clark County Fire Chief Roy Parrish said the inspectors would be
at the plant until a dispute between the fire department and the
company over storage of the finished chemical product is resolved.
   ``It's like a fire watch,'' said Parrish. ``We're going to have
them out there 24 hours a day.''
   Parrish refused to rule out the possibility of legal action
against the company if it does not agree to fire department
recommendations that it store the chemical in smaller piles and
place the piles further apart than it currently does.
   County officials and a team of safety experts hired by
Kerr-McGee plan to meet Thursday to try and work out an agreement
on the storage issue.
   ``We will ask some very pointed questions,'' said Parrish.
``They're going to have to come up with some reasons why they
selected the way they did to store the product.''
   Plant spokeswoman Annita Bridges said workers will be on the job
in three shifts while the plant gears up to operate at its capacity
of 36 million pounds of ammonium perchlorate a year.
   Officials of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
said last week that they had only enough fuel for eight shuttle
boosters, enough for four flights. Each set of boosters needs 1.7
million pounds of ammonium perchlorate mixed with its rubber-like
fuel.
   Kerr-McGee temporarily halted its production of ammonium
perchlorate after a series of thunderous explosions May 4 killed
two people, injured 326 and caused an estimated $73 million in
damage at the Pacific Engineering and Production Co. in Henderson.
   After a brief reopening the next week, production was halted
again under the threat of lawsuits by state and local officials
until an independent safety team could inspect the plant.
   Kerr-McGee agreed, among other things, to ship the chemical in
containers less susceptible to heat and shock, and reduce by 50
percent its supply of unfinished ammonium perchlorate.
   The cause of the Pacific Engineering blast is still under
investigation. Company officials have said the blast may have been
caused by a leaking natural gas line, but fire department sources
said the most likely cause was a spark that set off ammonium
perchlorate.
   Parrish said he would not speculate on when the department's
formal report fixing the cause of the explosions will be finished.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
