<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HilbertSentencing     06-13 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hilbert Sentencing,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former County Sheriff Sentenced To Jail</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Johnie is cq in 4th graf, `Hilbert, 45 ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA BRYSON HODEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARKERSBURG, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ex-sheriff who pleaded guilty to
buying the job from his predecessor for $100,000 was sentenced
Monday to seven years in a federal penitentiary.
   Former Mingo County Sheriff Charles E. ``Eddie'' Hilbert ``was
not motivated by personal greed or a lust for power,'' said
Hilbert's lawyer, John Cyrus. ``In a real sense (he was) a victim
of (a) corrupt system. ...
   ``The crimes he committed were those of a stupid man,'' Cyrus
told U.S. District Judge Charles Haden, adding that his client has
a ``low intelligence quotient (and is) only marginally literate.''
   Hilbert, 45, pleaded guilty in April to one count of mail fraud,
one count of tax evasion and one count of conspiracy to buy the
sheriff's job from then-Sheriff Johnie Owens.
   In addition to sentencing Hilbert to five years on the
conspiracy count, Haden also ordered him to pay a $10,000 fine. In
addition, Hilbert was ordered to serve two years on the mail fraud
charge, which stemmed from a scheme to obtain backdated insurance
coverage for his son, who had been involved in a motorcycle acident.
   Hilbert also was sentenced to three years in prison on the tax
evasion charge, but Haden said that sentence would run concurrently
with his other terms.
   The former sheriff, who is scheduled to begin serving his
sentence on Aug. 11, had faced a maximum sentence of 13 years in
prison and a $350,000 fine. Under federal law he must serve a
minimum of one-third of the seven-year sentence before he will be
eligible for parole.
   Cyrus said Hilbert ``did not profit'' from his crimes, but
rather, ``Mr. Hilbert's crimes are ... more crimes of the heart.
   ``Eddie Hilbert is a weak man further weakened by alcoholism,''
Cyrus told Haden, who emphasized that Hilbert pleaded guilty to a
conspiracy count under the federal government's Racketeer
Influenced and Corrupt Organizations act.
   Hilbert told the judge that he was sorry for what he had done
and added that he had never taken a kickback or sold drugs to
anyone in Mingo County.
   Owens, who said he took the $100,000 from Hilbert and gave some
of the money to county commissioners to approve the arrangement, is
serving a 14-year federal prison sentence.
   Former County Commissioner Rastie Runyon Jr. is scheduled to
report to federal prison later this month for his role in the
scheme. The other two county commissioners at the time also are
under indictment.
   Haden on Monday also accepted a guilty plea from former Mingo
County Democratic Chairman Donald Evans, 63, to one count of
conspiracy to buy votes. Evans, who is to be sentenced Aug. 8, also
has agreed to cooperate with federal prosecutors.
</TEXT>
