<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JailEscape     06-13 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jail Escape,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officers Scour Cumberland County For Escaped Inmates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY AMANA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FAYETTEVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five escapees, including a confessed
double killer, were still at large Monday as more than 75 officers
scoured the area for the men who cut their way from what was
thought to be an escape-proof jail.
   Six detainees, including the confessed double killer in the
so-called ``ninja'' slayings, escaped Sunday night from the
Cumberland County Jail. They left in their wake two small hacksaw
blades, an 8-inch-by-15-inch hole in a cell and a rope made of
bedsheets hanging from a fourth-floor window, authorities said.
   Frederick Glenn Evans, 20, who was being held on murder charges,
was recaptured shortly after the escape and was treated for a
broken leg or hip he suffered in a fall, said Harold Little, a
spokesman for the sheriff's department. The others remained at
large as officers with the FBI, State Bureau of Investigation,
state Highway Patrol and nearby military installations fanned out
to search the county.
   Fayetteville architect Dan MacMillan, who designed the jail,
said he was baffled at how the men sawed through the heavy-gauge
horizontal bars.
   ``An ordinary hacksaw would not cut this material,'' he said
Monday. ``I've seen demonstrations of it where they (try to cut) it
with an electric hacksaw, but the thing just goes back and forth
and it does not make any impression in the material. ... I'm really
not aware that there was a hacksaw blade available that would saw
the material.''
   The escape apparently was spotted by a police records clerk who
noticed someone drop from the center, Little said. Desk Sgt. Mike
Reihe gave chase but lost the suspects in the dark, Little said.
   Still at large Monday afternoon was Jeffrey Karl Meyer of
Raleigh, a 21-year-old former soldier at Fort Bragg who confessed
to the stabbing deaths of Paul Kutz Sr., 68, and his wife, Janie
Kutz, 62. Meyer was scheduled to appear in Superior Court Monday
for a continuation of the sentencing phase of his trial, in which
he may face the death penalty.
   The slayings came to be known as the ``ninja'' murders because
Meyer and accused accomplice Mark E. Thompson, another former
soldier at Fort Bragg, allegedly wore black clothes resembling
outfits worn by Japanese assassins.
   The other escapees were: Jerry Ronald Pond Jr., 24, of
Fayetteville, held in the slaying of a pawn shop employee; Gregory
Morris Lee, 30, of Fayetteville, held on a charge of first-degree
burglary, assault on a female and larceny; Jeffrey Charles Minnick,
22, of Hope Mills, held on charges of second-degree burglary,
first-degree sex offense and common law robbery; and Rick A.
Wilson, 30, of Hope Mills, held on charges of felony breaking and
entering.
</TEXT>
