<DOCNO> AP880613-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 2050EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d p AM-Bush-Appointments 1stLd-Writethru a0698 06-13 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Appointments, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0698,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Names Three Media Advisers</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Adds 2 grafs with Hart appointment, bgng ``Bush also named...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush on Monday named
James Lake as his campaign communications adviser and Sheila Tate
as campaign press secretary.
   Lake, a Washington-based political consultant, served a similar
role in the 1984 Reagan-Bush campaign and was press secretary to
President Reagan early in his 1980 campaign.
   Ms. Tate, a former press secretary to Nancy Reagan, had been
managing director of the Washington office of Hill and Knowlton, a
public relations and advertising company, since May 1987.
   Bush, who appeared with the new aides at a brief news conference
in the Old Executive Office Building, said ``having these two
professionals will strengthen my campaign organization.''
   The campaign has not had a press secretary since Peter Teeley, a
longtime Bush associate, resigned as communications director and
chief spokesman in mid-May after clashes with other senior Bush
aides.
   Bush said that, as press secretary, Ms. Tate would have ``full
unhampered access'' to him and other key campaign officials.
   Bush also named Stephen Hart, who has been acting press
secretary, to assistant to the vice president for press relations.
   Hart will deal mostly with matters affecting the office of the
vice presidency, while Ms. Tate and Lake will be involved in Bush's
campaign.
</TEXT>
