<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1615EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-BlairHouse     06-13 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blair House,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presidential Guest Quarters Displayed After $13 Million Makeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials on Monday showed off the $13 million
renovation of Blair House, the president's guest quarters where
visiting dignitaries can eat in one of three dining rooms,
entertain in a cozy library and have their hair styled at a private
Elizabeth Arden salon.
   ``It is not too grand, but it has elegance,'' said Chief of
Protocol Selwa Roosevelt, who oversaw the restoration. ``It is a
guest house worthy of this great nation.''
   Manager Benedicte Valentiner said she doesn't expect guests for
another six weeks because work is only 90 percent complete. The
chef, for instance, needs to a proper gas range for cooking. The
first official visitor has not been named.
   Blair House, a 115-room complex consisting of four connected
townhouses on Pennsylvania Avenue across from the White House, was
shut down in 1982 after a malfunctioning gas valve leaked explosive
natural gas during one dignitary's stay.
   In 1985, Congress allocated $8.6 million for a complete overhaul
that included new electrical heating, plumbing and air conditioning
systems, roof repairs, installation of fire and safety systems and
improved security.
   The rest of the money _ more than $5 million _ was raised
privately for refurbishing the interior of the four-story house.
Furniture is in the Anglo-American style of 18th and 19th centuries
with lots of overstuffed chairs and couches, Oriental rugs and
hand-painted wallpaper.
   ``We wanted it to be soft and light,'' said decorator Mark
Hampton, who shared the project with Mario Buatta. That was no
small feat because heavy curtains will be drawn to keep ``the local
Pennsylvania Avenue terrorist from looking in the windows,'' he
said.
   Rooms that formerly had dingy white walls were painted a variety
of bright colors: salmon, blue, shades of yellow, to name a few.
Light streams through the back windows that face an interior garden.
   Chiefs of state invited by the president to use Blair House will
sleep in a double canopy bed in a private room, part of a suite
that includes another bedroom for a spouse, a sitting room and
three bathrooms, one of which has a European bidet.
   If the leader feels cramped by an 18th century bed, the Blair
House staff can arrange for a king-size bed to be installed.
   ``We will do anything to make them happy,'' said the
multi-lingual Valentiner, who will stay on premises to supervise
the staff of 13 during a an official visit. The most number of
people Blair House can accomodate is 27 _ 19 guests and eight staff
members. All stay free of charge.
   If the leader wants see people, he or she can attend to business
in a book-lined libary, which Hampton tried to give a masculine
feel by using rich brown tones. For news conferences, heads of
state have the use of a high-ceilinged room with two fireplaces.
   Since dignitaries often bring family members, Blair House has a
private Elizabeth Arden studio with professional hair styling
equipment.
   The original house, built in 1824, is rich in history. After the
original owner's death it was sold to Francis Preston Blair, an
intimate of President Andrew Jackson.
   Before the outbreak of the Civil War, Col. Robert E. Lee was
offered the command of the Union Armies at a Blair House meeting,
but he declined in favor of his native Virginia.
   President Roosevelt approved the acquisition of the house in
1942, saying the government needed it ``for the entertainment of
distinguished visitors.''
   On Nov. 1, 1950, two Puerto Rican nationalists tried to force
their way into Blair House in an assassination attempt on President
Truman. One of the nationalists and a White House guard died in the
shootout.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
