<DOCNO> AP880613-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1800EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Skunky     06-13 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Skunky,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pet Skunk Put To Sleep For Biting Neighbor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCEVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pet skunk who made headlines and
drew hundreds of callers lobbying to save his life was put to death
Monday because the man he bit refused to undergo precautionary
rabies treatment.
   After three stays of execution, Skunky was given a fatal
injection so that his brain could be tested to see whether he had
rabies.
   Skunky's owner, Jan Shelton of Buford, had tried until the end
to save the animal by trying to persuade the man whom Skunky bit
either to take rabies shots or drop his complaint.
   She had tears in her eyes as she spoke her last words to her
pet. ``Hey, you're sleeping. You're not conscious. It's fine,'' she
said.
   The bitten man, William Eugene Evans, 48, had said Thursday he
would not change his mind and either drop his complaint or undergo
a $600 series of rabies shots. Both moves would have spared
Skunky's life.
   Evans' physician said Evans should avoid rabies shots because he
suffered a heart attack two weeks ago.
   Ms. Shelton claims that Evans was mistreating her 1-year-old
skunk when he was bitten June 4, but Evans said he was bitten when
he reached down to pet the animal, thinking it was a cat.
   Officials say that the skunk is not classified as a domestic
animal, and by state law, had to be put to death and its brain
tested for rabies. The only alternatives were for Evans to
volunteer to undergo rabies treatment or to take a chance and agree
to spare Skunky from the fatal test.
   County Public Information Officer David Hirt noted that Skunky
had won three stays of execution last week, when the story began
making headlines.
   Skunky won his first postponement so that his case could be
heard by the county commission last week. The commission gave him
another break until Thursday, and then agreed to an extension until
Monday at noon.
   ``I've had hundreds of calls to the county office to save
Skunky,'' said Hirt.
</TEXT>
