<HEAD>American Jewish Congress Sponsors Forum With Retired Israeli
Generals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Jewish Congress will present a
satellite television forum to enable four retired Israeli generals
to explain their support of a Middle East land-for-peace compromise
to Jews in 22 U.S. cities, the group's president said Monday.
   ``We wanted to present another point of view by people who know
the situation best,'' Robert F. Lifton told a news conference.
   He noted that conservative Israeli leaders have taken the stance
that any relinquishing of territory would be ``tantamount to
suicide.''
   However, Lifton said his organization had scheduled the
televised forum to inform American Jews about the viewpoint which
believes that a ``land-for-peace compromise with conditions is a
better choice'' than continuing the status quo.
   Lifton said conditions for such a compromise might include a
lengthy transition period; demilitarization of the area; removal of
foreign troops east of the Jordan River, and establishment of
warning stations.
   The forum, which will allow the audience to question the panel,
is scheduled to begin at 5 p.m. EDT Tuesday.
   The panelists are retired Brig. Gen. Yoram Agmon, former air
attache at the Israeli Embassy in Washington; retired Maj. Gen. Ori
Orr, former chief of staff of the central command; retired Brig.
Gen. Ephraim Sneh, former head of civil administration for Judea
and Samaria, and retired Maj. Gen. Aharon Yariv, former director of
military intelligence.
