<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest Bjt   06-13 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest, Bjt,0686</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Policeman Shot in Ethnic Protest; General Strike in Armenia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A general strike was said to have virtually shut
down Armenia on Monday, and a shotgun blast killed a policeman
during weekend ethnic protests in the neighboring southern republic
of Azerbaijan.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said an
Azerbaijani officer was killed by shotgun fire during protests in
Baku, the Azerbaijani capital. Gerasimov identified the slain
officer only as Sgt. Izmailov.
   It was the first official confirmation of a police death in
ethnic unrest that began in February in the neighboring Caucasus
republics. Gerasimov identified the gunman only as an Armenian
named Aganbegyan.
   Azerbaijanis and Armenians are arguing over control of
Nagorno-Karabakh, a region with a predominantly Armenian population
that was assigned to Azerbaijan in 1923. The conflict is aggravated
by the fact that most Azerbaijanis are Moslems and most Armenians
are Christians.
   On Sunday, rumors that two Armenians had been killed in
Azerbaijan led to protests by Armenians in Moscow. They gathered in
a cemetery and marched to the offices of the official Tass news
agency.
   Gerasimov told reporters Monday: ``We have received information
from Baku that the information about the murder of two Armenians is
false. In fact, there was a shooting in Baku from a shotgun _ a
shot from a shotgun and the bullet killed a militia sergeant
there.''
   ``The bullet was deflected from some kind of surface,'' he said,
and police have not determined whether the killing was intentional
or accidental. It occurred ``during a demonstration for retaining
Nagorno-Karabakh region in Azerbaijan,'' Gerasimov said.
   He provided no details of the shooting and did not say precisely
when it occurred. There were unconfirmed reports Saturday of
large-scale protests in Baku.
   Gerasimov and Sergei Grigoryants, a Moscow dissident reached by
telephone, said Armenians met in their capital, Yerevan, on Sunday
and decided on a general strike.
   Its timing is an attempt to influence a June 15 meeting of the
Supreme Soviet of Armenia.
   Armenia's new Communist Party leader, Suren Arutyunyan,
addressed protesters and told them the Armenian Supreme Soviet
would ``not only review, but decide positively'' on their claim,
Grigoryants said. National government and party officials have
refused the Armenian demand for control of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Grigoryants, a former political prisoner, said the activists had
not decided how long the strike would run but that it might
continue until June 28, when a special conference of the national
Communist Party begins in Moscow.
   He said estimates of the number of people who gathered in
Yerevan on Sunday ranged from 500,000 to 700,000, which would rival
the huge demonstrations at the end of February. His estimate could
not be confirmed independently.
   After the February protests, riots broke out in the Azerbaijan
city of Sumgait, north of Baku. Officials have said 32 people were
killed _ 26 Armenians and six Azerbaijanis.
   Those who protested on Sunday agreed on a general strike to
include all industries except food processing, health care and
transportation, Grigoryants said, and it spread to public transport
on Monday.
   He said strikes were under way throughout Armenia, with the
possible exception of Kafan city, from which he had no information.
   According to official and dissident versions of events in
Yerevan, strikes, meetings and protests continued from Sunday night
into Monday morning.
   Grigoryants said the constant gatherings in the main square were
called off Monday afternoon because the temperature reached 104
degrees.
   People assembled again Monday night but there was no information
on their numbers or what happened, he said.
   Arutyunyan was made Armenian party leader May 21, replacing
Karen Demirchyan. Azerbaijan party leader Kyamran Bagirov was
replaced the same day in a clear indication of Moscow's displeasure
with the unrest.
   Gerasimov said the trouble did not stem from Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's efforts to reform Soviet society. ``This is not the
result of democracy and glasnost, but many years of stagnation when
we didn't delve deeply enough into national problems,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
