<HEAD>Angels Say Police Arresting, Harassing Them Over Patrol</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Guardian Angels on Monday accused police of
harassing them to halt their patrol of a restaurant district,
saying police arrested two Angels after they were menaced by a
knife-wielding crack dealer.
   ``I think it's ridiculous for the police to be fighting the
Guardian Angels. They should be fighting the crack dealers,'' said
Lisa Sliwa, spokeswoman for the group and wife of the group's
founder, Curtis Sliwa. ``It's almost as if they are on the side of
the drug dealers.''
   The confrontation that led to the arrest of two youths Sunday
night followed an incident the previous night that left one Angel
critically injured after he was stabbed.
   The Angels started their patrols of the Restaurant Row section
of West 46th Street in midtown Manhattan last Wednesday. Fifteen
proprietors asked the volunteer patrol group to help rid the block
of drug traffic.
   Asked if the Angels were being harassed by police, Detective
Joseph McConville, a department spokesman, said: ``I have no
knowledge of that.''
   He had no comment when asked if the Angels were being asked not
to patrol Restaurant Row.
   According to Ms. Sliwa, the latest incident occurred at about 1
a.m. Monday while the two Angels were on patrol in the area.
   ``They told a small group of crack dealers to leave the area, to
move on. One of the crack dealers pulled out a knife from his back
pocket and threatened the Angels,'' she said.
   The Angels immediately called police, who took everyone to the
Midtown North precinct station, she said.
   McConville, however, said the incident occurred about 9:20 p.m.
Sunday.
   John Johnson, 24, of New York, told police he was surrounded by
12 Angels and refused to leave the area when they ordered him out.
Johnson, according to McConville, was bumped by an Angel and then
``took out a pocket knife and held it at his side for protection.''
   When police arrived, they arrested Johnson and two Angels, Loren
Gonzalez, 21, of Milwaukee, and David Baldwin, 18, of Newark, N.J.
The three were charged with menacing and the Angels also were
charged with harassing.
   In Saturday's incident, Illya Lichtenberg, 16, of Verona, N.J.,
was hit in the head with a bottle and stabbed in the chest during a
confrontation between about 15 Angels and 15 other people, police
said.
   Lichtenberg was in critical condition Monday at St. Vincent's
Hospital after surgery. A 25-year-old man has been charged with
attempted murder in the incident.
