<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FriendshipFlight     06-13 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Friendship Flight,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Island-Hopping Flight Aims To Break Cold War Barriers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be topped with detail after landing in Provideniya,
U.S.S.R</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOME, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Alaska Airlines Boeing 737 jet crossed
the ice-clogged Bering Strait on Monday in a short but historic
flight aimed at bridging 40 years of wariness and distrust between
the United States and the Soviet Union.
   The one-time charter ``friendship flight'' to the eastern
Siberia port of Provideniya from the western Alaska town of Nome
was seen as a tentative first step in thawing relations and
reuniting Eskimo families split when the Iron Curtain slammed shut
during the Cold War in 1948.
   The border between Alaska and the Soviet Union was closed first
by the United States, and then by the Soviets.
   Monday's 40-minute flight was approved by the Soviets with
little notice earlier this month after two years of work by
Alaskans promoting the idea.
   Eighty government officials, Eskimos and journalists were booked
aboard the jet making the 225-mile flight. It left Nome shortly
after 3 p.m. EDT.
   Provideniya officials planned to entertain the visitors with
tours, a banquet and a trip to an outlying native village.
   The flight is part of a broader effort being mounted by Alaska
business leaders, educators, and state officials to improve the
state's relations with the Soviet Union.
   The flight was the dream of James Stimpfle, a Nome real estate
agent seeking ways to improve Nome's economy. He envisions Nome as
an economic and cultural center for both sides of the Bering Strait.
   Alaska Airlines is seeking permission to follow the one-time
charter with twice-weekly tourist excursions between Nome and
Provideniya.
   While peaceful interactions begin to flourish, military interest
in Alaska and Siberia also runs high. The U.S. Navy has increased
its emphasis on a strong defense in the North Pacific and Bering
Sea, and U.S. fighter jets last year intercepted a record number of
Soviet military aircraft off Alaska's coasts.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Editors: David Foster is the AP's regional correspondent
covering the Northwest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
