<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 2009EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Phobias-NavyDeath     06-13 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phobias-Navy Death,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Needs Better Recruit Screening for Phobias, Congressman Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tragedies like the death of a Navy recruit
during a training program could be avoided if the Pentagon did a
better job of screening recruits for potential mental health
problems, Rep. Michael Bilirakis said Monday.
   ``We need to find out what steps are being taken by the military
to deal with this very serious problem of phobias,'' the Florida
Democrat told a news conference.
   On Monday he wrote to Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci
seeking detailed information about how the Pentagon screens
recruits for potential mental health problems. Carlucci's office
said the secretary would not have any comment because the letter
hadn't yet been received.
   Bilirakis' letter referred to the March 2 death of Airman
Recruit Lee Mirecki, 19, of Appleton, Wis., who drowned during an
elite rescue swimmer training program at the Pensacola, Fla., Naval
Air Station.
   A Navy investigator is now deliberating whether five swimming
instructors and a commanding officer should be court-martialed
because force was used to stop Mirecki from leaving the pool where
he drowned.
   Testimony at a Navy preliminary hearing indicated Mirecki had a
phobia about being pulled under water.
   Bilirakis held his news conference along with members of the
Phobic Society of America, who said Mirecki's case highlights the
dangers of phobias.
   Phobias are defined as persistent, irrational fears of a
specific object, activity or situation which results in a
compelling desire by an individual to avoid the fearful stimulus.
   Bilirikis, citing statistics from the National Institutes of
Mental Health, said ``phobias are the number one mental disorder in
this nation and one out of every eight people suffer from some sort
of phobia.''
   According to Bilirakis, Mirecki's death may have been avoided
had his phobia been recognized before he entered the training
program.
   Bilirakis said nothing on the military medical forms filled out
by recruits addresses phobias. ``Additionally, I am told there is
nothing in the military medical procedures requiring a doctor to
ask about specific mental health disorders at all.''
</TEXT>
