<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1754EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-USDA-Coca     06-13 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USDA-Coca,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USDA Greenhouse is Site of Battle in Federal War on Cocaine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Department researchers are growing
coca plants in a $1 million-a-year search for ways to eradicate
South American crops destined for processing into cocaine,
officials said Monday.
   Between 400 and 600 plants are being grown at two USDA research
sites, one a greenhouse near Washington and the other an outdoor
location in an undisclosed, warm-weather area, said Dr. Edward B.
Knipling, associate deputy administrator for the Agricultural
Research Service's national program staff.
   Knipling said all of the plants used in the experiment are
incinerated afterward and that no cocaine is produced from them.
   Researchers earlier had grown opium poppies in Thailand and
marijuana in the United States as part of USDA's research into ways
to stem production of narcotics. The priority changed two years ago
because of growing use by Americans of cocaine and crack, a cocaine
derivative, Knipling said.
   The project was spotlighted in a report published in The New
York Times on Sunday.
   Knipling estimated the cost of the program at about $1 million a
year. He said part of the funds come from the research service's
regular budget and the rest by the State Department.
   ``There is absolutely none being developed into cocaine,''
Knipling said. `` ... It's not possible, not at our agricultural
facilities.''
   He confirmed that the seeds were brought to the United States
from South America and said a number of herbicides have been tested
for use against the plant.
   The chief herbicide recommended to the State Department for use
against coca is tebutherion, a product manufactured by Eli Lilly &
Co. of Indianapolis under the trade name Spike. Knipling said it is
used in considerable quantities in the United States to clear brush
in areas where food crops do not grow.
   Guards, alarms and wire fences are being used to keep out
intruders at the USDA installations, Knipling said. He refused to
disclose the precise whereabouts of either of the growing sites.
   The issue first surfaced when the former head of the project,
Walter Gentner, said in interviews that he had resigned in April to
protest what he described as the failure of the Agriculture and
State departments to examine adequately the potential dangers from
use of the herbicide.
   Knipling said there had been considerable pressure from various
places in the administration to get on with approval of Spike for
use against coca.
   ``We've been under an extensive sense of urgency coming from the
State Department and, of course, the White House, itself, that this
is a high-priority project,'' he said.
   Knipling said there had been ``frequent calls and visits'' to
the research service that intensified the pressure. He also said it
was intensified by demands from Congress and the public for action
to combat drugs.
   Knipling contended that illicit cocaine production in South
America is doing far more to endanger the environment than would
use of tebutherion. He said there was little doubt that the coca
leaves were being heavily sprayed with pesticides, which could
cause harm.
   Moreover, he said, sulfuric acid and other chemicals being used
to process the coca into cocaine are undoubtedly dumped into
streams when the manufacturing process is over.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
