<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Roberson     06-13 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Roberson,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Funeral For Stuntman Who Took Fall For John Wayne, Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends and relatives gathered Monday to bury
veteran movie stunt man Charles H. Roberson, who for decades took
falls for John Wayne and even broke limbs on behalf of the Duke.
   Roberson, 69, died of cancer last Wednesday at Mercy Hospital in
Bakersfield.
   Roberson first doubled for Wayne in the 1949 film ``The Fighting
Kentuckian,'' and he retired in 1976 after working with Wayne on
the actor's final film, ``The Shootist.''
   ``He could do any stunt I could do. But the money people
couldn't afford to let him get hurt, so I was the one who ended up
in stitches,'' Roberson said in a 1984 interview.
   During nearly three decades of stunts for Wayne, Roberson
cracked his back, twisted an ankle and broke ribs and arms.
   He also did stunt work for Gregory Peck, Jeff Chandler, Clark
Gable and Ronald Reagan, who sent him a telegram after he became
ill last October.
   After retirement, Roberson raised thoroughbred horses on his
ranch south of Bakersfield.
   He also was the subject of a book titled ``The Fall Guy,'' by
Bodie Thoene, which later was the basis of the television series by
the same name starring Lee Majors.
   ``He was known as the finest stunt man in Hollywood and also the
best director of action scenes,'' said Ms. Thoene, of Glennville.
``He's one of the last of them. There aren't too many left like
him.''
   Roberson is survived by his wife, Dolly Mae Roberson, four
daughters, a sister and several grandchildren.
</TEXT>
