<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 2019EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RunwayAccident 1stLd-Writethru   06-13 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Runway Accident, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0722,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Probe Jetliner's Skid Off Runway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-9 ``There was'' with two grafs of comment from
airline; picking up 10th graf pvs ``Port of...'' SUBS final graf to
UPDATE with information about canceled flights.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY McDONALD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators examined an Alaska Airlines
jetliner Monday and interviewed crew members to learn why it veered
from a runway and skidded to a stop in mud after landing at
Seattle-Tacoma International Airport.
   Four people were slightly injured Sunday night aboard the Boeing
727-200, which remained overnight in the grassy strip between the
airport's parallel runways.
   The 75 passengers and seven crew members aboard Flight 187 from
Tucson, Ariz., used emergency chutes to evacuate as a precaution,
airport officials said.
   ``It was a fairly normal flight until we landed,'' said
passenger Marlene Davies, 52, from nearby Kent. ``I saw the white
line and we kept going over it. And then I saw smoke or dust or
something. It was very scary.''
   ``It seemed to me like about 30 seconds from the time we stopped
to the time the stewardess threw the door open and yelled to
evacuate,'' she said.
   Once out of the plane, ``We ran as fast as we could to the
runway we had just been on,'' said passenger Katherine Tune of
Seattle. ``We all congregated and the emergency crews gathered.''
   The jet was towed Monday morning to an airport hangar where the
National Transportation Safety Board began its probe of the
accident. A representative of Seattle-based Boeing was assisting,
the jet manufacturer said.
   ``Upon examination of the airplane after it came to rest in the
grassy area, the left tire of the two-tire front nose assembly gear
was flat,'' said Dave Marriott, a spokesman for the Seattle-based
Alaska Airlines.
   ``Whether it was flat before they landed, flat on impact or flat
after that is still being looked into,'' he said.
   Port of Seattle spokesman John Eliadis said the nose of the
plane stopped about 400 feet from the runway, and investigators
were checking to see whether the plane might have blown a tire upon
landing or possibly struck some debris on the runway.
   Gwen Gause, an NTSB staff assistant in Seattle, said the plane's
nose wheel had to be dug out of mud before the plane could be
moved. There was no other visible damage to the plane, she said.
   Ms. Gause said it may take months to determine the cause of the
accident.
   Margo Spellman, airport spokeswoman, said two passenger
complained of back pain were treated at area hospitals. A third
person had a bruised knee and a fourth suffered a sprained ankle,
Ms. Spellman said.
   The flight originated in Tucson and made stops in Phoenix and
Portland, Marriott said. Marriott said the airline canceled four
flights Monday between Seattle and various California airports
because the plane was taken out of service, but expected to operate
those flights on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
