<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     06-13 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Cruiser Back to Work After Maintenance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A superpowerful American missile cruiser
returned to patrol duty in the Persian Gulf Monday after being
pulled off for what a U.S. Navy spokesman said was maintenance.
   The 9,400-ton USS Vincennes was taken off duty less than two
weeks after its arrival in the waterway May 28. It is the first of
the Navy's billion-dollar Aegis-type cruisers to be assigned to the
gulf.
   U.S. Navy officers say the warship's multiple-mission,
computer-linked radar and weapons system vastly expands the Navy's
air and sea surveillance capabilities.
   The Navy spokesman, Lt. Cmdr. Brad Goforth, said the Vincennes
was withdrawn for ``maintenance upkeep,'' but refused for security
reasons to say what was the exact nature of the problem.
   The ship was out of action for about three days, other Navy
sources said.
   Those sources, who spoke on condition of not being identified,
said the ship's ``phased-array'' radar system was involved, but
could give no other details, and this could not be verified. Unlike
standard radar, the system is able to constantly monitor scores of
contacts simultaneously.
   In its first week in the gulf, the Vincennes had a near
encounter with an Iranian frigate that intercepted, boarded and
then escorted away the Cypriot-flag freighter Vevey, suspected of
carrying war-related cargo.
   The cruiser followed the detained ship to the edge of Iran's
declared ``war-exclusion zone'' in hopes of detecting some signal
from the Vevey that would justify its intervention, but neither saw
nor heard any, U.S. officers said.
   Meanwhile, Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit said an
American-owned supertanker, attacked by Iranian gunboats Saturday,
would continue to Singapore as planned after repairs at a United
Arab Emirates shipyard.
   The 258,979-ton Esso Demetia, owned by the Exxon Corp. and
sailing under the British flag, had eight holes in its hull from
rocket-propelled grenades, Lloyd's said.
   Fires broke out but were controlled, Lloyd's said. There were no
casualties.
   The London-based maritime agency, which monitors commercial
shipping worldwide, said the ship now is anchored off Bahrain and
will sail to Fujairah, on the Gulf of Oman, for repairs. Later it
will head for Singapore, its original destination, with its cargo
of Saudi Arabian crude.
   The raid took place about 45 miles off Saudi Arabia, in an area
where no such attacks are rare, according to U.S. Navy officials
and gulf-based shipping executives. All these sources spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Of interest to Navy intelligence was how the two or three armed
speedboats could appear in daylight and just as quickly vanish in
the western gulf, about 60 miles off Iran and the same distance
from Iranian-held Farsi Island. The island is known as an operating
base for the speedboat-borne Revolutionary Guards in the northern
gulf.
   U.S. forces maintain a careful watch on shipping activity in the
gulf, including small- and medium-sized craft that might be used
for minelaying or as ``mother ships'' for the speedboats.
   In land and air action in the nearly 8-year-old war between Iran
and Iraq, Iran said its forces drove into southern Iraq behind
helicopter gunships on Monday, recapturing some of the territory
east of Basra they lost three weeks ago. Iraq said it repulsed the
invaders.
   Iran claimed Iraqi planes dropped chemical bombs on the
attackers but said chemical warfare units neutralized the poison
gas and kept casualties to a minimum.
</TEXT>
