<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Communists     06-13 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Communists,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Natta Resigns As Secretary Of Italy's Communist Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alessandro Natta, who led the Communist Party to its
recent election defeats, resigned Monday citing reasons of health.
   Natta, 70, had a heart attack in April. He had led the largest
Communist Party in the West since the death of party chief Enrico
Berlinguer in 1984.
   Achille Occhetto, 51, the deputy party secretary, is expected to
succeed Natta. Although the Communists are Italy's second-largest
party, they been excluded from the national government since 1947.
   Natta said in a letter of resignation to the Central Committee
and watchdog Central Control Commission that the party faces
difficult tasks and cannot be ``subordinate'' to his recuperation.
   The letter was made available to journalists.
   Upon taking power, Natta promised to follow the policies of
Berlinguer, who proclaimed the party's independence from Moscowk,
but lacked the appeal of Berlinguer, who led the party to 34.4
percent of the vote in 1976 _ just 4 percent less than the dominant
Christian Democrats.
   Under Natta's leadership in June 1987, the party suffered its
worse election defeat in 20 years, winning 26.6 percent of the vote
for the Chamber of Deputies. It now has 177 seats in the 630-seat
chamber.
   In recent local elections, the party got 21.9 percent, a large
decline from the 25.8 percent it received in the last local voting
in 1983.
</TEXT>
