<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Greece     06-13 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Greece,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premiers Have ``Very Friendly'' Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VOULIAGMENI, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prime ministers of rivals Greece
and Turkey held discussions ``in a very friendly atmosphere''
Monday of problems that only last year brought the two NATO allies
close to war.
   As they talked outside the capital, about 2,000 Greek Cypriot,
Armenian and Kurdish demonstrators in the city burned Turkish flags
outside the Turkish Embassy and shouted ``Fire for the Turkish
dogs!''
   Hundreds of helmeted riot police guarded the embassy building
but there were no clashes, witnesses said.
   No signs emerged of a breakthrough on the major disputes over
Cyprus and the Aegean Sea during Monday's one hour of talks between
Premiers Andreas Papandreou of Greece and Turgut Ozal of Turkey.
   Mesut Yilmaz, the But Turkish foreign minister, told reporters
later: ``The meeting was held in a very friendly atmosphere and all
bilateral problems and international issues were handled,''
   Ozal began a three-day visit to Greece on Monday, the first by a
Turkish premier in 36 years.
   Pro-government and opposition Greek newspapers both gave him a
cool reception.
   ``Frozen Smiles'' was the headline in 24 Hours, an independent
Athens daily. ``The country receives Ozal with a cold heart,'' said
the pro-government Avriani.
   In separate statements before the talks started, both leaders
made clear they did not expect immediate major advances on the main
disputes.
   On Monday night, Ozal was guest of honor at a dinner beside the
the swimming pool of a seaside hotel in Vouliagmeni, outside
Athens, where he and Papandreou are staying.
   ``There is no room for petty designs, one-sided gains and
short-sighted tactics,'' Ozal said in his speech, in an apparent
reference to Greek demands that Turkish troops leave Cyprus.
   Papandreou said in his speech he had revived an earlier proposal
for demilitarization of the Mediterranean island and establishing a
joint Greek Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot police force.
   ``It's clear that progress in Greek-Turkish relations is
directly affected by the solution of the Cyprus problem ... and
this is directly linked with the withdrawal of troops from the
island,'' he said.
   Ozal will drive into downtown Athens on Tuesday to lay a wreath
at the Monument of the Unknown Soldier outside Parliament, then
hold more private talks with Papandreou in the evening.
   Ozal began his visit with an appeal for patience on the ``the
long road (to peace) on which we have started journeying.''
   ``We must have realistic expectations, otherwise the
disappointments to be suffered will take us away from our main
goal,'' he told reporters. ``The problems go back a long time and
as solutions were delayed some of these problems petrified and
prejudices increased.''
   When Ozal arrived at the airport, only a few red-and-white
Turkish flags were displayed and a Greek commando squad in
camouflage battle-dress formed the honor guard.
   The neighbors came to the brink of war in March 1987 over
oil-drilling rights in the Aegean seabed. The near-clash apparently
convinced Papandreou to alter his no-dialogue policy toward Turkey
and seek friendlier relations.
   Greece wants Turkey to pull its troops out of northern Cyprus
and agree on a joint appeal to the World Court to settle the Aegean
continental shelf dispute.
   Ozal says Turkey will not be pressured into withdrawing its
forces from Cyprus and prefers Greek-Turkish talks to solve the
Aegean problem. The soldiers were sent after a brief Greek-led coup
in July 1974.
</TEXT>
