<DOCNO> AP880613-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1954EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     06-13 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jaruzelski Appeals For Reconciliation, But Not With Solidarity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski
appealed Monday for national reconciliation and expressed
willingness to legalize new associations and cooperate with
``communities'' outside official life _ but not with Solidarity.
   ``We can talk to anyone, as long as he is not a client,
especially a paid one, of a foreign court,'' Jaruzelski said. He
referred to grants of $1 million the U.S. government gave to
Solidarity after it became the first free trade union federation in
the Soviet bloc.
   Jaruzelski gave the major policy address at the start of a
two-day meeting of the 230-member Central Committee of the Polish
United Workers' (Communist) Party. He is party first secretary and
president of the Council of State.
   Janusz Onyszkiewicz, national spokesman for the now outlawed
Solidarity labor federation, said in a telephone interview that any
claim that Solidarity is disloyal to Poland did not merit a
response. He noted that both Poland's Roman Catholic Church and the
communist government have accepted U.S. aid in the past and added,
``We are in very strange company.''
   It was the first Central Committee plenum since a series of
strikes between April 25 and May 10. Five factories were struck and
25 other plants endured brief stoppages or strike threats in the
strongest labor action since Solidarity was suspended in December
1981 and subsequently outlawed.
   Solidarity had been chartered by the government during
nationwide strikes in August 1980.
   Jaruzelski accused the leaders of the recent strikes of an
``almost pathological lack of responsibility'' and said they could
not be ``an objectively credible partner in dialogue.''
   But he said authorities are ready to talk with critics who want
to improve the state.
   ``National reconciliation is a basic condition and one of the
goals of socialist renewal,'' Jaruzelski said. ``It is broader
today than in past years.''
   Jaruzelski said a planned new law on associations would lift
administrative restrictions and grant the associations more
freedom. In the meantime, officials should legally register new,
``socially justified'' groups, he said.
   He mentioned no groups specifically. Indications have emerged
that at least three suppressed groups _ the pro-private enterprise
Economic Society; the Polish chapter of the PEN writer's club and
the Dziekania political discussion club _ may soon be registered.
   About 300 mostly non-controversial private associations were
legalized last year, but applications of many other groups were not
approved, including local chapters of Solidarity and the
Independent Students Association.
   Jaruzelski said ``ideas and practices are crystalizing slowly''
for cooperation with what he called independent communities that
have refused to join PRON, the official national unity organization.
   He proposed a permanent wage-price commission with
representatives of labor, management and consumers that would seek
a social consensus for price increases. He said this would avoid
periodic across-the-board price increases like one this year and
instead aim at a floating system with prices evolving gradually.
   Jaruzelski noted that Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev will visit
Poland next month and said the trip will add a ``new, significant
chapter'' to Polish-Soviet relations.
</TEXT>
