<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-SpyCharges     06-13 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Spy Charges,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Prosecutor Files Charges Against Alleged KGB Agent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARLSRUHE, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet immigrant engineer has
been charged with spying for the KGB, authorities said Monday.
   The charges accuse 34-year-old Peter Friesen of providing the
Soviets with information about his job and trying to infiltrate a
West German political party, said chief federal prosecutor Kurt
Rebmann in a statement.
   He said Friesen was trained by the Soviet secret police and
intelligence agency in using coded messages before he emigrated to
West Germany in 1981.
   The statement said Friesen stopped his espionage activities in
November 1985 on KGB orders after West Germany's chief of
counter-espionage, Hans-Joachim Tiedge, defected to East Germany.
   Friesen was arrested in March along with six other suspected
Soviet KGB agents in what Rebmann said at the time was a major
crackdown on Soviet spying activity in West Germany.
   Alexander Prechtel, spokesman for the federal prosecutor's
office, on Monday declined to provide further details on Friesen's
case, including where he worked.
   No trial date was set, he said in a telephone interview.
   Five of the seven arrested remain in investigative custody.
Investigations against the other two are continuing although they
are no longer in custody, Prechtel said.
</TEXT>
