<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1956EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WhaleAttack     06-13 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Whale Attack,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yachtsman Rescued After Vessel Sunk By Whales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cargo ship on Monday rescued an English
yachtsman whose vessel sank after a herd of whales apparently
attacked the craft during a trans-Atlantic yacht race, the coast
guard said.
   A distress message received by the coast guard in Falmouth said
the yacht had come under attack by whales 1,000 miles west of the
southwest tip of England, the Defense Ministry said.
   David Sellings, 41, who was competing in the Carlsberg
single-handed trans-Atlantic race, told rescuers the 25-foot yacht
sank in seconds but that he managed to recover his dinghy and set
off a distress beacon.
   Sellings escaped unhurt, the coast guard said.
   A Royal Air Force Nimrod reconnaisance plane spotted the dinghy
and, after eight hours, Sellings was picked up by the West German
coaster Bridgwater. He was expected to return to Liverpool on the
ship Friday.
   A coast guard spokesman said about 20 whales apparently attacked
the yacht and may have been protecting their young.
   ``It is very unusual for whales to attack a boat, but not
unknown,'' said the spokesman, who requested anonymity.
   The trans-Atlantic race from Plymouth on the south coast of
England to Newport, R.I., began June 9. Eleven of the 94 vessels
have dropped out to date.
