<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Portugal-Pessoa     06-13 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Portugal-Pessoa,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lisbon Engulfed in Celebrations Marking Centenary of Poet's Birth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>by PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acrobats, films, art exhibits, folk
songs and spirited public readings on Monday celebrated the 100th
birthday of Portugal's most acclaimed poet of the century, Fernando
Pessoa.
   ``A simple man who became a symbol of universal man,'' Lisbon
Mayor Nuno Krus Abecassis said of Pessoa at the unveiling of a
statue of the poet outside one of Pessoa's favorite cafes in the
Portuguese capital. Pessoa died in 1935 at the age of 47.
   Hundreds of people gathered in the plaza in front of the
Brasileira cafe for the ceremony, including President Mario Soares
aning writers.
   The bronze figure of Pessoa is seated at a table identical to
those of the Brasileira a few feet away and the sculpture includes
an empty seat for a passerby to join the poet.
   In the afternoon there d dozens of leadagain were hundreds of people
outside the
house where Pessoa was born as dozens of doves were released at
3:20 p.m., marking the time of the poet's birth in 1888.
   In a touch that might have brought a smile from the taciturn
Pessoa, a tape recording of church bells was played at the same
moment. Officials said the bells in nearby churches that were to
ring in Pessoa's honor were found to be no longer functional.
   Performers read from Pessoa's works, acted out skitguages
including Chinese, Japanese, Bulgarian, and Estonian.
</TEXT>
