<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Afghanistan     06-13 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Mediator Says Soviets Leaving Afghanistan `Faster Than
Expected</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One name Najib is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet troops are leaving Afghanistan
``faster than we all expected,'' the U.N. mediator who negotiated
the withdrawal said Monday.
   Diego Cordovez refused to say how many Red Army troops have
pulled out since the Geneva Accord took effect May 15.
   He also said he is disturbed by allegations the pact is being
violated.
   The Soviets said they had 100,300 troops in Afghanistan as of
May 15 and would withdraw one-fourth of them by early June. Western
intelligence agencies had estimated Soviet troop strength as up to
115,000.
   In Moscow, Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Afghan
President Najib on Monday spoke of ``resolute retaliatory
measures'' if Pakistan continues to aid Moslem guerrillas battling
the Kabul regime.
   The warning was the first of its kind directly from Gorbachev.
It came as sources in Pakistan said Soviet forces had returned to
some cities in eastern Afghanistan to fight guerrillas who raided
posts defended by Afghan troops.
   Najib and Gorbachev distributed a joint statement over the
official Soviet news agency Tass saying: ``The Soviet Union and
Afghanistan believed that the U.N. Mission monitoring compliance
with the Geneva accords would adopt ... effective measures to curb
the practice (of Pakistan's aiding the guerrillas) which, if
continued would make it necessary to undertake the most resolute
retaliatory steps.''
   Last week, Najib accused Pakistan of violating the accords by
aiding the guerrillas and Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze said Moscow might have to review its troop withdrawal
schedule.
   Both were in New York last to attend a special U.N. conference
on disarmament.
   Pakistan, in turn, has accused Afghanistan of intruding on its
airspace and territory.
   Pakistan's U.N. ambassador, S. Shah Nawaz, said Monday that
``the world will not be surprised if a crumbing (Afghan) regime
makes a desperate bid to retain the protective umbrella of foreign
troops, the withdrawal of which is the central element of the
Geneva Accords.''
   He addressed the 159-nation General Assembly during a special
session on disarmament.
   Cordovez said later in a news conference: ``Let me say that
nothing that has happened was not foreseen in the Geneva accords.
It is unfortunate that we have encountered difficulties, and I am
... concerned about them.''
   He said the accord ``envisages violations'' and has procedures
to deal with them.
   ``It was also expected, of course, that some people would make a
lot of noise,'' said the U.N. official.
   ``The withdrawal has been going on very well ... faster than we
all expected, and when people now talk about (the withdrawal)
slowing down, I would say, in reference to what? The agreement
provides simply that 50 percent of the troops should be out by the
15th of August.
   Cordovez said he would visit Afghanistan and Pakistan at the end
of the month to review the implementation of the Geneva accords.
   Soviet troops first entered Afghanistan at the end of 1979 to
support its Marxist government.
   The United Nations mediated the accord between Afghanistan and
Pakistan aimed at restoring peace in Afghanistan, with the United
States and Soviet Union signing as guarantors of the pact. Pakistan
adjoins Afghanistan, is headquarters for all major Afghan guerrilla
organizations and shelters about 3.5 million Afghan refugees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
