<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Awad-Profile     06-13 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Awad-Profile,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Activist First Exposed To Passive Resistance In U.S. Civil Rights
Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mubarak Awad, the Arab-American advocate of
non-violent protest who was deported by Israel on Monday, got his
first taste of passive resistance as a student in the American
South during the early 1960s.
   When he returned home to Jerusalem in 1983 after 13 years in the
United States, Awad applied these ideas to the Arab-Israeli
conflict, calling for civil disobedience to protest Israeli
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Awad remained largely unknown until Israeli authorities ordered
him deported last month, saying he played a role in inciting the
Arab uprising that began last Dec.8.
   ``He openly and intensely acts against Israeli control,'' read a
decision last week by the Israeli Supreme Court upholding the
deportation order.
   His case drew worldwide attention and U.S. Secretary of State
George P. Shultz tried to intercede on his behalf.
   Awad's American-born wife, Nancy Nye, said her husband never
tried to be a leader, but she noted his ideas for boycotts of
Israeli products and non-payment of taxes are being used in the
uprising.
   ``If you read an article Mubarak wrote in 1983 and read today's
underground leaflets, it's almost as if he envisioned what was
going to happen,'' she said in a telephone interview.
   Ms. Nye, however, has denied Israeli charges that her husband
wrote leaflets advocating violence. He has been criticized by
Israelis for not speaking out against violent attacks by
Palestinian militants.
   Awad, a soft-spoken man with graying, curly hair, said in a
statement addressing Israel's government last week: ``You have the
power, the law and the gun pointing in my face. I am armed with
hope, truth and non-violence.''
   Awad was born in Jerusalem on Aug. 22, 1943, the fifth of seven
children of a Greek Orthodox father and a Protestant mother.
   His father was killed by a stray bullet near his home during the
1948 Middle East war. Awad and his siblings were sent to orphanages
and boarding schools while his mother worked as a nurse.
   Awad graduated from an Anglican school in Jerusalem and in the
early 1960s went to Lee College, a Pentecostal school in Cleveland,
Tenn., intending to become a minister.
   But Ms. Nye said Awad returned to Jerusalem after a little more
than a year, repelled by the racial discrimination he saw.
   ``But there he first became interested in Martin Luther King Jr.
and the methods of resistance he advocated,'' Ms. Nye said.
   ``This was reinforced by his education at a Mennonite school,''
she said. ``He participated in anti-war demonstrations in America,
and from there it was just a natural progression.''
   Awad taught for several years, then in 1970 he returned to
United States to study at Bluffton College, a Mennonite school in
Bluffton, Ohio.
   Later, he earned a master's degree in counseling from St.
Francis College, a Catholic institution in Fort Wayne, Ind., and a
doctorate from the International Graduate School in St. Louis.
   In January 1978, he launched the Ohio Youth Advocate Program,
which offered community service programs for troubled youths.
   Awad returned to Jerusalem in 1983 and two years later founded
the Palestinian Center for Non-Violence. He lectured on civil
disobedience, counseled teachers against corporal punishment and
planted olive trees in West Bank villages to underscore the Arabs'
claim to the land.
</TEXT>
