<DOCNO> AP880613-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1957EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ControversialNominee     06-13 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Controversial Nominee,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judgeship Nominee Accused of Keeping Liens `Hanging Over a Dying
Man'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's nominee for a California
judgeship was accused at a Senate hearing Monday of keeping
property liens ``hanging over a dying man'' in a lawsuit filed by
the U.S. Olympic Committee.
   Vaughn R. Walker, nominated for a U.S. district court judgeship
for northern California, sharply disagreed with the statement by
the attorney who opposed him in the trademark infringement case.
   Walker told the Senate Judiciary Committee at his confirmation
hearing there was ``nothing malicious'' in his representation of
the USOC against the late Tom Waddell, an AIDS victim who spent the
last years of his life trying to organize athletic games he wanted
to call the ``Gay Olympics.''
   The nominee was among 13 current or former judicial candidates
listed by Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C. as victims of a Democratic
plot to delay Reagan's judgeship nominees in the waning days of his
administration.
   Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., who presided at the hearing, said
many of the delays were caused by the Justice Department's
tardiness in responding to committee information requests on
nominees.
   Other delays resulted because Democrats wanted to investigate
nominees thoroughly ``before they are given a lifetime charter to
sit in judgment on the rights and liberties of the American people,
not afterwards,'' Leahy said.
   There were two major issues in Walker's nomination: his
membership in San Francisco's Olympic Club, which has few black
members and does not allow its female members to vote; and his
conduct in representing the Olympic committee, a case in which the
Supreme Court eventually ruled the USOC had exclusive use of the
Olympic name and the gay organization could not use it.
   Walker said he has been working from within to get the Olympic
Club to change its policies, with some recent success.
   He promised to resign if current efforts to recruit minorities
and allow full voting rights to women become stalled. Supreme Court
Justice Anthony Kennedy resigned from the same club because he
disagreed with the policies toward minorities and women.
   In the Olympic case, Walker was retained by the USOC in 1984 to
prevent use of the ``Gay Olympics'' name. A U.S. district judge
ordered that Waddell _ a former U.S. Olympic decathlon athlete _
and a gay organization were liable for $96,000 in attorneys fees,
and Walker slapped liens against Waddell's home and other property
in an effort to collect the money.
   The liens were not removed until six days after Waddell's death
due to AIDS in July 1987.
   Walker defended his actions, saying a federal appellate court
ruling in the case automatically dissolved the liens. But the
attorney for Waddell, Mary Dunlap, told the committee that she and
Waddell's estate lawyer were unable to get the liens removed
without Walker's agreement, which he refused to give.
   She said Walker left the liens ``hanging over a dying man at the
time he needed to know his daughter would inherit his estate.''
   Ms. Dunlap contended that Walker ``misrepresented the facts'' to
the committee by telling senators that she had done nothing to
obtain an order removing the liens. Ms. Dunlap said that she and
Waddell's estate lawyer repeatedly tried without success to get
Walker to sign a release.
   Walker has drawn opposition from San Francisco's gay community
and the city's Board of Supervisors, which voted unanimously
against the nomination. His main supporter, Republican Sen. Pete
Wilson of California, told the committee:
   ``What principle of American jurisprudence is more fundamental
than that due process of the law requires that however unpopular a
client, that client and that client's cause of action are entitled
to be represented by competent counsel.''
   Walker used similar language in defending himself, telling
Leahy, ``I was perfectly aware of how unpopular the position was.''
But he added that the committee should be looking for judicial
candidates ``willing to take stands'' that are legally correct,
``even though they may be unpopular.''
   Walker said the Olympic committee held firm on the lien, adding
it did so in the hope that the gay organization working with
Waddell _ San Francisco Arts and Athletics _ would raise the money
for the attorney fees.
   ``The client made the decision it had the right to recover the
cost of the suit. That was a perfectly legitimate decision on their
part,'' Walker said, adding, ``I was not at liberty'' to go against
his client.
   He added that in his opinion, ``The liens were ineffective after
the court of appeals judgment'' which vacated them.
   If that were so, Leahy asked, ``Why didn't you sign the
release?''
   ``The client wanted to pursue it,'' Walker said.
</TEXT>
