<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-SpyCharge 1stLd-Writethru a0736 06-13 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Spy Charge, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0736,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadian Charged With Obtaining Classified U.S. Military Documents</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 3 grafs SUB for grafs 3-4 pvs, The minister ... UPDATING with
CBC report and changes to conform. Picks up 5th graf pvs, ``But we
...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian man has been arrested and charged with
obtaining classified U.S. military documents that could have been
useful to the Soviet Union or East bloc countries, the government
announced Monday.
   Stephen Joseph Ratkai, 25, was arrested Saturday in St. John's,
Newfoundland, following an investigation by the Canadian Security
Intelligence Service, the Royal Canadian Mounted Police and U.S.
Navy intelligence, according to Solicitor General James Kelleher.
   The minister declined to say if Ratkai actually passed or tried
to pass the documents to anyone, but he said the offense involved a
``foreign agent.'' He said that information would come out in court.
   Kelleher gave no details of the contents of the documents. The
Canadian Broadcasting Corp. in a television report said the papers
involved operations at the U.S. naval base at Argentia,
Newfoundland, where U.S. and Canadian military forces cooperate in
monitoring the movements of Soviet submarines.
   The solicitor general said no Soviet diplomats or citizens
residing in Canada were involved ``to our knowledge.''
   ``But we believe the information _ the documents _ would be
useful to the Soviet Union and-or other East bloc countries,''
Kelleher said.
   He said Ratkai was not a member of the Canadian armed forces or
government but was believed to be a native-born Canadian citizen.
He gave no other details on Ratkai's background.
   Ratkai was charged under a section of the Official Secrets Act
that prohibits the gathering or passing of classified documents or
information that could be of use to a foreign power and could harm
the interests of Canada and its allies. The offense carries a
maximum penalty of 14 years in prison.
   Ratkai was arraigned in a St. John's court on Sunday and is
scheduled to appear in court again on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
