<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nigeria-Waste     06-13 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nigeria-Waste,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Threatens Execution of Those Dumping Toxic Wastes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military government said Monday it
will execute anyone convicted of involvement in dumping foreign
toxic waste in Nigeria.
   Duro Onabule, spokesman for President Ibrahim Babangida, said
the death penalty also might apply to foreigners connected with the
dumping of more than 2,000 tons of chemical waste near the town of
Koko, including poisonous and radioactive material. Koko is 150
miles southeast of Lagos, capital of this West African nation.
   Prince Tony Momoh, the information minister, said at a separate
news conference that 15 people had been arrested in the Koko
dumping. He did not identify them but said an Italian who directed
the operation, Gianfranco Raffaelli, fled the country after
newspapers reported the dumping.
   ``There will be no mercy on this issue,'' Onabule told
reporters. ``We would rather do away with 20 Nigerians, stupid
Nigerians, than allow them to endanger the lives of millions of
Nigerians and fellow Africans.''
   He said the government seized the land on which the waste was
dumped.
   Last Friday the government said it had seized an Italian ship
that would be forced to remove the waste and recalled its
ambassador from Italy. An Italian firm was accused of dumping the
waste for European companies.
   Police guarding the site in Bendel state were withdrawn Sunday
for their own safety, the Nes Agency of Nigeria reported. It said
confirmation by chemists that the waste included poisonous
substances prompted removal of the policemen, who had been
stationed around the site to keep the public away.
   Scientists urged anyone who had been near the site to have a
medical examination.
   Attempts by European and American companies to dump toxic waste
in West Africa have provoked protests in recent weeks.
   Five Congolese, including three senior government officials,
were arrested after a dumping scheme was discovered there. Guinea
arrested a Norwegian businessman and charged him with complicity in
dumping American waste on an island near the capital, Conakry.
   Several other countries said they had refused lucrative offers
from Western companies seeking permission to dump chemical waste.
</TEXT>
