<1ST_LINE>r i AM-US-Greece 1stLd-Writethru a0675 06-13 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Greece, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Washington</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Urges Extradition of Alleged Palestinian Terrorist</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with new info Greek response and changes
to conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A district attorney has asked for more
information in his examination of a U.S. request for extradition of
a Palestinian accused in the bombings of two American jetliners,
judicial sources said Monday.
   They said the request for Mohammed Rashid's extradition ``wasn't
backed by hard enough evidence that would support opening
extradition proceedings.''
   District Attorney Elias Spyropoulos, who is handling the case,
told U.S. authorities Greek law sets a two-month time limit for
providing needed information in extradition requests, according to
the sources, who spoke on condition they not be identified.
   ``What the Americans have so far provided won't do, and if the
additional evidence hasn't landed on the district attorney's two
months from now, the proceedings can't be pursued,'' one source
said.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said in Washington on
Monday that the United States asked Greece for the immediate
extradition of Rashid, ``a Palestinian terrorist wanted in
connection'' with the August 1982 explosion aboard a Pan American
World Airways passenger jet in Hawaii. The blast killed one person
and wounded 15.
   Redman said the United States was heartened by the Greek
government's June 7 statement saying it was dedicated to the
international fight against terrorism.
   ``We strongly believe that the most effective way to fight
terrorism in this case is to expeditiously begin extradition
proceedings against Rashid,'' he added.
   It was the first time the Reagan administration publicly
acknowledged it was seeking Rashid, 34. American officials admitted
privately last week that they were seeking Rashid's extradition but
declined to make the case public, citing the delicacy of the
negotiations.
   Rashid was arrested at the Athens Airport June 1 by Greek police
acting on information from the United States, according to police.
   U.S. officials said last week Rashid also is wanted in
connection with a 1986 explosion aboard a Trans World Airlines
plane flying over Greece in which four people were killed. Redman
did not mention that case in his brief statement on Rashid.
   The U.S. decision to publicly comment on the case came after a
Greek security official in Athens said earlier Monday that Greece
would try Rashid on the charge of using a false Syrian passport to
enter the country.
   If convicted on that count, Rashid could be given a jail term of
1{ to two years to be served before an extradition hearing took
place, said the security official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Government spokesman Yiannis Roubatis declined to comment on the
case.
   Greece has followed a similar procedure in delaying extradition
proceedings until a suspect served a misdemeanor sentence.
   A Jordanian arrested at the Greek-Turkish border in 1982 is
still awaiting extradition to Italy, where he is wanted for
allegedly plotting an attack at a Rome synagogue that killed a boy.
   The Jordanian, Abdel Osama Al-Zomor, served a 20-month sentence
for smuggling explosives before the extradition request was heard.
Although the request eventually was approved by the Supreme Court,
Al-Zomor was sentenced again for being found in possession of an
illegal weapon in his prison cell and remains in Greece.
   Premier Andreas Papandreou's Socialist government, which has
good relations with the Palestine Liberation Organization, has been
accused of being lax in fighting terrorism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
