<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-PlaneCrash     06-13 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Plane Crash,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eight Die In Plane Crash, Second Air Tragedy In Two Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PLATA, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight people died when a private
plane with engine trouble crashed while trying to make an emergency
landing Monday night. It was the country's second fatal air
accident in as many days.
   Air authorities in La Plata, 30 miles south of the capital
Buenos Aires, said the pilot of the Havilland Dove twin-engine
craft told the control tower he was having problems with one engine.
   He requested emergency landing rights, which were immediately
granted, officials said.
   But the plane crashed in Arana, a community five miles from the
airport, police at the scene said.
   Eight bodies were recovered, including that of a police
inspector and two children, ages eight and nine, police said. The
ninth victim was taken to a local hospital in serious condition,
police said.
   On Sunday, an Austral Air Lines DC-9 jetliner smashed into a
hillside in heavy fog and burst into flames outside Posadas in
northeastern Argentina. All 22 aboard were killed.
   The cause of that fiery accident, which claimed the lives of 15
passengers and seven crew members, is under investigation. Two of
the victims were Japanese and a third was French.
   Austral is a private carrier bought last year from the state and
competes with the government carrier Aerolineas Argentinas on
domestic routes.
</TEXT>
