<DOCNO> AP880613-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 2137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-USBusiness     06-13 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-US Business,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China and U.S. To Hold Biggest-Ever Business Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Chinese officials already have been turned
away at the door while others will come laden with gifts and
promises of banquets to the biggest business conference ever held
between the United States and China.
   Nearly 1,000 Americans from 600 mostly smaller and medium-sized
businesses are to attend the June 20-23 U.S. Joint Session on
Industry, Trade and Economic Development at the Great Hall of the
People.
   They will discuss investment opportunities with about 800
Chinese officials from 22 provinces and municipalities.
   The U.S. Embassy's commercial officer, Dennis Barnes, said it
will be the first time so many smaller U.S. companies visit China,
a nation they previously avoided because of the risks involved.
   The Chinese will try to convince the Americans they are
eliminating investment risks, such as difficulty in repatriating
profits, inadequate energy supplies, red tape, corruption and
insufficient say over personnel matters.
   The event is sponsored by the China Association of Science and
Technology and People-to-People International, a Spokane, Wash.,
group founded in 1956 by President Dwight Eisenhower.
   Wu Ganmei, organizer of the seminar, said Chinese trying to
promote their respective regions for investment will set up about
100 booths in the Great Hall, the political center of China.
   She said about 30 cities have invited the American business
executives to come for first-hand looks in post-seminar tours.
   ``We heard that the Soviet Union and the United States had the
same kind of meeting and (Soviet leader Mikhail) Gorbachev talked
for 52 minutes. Well, ours is going to be bigger,'' Ms. Wu said.
   China is now eagerly courting foreign investors in its drive for
rapid economic development. The government has encouraged
more-developed coastal areas in particular to set up
export-oriented industries with the help of foreign money.
   According to Chinese statistics, U.S. businesses contracted for
407 joint ventures and pledged investment of $3.1 billion as of the
end of last year. That figure is second only to the amount invested
by Hong Kong.
   Ms. Wu said 95 percent of the Americans to attend the seminar
will be coming to China for the first time, and Chinese are
scrambling to be at the head of the line to greet them.
   Initially, she said, they planned to limit participation to
representatives from coastal provinces, but later, under strong
pressure, expanded to let in the industrial city of Wuhan and
Sichuan province, home of senior leader Deng Xiaoping. Other
provinces asking to participate have been rejected.
   She said the mayor of Harbin, an industrial city in the
northeast, insisted on coming with a 15-member delegation. ``We
told him no,'' she said, but added that in the end they may allow
the city to send four or five observers.
   Ms. Wu said their offices are already full of books, handouts
and gifts prepared by provinces to woo the Americans, and that
mayors and governors are vying to hold lunch and dinner banquets
for the potential investors.
   Sichuan province was spending $108,000 for gifts and investment
guides and one province had plans to charter an aircraft to
transport Americans to its cities.
   Among the U.S. representatives at the meeting will be James
Abdnors, head of the U.S. Small Business Administration; Richard A.
Lempert, vice president of American Airlines; Malcolm T. Stamper,
vice chairman of Boeing Co.; and Barton Brown, vice president of
General Motors Corp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
