<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti-Demonstration     06-13 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Demonstration,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Demonstrate At Funeral In Cap-Haitien</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Nearly 5,000 people demonstrated in
Cap-Haitien after the funeral of a young man who was killed by a
soldier at a slum area courthouse a week ago, the radio station
Haiti-Inter reported Monday.
   The protest occurred Saturday afternoon around Sacre Coeur
Church in the poor La Fossette quarter of Cap-Haitien.
   Soldiers intervened when the crowd headed for the courthouse
shouting anti-government slogans, and dispersed the demonstrators
with tear gas and shots fired into the air, the radio said. One
protester was beaten with a club, it said, but no arrests or
further incidents were reported.
   Reynold Nivrose, 19, was shot dead June 6 by the
sergeant-at-arms of the La Fossette courthouse, who had been
ordered by a judge to arrest him. Nivrose had protested a ruling by
the judge and fled when the sergeant-at-arms tried to make the
arrest.
   Ernst Malebranche, outgoing president of the Port-au-Prince Bar
Association, said in an interview: ``Both the judge and the soldier
acted illegally _ the judge, who is not authorized to order the
arrest of a citizen, and the soldier, who used his firearm
unnecessarily.''
   A mob stormed and ransacked the courthouse June 6 after Nivrose
was killed.
</TEXT>
