<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Libya-Gadhafi,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Libyan Leader Commutes Death Sentences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi has commuted the death
sentences of prisoners awaiting execution in his country, the
official Libyan news agency JANA said Monday.
   The agency, monitored in Rome, also said Gadhafi pledged ``to
continue the struggle for abolishing the death sentence.
   ``The leader intervened to cancel the death penalty on those
convicted ... and to change it to a prison sentence,'' the news
agency said.
   JANA did not say how many prisoners' death sentences were
commuted, nor did it say how long the new prison terms would be.
However, Gadhafi recently advocated life in prison without
possibility of parole as an alternative to the death penalty.
   Gadhafi's reported action came a day after he expressed regret
that Libya's highest policy-making body, the General People's
Congress, did not abolish capital punishment at its special human
rights session.
