<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Convicts     06-13 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Convicts,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Armed Prison Escapees Captured at Mountain Cottage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three armed convicts who escaped last week from
a maximum-security penitentiary outside Montreal were captured
Monday at a cottage in the Laurentian hills, Quebec police reported.
   Andres Dugas, police spokesman, said officers seized the
escapees at the cottage 25 miles northeast of Montreal without a
shot being fired.
   ``We had a tip and drove up to the cottage with our armored
truck'' and the convicts surrendered without resistance, he said.
   Recaptured were Robert Henley, 25, serving a life sentence for
murder; Rene St. Arnaud, 29, sentenced to 12 years for armed
robbery, and his brother Pierre, 23, serving seven years for
robbery.
   Henley, who was wounded in a shootout during the escape Thursday
from the Laval Institute, was hospitalized for treatment.
   ``Henley was so badly hurt he couldn't raise his hands above his
head when we asked him to surrender,'' Dugas said.
   The three used a forklift vehicle and garden hose to scale the
wall of the prison, taking a woman guard and a passing woman as
hostages as they fled in a car. The hostages were released unharmed
near the U.S. border.
   Officials said the convicts were seen climbing the prison wall
and in an exchange of gunfire Henley and one guard were wounded.
   They said an investigation is under way to determine how the
three convicts were armed and how they received the weapons.
