<DOCNO> AP880613-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 2333EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Anti-UnionViolence     06-13 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anti-Union Violence,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: 350 Trade Unionists Killed in 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 350 trade unionists were
killed and 7,500 arrested worldwide during 1987, the International
Confederation of Free Trade Unions said in a report released
Tuesday.
   Despite improvements in some countries, ``the overall picture
remains grim,'' the ICFTU said in its annual survey of anti-union
violence.
   ``There is a tendency among governments to consider respect for
trade union rights as less important than certain other human
rights,'' it said.
   The rights violations occurred in both dictatorships and
democracies, according to the Brussels-based ICFTU, which has 141
affiliates in 97 non-communist nations and claims it represents 87
million workers.
   Its 58-page report said violations last year of union rights
ranged from denying the right of association to ``murder, torture
and imprisonment.''
   The ICFTU report said Latin American unionists faced the most
ruthless treatment.
   It said that in Brazil, more than ``200 killings occurred
related to disputes over landownership, many of which concerned
leaders and members of the National Confederation of Agricultural
Workers.''
   ``There is evidence'' most of the victims were slain by killers
hired by landowners, according to the report.
   In Colombia, paramilitary groups killed at least 74 trade
unionists and ``the real figure is probably much higher,'' it said.
   The report stated: ``The most flagrant trade union rights
violations are undoubtedly taking place in countries under
dictatorship, irrespective of their ideological orientation.
   ``However, in many countries, even those with long established
democratic traditions, there are also restrictions and
infringements of these rights.''
   The ICFTU said laws in Britain and Canada undermined the rights
of trade unions and ``in the United States serious cases of
union-busting continue to occur.''
   It gave this summary:
   _Africa: In most nations, unions are controlled by the parties
in power that forbid rivals, ban or curb the right to strike and
interfere with the organization of union activities. In Ethiopia,
the trade union movement must by law follow Marxist theory and
South Africa ``totally negates fundamental human rights.''
   _Latin America: ``Infringements of trade union rights continue
to occur on a wide scale. Chile, El Salvador, Honduras, Guatemala
and Haiti, among others, continue to violently suppress union
activities.'' In Nicaragua, the human rights situation generally
has improved but ``specific violations of trade union rights
continue to occur'' including detention without trial and
persecution of union members.
   _Asia: In communist nations ``freedom of association, free
collective bargaining and the right to strike do not exist.''
Anti-communist South Korea used ``extreme police violence'' against
strikers.
   _Europe: The introduction of economic reforms in some East
European nations did not boost trade union rights. In Poland, the
courts rejected more than 30 applications for recognition by
``local enterprise sections'' belonging to the outlawed Solidarity
union federation. Romanian police broke up a demonstration of union
workers in November.
   In Britain, ``the most outrageous attack on basic trade union
rights in recent years continues to be the ban'' on union
membership in the government's intelligence gathering center at
Cheltenham.
   _Middle East: Some Arab nations allow only a single trade union
and in others, such as Bahrain, Saudi Arabia, Oman and Qatar, trade
unions are banned.
   Emergency regulations remain in force in Turkey ``to restrict
human and trade union rights,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
