<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Scotus-Byrne     06-13 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Byrne,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Byrne's Applications for Stay of Execution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court late Monday denied two
applications to halt the scheduled Tuesday morning execution of a
Louisiana man convicted of romancing, robbing and murdering a
service station worker in August 1984.
   The denials of the applications by Edward Byrne Jr., 28, set the
stage for the 100th execution in the nation since capital
punishment was reinstated more than 10 years ago.
   The first application for stay of execution filed by Byrne was
denied with the standard dissent by Justices William J. Brennan and
Thurgood Marshall, who dissent to all executions, said Supreme
Court spokeswoman Toni House. Justices Harry A. Blackmun and John
Paul Stevens indicated they also would have granted the stay, Ms.
House said, but noted that it takes five justices to grant such a
stay.
   The second application also was denied with dissents by Brennan
and Marshall, with Stevens indicating he also would have granted
the stay, she said.
   Byrne request that the court review the case was not addressed,
Ms. House said.
   Byrne was to die in the electric chair at the Louisiana State
Penitentiary in Angola for fatally bludgeoning Roberta Johnson of
Bossier City. He has admitted since his arrest that he started
dating her because she handled large sums of money at the service
station where he worked.
   He admitted hitting her in the head with a hammer, but insisted
that he never intended to kill her.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
