<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv23,0507</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, June 23</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   Today is Thursday, June 23, the 175th day of 1988. There are 191
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On June 23, 1947, the Senate joined the House of Representatives
in overriding President Harry S. Truman's veto of the Taft-Hartley
Act. The new law banned the closed shop, provided for a ``cooling
off'' period before strikes, required union finances to be made
public and prohibited unions from making donations to political
campaigns.
   On this date:
   In 1683, William Penn signed a friendship treaty with the Lenni
Lenape Indians near present-day Philadelphia.
   In 1868, Christopher Latham Sholes received a patent for an
invention he called a ``Type-Writer.''
   In 1931, aviators Wiley Post and Harold Catty took off from New
York for a flight around the world.
   In 1938, the Civil Aeronautics Authority was established.
   In 1956, Gamal Abdel Nasser was elected president of Egypt.
   In 1967, the U.S. Senate voted to censure Democrat Thomas J.
Dodd of Connecticut for using campaign money for personal uses.
   In 1967, President Lyndon B. Johnson and Soviet Premier Alexei
Kosygin held the first of two meetings in Glassboro, N.J.
   In 1969, Warren E. Burger was sworn in as chief justice of the
United States by the man he was succeeding, Earl Warren.
   In 1972, President Richard M. Nixon and White House chief of
staff H.R. Haldeman agreed to use the CIA to obstruct the FBI's
Watergate investigation. (The revelation of the White House
recording of this conversation resulted in Nixon's resignation in
August 1974.)
   In 1985, all 329 people aboard an Air-India Boeing 747 were
killed when the plane crashed into the Atlantic Ocean near Ireland.
   Ten years ago: The United States recalled George W. Landau, the
U.S. ambassador to Chile, charging the Chilean government had not
cooperated enough in the investigation of the 1976 murders of
former Chilean diplomat Orlando Letelier and an associate in
Washington.
   Five years ago: In a ruling that effectively shifted the balance
of powers in the federal government, the U.S. Supreme Court struck
down, 7-2, the so-called ``legislative veto,'' which Congress had
used to curtail the powers of the executive branch.
   One year ago: The Iran-Contra hearings resumed after a two-week
break. Former CIA employee Glenn A. Robinette testified he had
installed a $14,000 security system at the home of Lt. Col. Oliver
North, then helped make it appear that North had paid for the work.
   Today's Birthdays: Advertising executive David Ogilvy is 77.
Former Secretary of State William P. Rogers is 75. Actress Irene
Worth is 72. Singer June Carter Cash is 59. Olympic hall-of-famer
Wilma Rudolph is 48. Musical conductor James Levine is 45. Actor
Ted Shackelford is 42.
   Thought for Today: ``To forgive and forget means to throw
valuable experience out the window.'' _ Arthur Schopenhauer, German
philosopher (1788-1860).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880613-0226 </DOCNO>
