<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1018EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-Sharkey Adv14   06-13 0814</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Sharkey, Adv 14,0830</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, June 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Ray Sharkey Back as Mobster in Return of `Wiseguy'</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You viewers who never understood why friends
and co-workers were mad for a TV villain can catch up beginning
Wednesday when CBS reruns the ``Wiseguy'' episodes guest-starring
Ray Sharkey as mobster Sonny Steelgrave.
   ``Wiseguy'' stars Ken Wahl as undercover agent Vinnie Terranova,
who was himself so charmed by Steelgrave he almost went over to the
other side. He has since gone on to chase new villains.
   ``This is a whole new way to do television,'' said Sharkey.
``You can get actors who do mostly movies, because you've got a
story with a beginning, middle and end. It runs longer than a
miniseries and you can develop a character. I've heard someone
refer to this as a soap opera for tough guys.
   ``But I won't be back on `Wiseguy' next season. I'm history. The
only way I could come back is in a flashback. We may do that. We've
gotten so many letters asking for me that I think we should give
them something. There's even a Sonny Steelgrave Memorial Society.
They write us each week asking us to bring back Sonny.''
   Though the Steelgrave episodes that opened ``Wiseguy'' last fall
attracted a following, the show was up against NBC's ``Cheers'' and
``Night Court'' on Thursday night and didn't get big ratings. CBS
is hoping that will change if a new audience catches the show this
summer. Wednesday's episode is the two-hour movie that introduced
the character.
   Sharkey's portrayal of Steelgrave, with his murderous, mercurial
charm, has been likened to James Cagney's Cody Jarrett in ``White
Heat,'' or Humphrey Bogart's Duke Mantee in ``The Petrified
Forest'' and Mad Dog Earle in ``High Sierra.'' Sonny's apocalypse
is nearly as spectacular as Cagney's in the gasoline refinery in
``White Heat.''
   ``I meet people who memorize Sonny's dialogue and say it back to
me,'' said Sharkey. ``Just like `The Rocky Horror Show.'''
   The role in ``Wiseguy'' was a much-needed boost for Sharkey. He
had made a big splash playing an ambitious manager in ``The
Idolmaker'' in 1980, but his career dissolved into alcohol and
drugs.
   ``I went at it full-blown,'' he said. ``It was fun for a while.
Then it got crazy and by 1985 it was sickening. I lost great parts
to guys who became big stars. I couldn't get insured. I'd turn in
my urine tests knowing I would never pass.
   ``I spent several years in and out of hospitals. I'd dry out, do
a movie and end up back in the hospital. I finally found a place
that dealt with the problem and not the personalities. I spent 62
days there, came out and went right to work.''
   He was only four days out of the rehabilitation program when he
began the role on ``Wiseguy.''
   He is currently starring as a Puerto Rican angel in ``Wired,''
based on the controversial Bob Woodward book about John Belushi,
who died of a drug overdose. The angel is a fantasy element added
to the movie. Sharkey says it's like playing the dark side of
``It's a Wonderful Life.''
   The angel picks up Belushi at the morgue ``and shows him the
error of his ways.''
   ``It's great,'' Sharkey said, ``because he gets in all the Blues
Brothers dance numbers and the `Saturday Night Live' comedy
sketches.''
   In August, Sharkey is set to co-star with Jacqueline Bisset in
the romantic comedy ``Scenes From a Class Struggle in Beverly
Hills.'' In September, he is slated to play attorney Roy Cohn, the
former aide to Sen. Joseph McCarthy who died of AIDS.
   After finishing the ``Wiseguy'' shooting in Vancouver, Canada,
Sharkey went to Greece and Africa for the movie ``Act of Piracy,''
playing ``a really bad guy, a gun smuggler and modern-day pirate in
the Caribbean. Those guys'll kill your whole family and take your
boat to run guns or drugs.''
   ``Sonny's different. He was a man who could carry out his own
brand of ethics. He did it with such charm and lack of guilt. And,
I think the audience likes to see bad boys having fun. Sonny was a
man who was very family-oriented. His attitude was `Don't judge me
by what I do for a living.'''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   PODIATRIST TO THE STARS _ Dr. M.H. Sward, a Beverly Hills
podiatrist whose patients have included Jackie Gleason, Walter
Pidgeon and Groucho Marx, has turned actor at the age of 59. Sward,
known professionally as Mac Ward, has just done a commercial for
Cheerios breakfast cereal. He also did a non-speaking role in
Charles Bronson's ``Messenger of Death.'' He got the acting bug
when he attended a commercials workshop and was signed by an agent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, June 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880613-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv14   06-13 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 14,0661</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Tuesday June 14</NOTE>
<HEAD>For Once, Is Murphy Wrong?</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires. John Cunniff is on vacation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Murphy's Law may never be abolished, but it
appears to have been at least temporarily suspended for the benefit
of the U.S. economy.
   The proposition that ``whatever can go wrong will go wrong''
seemed an apt one for followers of economic affairs over the past
couple of decades.
   Recessions alternated with outbursts of inflation until the two
evils finally came together in a phenomenon that was dubbed
``stagflation.''
   When a long period of growth finally arrived in the 1980s, it
had to be financed with huge deficits in the federal budget and
international trade. Then the stock market crashed.
   But in 1988, for a change, the surprises have been almost
entirely on the positive side. As midyear approaches, there is
little sign of any of the woes that many pundits were forecasting
at New Year's.
   ``When the year began, it appeared that the challenges facing
the global economy would prove too difficult to overcome without a
serious slowdown, if not an outright recession,'' observed David
Resler, chief economist at the investment firm of Nomura Securities
International Inc.
   ``Avoiding that unhappy outcome would require robust growth in
foreign demand for American goods, plus an adequate expansion of
manufacturing capacity so that both foreign and domestic demands
could be satisfied at reasonably stable prices.''
   In addition, Resler said, ``consumer spending would need to
increase only moderately so that the additional savings needed to
replace diminished foreign capital flows would be forthcoming.
   ``There were few optimists about the prospects of meeting those
lofty goals. But the facts now seem to indicate that the U.S.
economy is getting just that mix of growth.''
   The big surprise, of course, is that things have gone as well as
they have in the wake of the biggest stock market drop ever last
Oct. 19.
   The collective vision of stock investors and traders is supposed
to be pretty sharp. When the market takes a big dive, government
policymakers, business planners and lots of other people pay close
attention.
   But eight months after the fact, whatever calamity the crash
might have been foretelling has yet to make its presence felt
outside the securities industry itself.
   The manufacturing economy is enjoying a boom in exports, and
consumers haven't gone into hiding.
   In fact, the passage of time has given increasing credence to
the strange idea, first advanced by a few observers in the midst of
the commotion in October, that the crash actually was a beneficial
event in some significant ways.
   ``Economic performance during the first half of 1988 got a
helping hand from the stock-market plunge last October,''
economists at Merrill Lynch say in a just-issued report.
   ``That event jolted financial markets, and the financial sector
is still shaky. But the liquefication of financial markets that
occurred after Oct. 19 and the resulting decline in interest rates
supported real economic activity as 1988 began.
   ``Even though short-term rates are back to where they were in
September 1987, interest-rate-sensitive sectors, particularly
housing and consumer spending, are stronger than they would have
been had rates not declined earlier.''
   Don't be fooled by all this, say the pessimists. If the alarms
sounded by the crash for the federal budget and the machinery of
the markets themselves continue to go unheeded, they warn, more big
trouble is likely.
   What's more, they add, Murphy's Law applies particularly when
people get comfortable and complacent and think the times are going
well.
   Still, it may be possible, without tempting fate, to add a new
corollary to Murphy's Law for economic purposes: Every once in a
while, unaccountably and when least expected, something will go
right.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tues June 14</NOTE>
