<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--ShuttleCountdown-Leader Adv26   06-13 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Shuttle Countdown-Leader, Adv 26,0514</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv26</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 26</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Shuttle Countdown</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Visitors entering Forrest S.
McCartney's office can't miss this sign: ``If it isn't safe, say
so.''
   As director of the Kennedy Space Center, McCartney is overseeing
the preparation of Discovery for the first post-Challenger space
shuttle flight later this summer.
   The sign sums up his approach. If anyone, anywhere in the
system, has a concern, that person should report it.
   ``I'd rather call a timeout to take a look at those concerns
than to move on without checking thoroughly,'' McCartney said in an
interview. ``I don't want anyone on launch day to say, `Is there
something I overlooked, something I should have reported and
didn't?' We want to be sure we have done everything humanly
possible to make this vehicle as safe as it can be before it
flies.''
   Several workers have come forward with legitimate concerns.
Other reports have proved unfounded, and have caused processing
delays. McCartney says he'd rather be safe than sorry.
   McCartney, 57, was a lieutenant general in charge of the Air
Force Space Division when NASA administrator James C. Fletcher
tapped him to be center director. He was part of the space agency
overhaul after the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion of space shuttle
Challenger. He retired last year from the Air Force and continued
in the job as a civilian.
   McCartney has gained a reputation as a ``hands-on'' director who
takes a personal interest in his 13,000 workers and the shuttle
hardware that is checked out, assembled and readied for launch here.
   He pays close attention to the processing through daily staff
meetings, weekly sessions with center managers and monthly
conferences with key NASA shuttle officials. said.
   ``I also get out and talk with the people,'' McCartney says. ``I
want to know what they are thinking. Almost every day I personally
check the hardware _ the orbiter, the solid rocket motors. If I get
a free hour, I say it's time to go out and kick some tires, so I
get in the car and go out there.
   ``The workers talk freely with me. They discuss a full spectrum
of concerns, from processing concerns to work hours. They don't
feel intimidated. It's a good repartee, and I feel good about it.''
   When he first took over as director, NASA's target for resuming
shuttle flights was February 1988. That date has slipped several
months, and, while the delays have been frustrating, he says they
have been necessary.
   McCartney said the emphasis on quality and safety has created
enormous paperwork, or flight documentation, as he calls it.
   ``We close out flight documentation in an orderly way,'' he
said. ``We are not going to move hardware to the next station until
it is ready. It's time-consuming, but, when in doubt, don't. No one
is in a hurry to make a mistake.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
