<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv26   06-13 0962</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 26,0985</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 26</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Godspell,'' the joyous little pop musical that
put the Bible on Broadway, is back in town.
   The show, now playing at the Lamb's Theater, was directed by Don
Scardino who has a long association with the hit musical. He played
Jesus for more than 1,000 performances during the show's seven-year
run in New York.
   ``Godspell,'' based on the Gospel of St. Matthew, is one of
those classic show business tales of success: Young man
(John-Michael Tebelak) writes show as a master's project at
Carnegie Tech in Pittsburgh. Show gets done on a shoestring in New
York at a small experimental theater off-off-Broadway. Gets
favorable reviews. A revised version, with new songs by Stephen
Schwartz, opens at a larger off-Broadway theater and eventually
makes its way to Broadway. At one time during the 1970s, there were
30 companies of the musical playing around the world.
   Scardino first came to ``Godspell'' in 1972 at the age of 24. He
starred as Jesus in the Toronto company of the show and later came
to New York for a two-year run.
   ``Finally, with shinsplints, a sprained ankle and nodes on my
vocal chords, I gave up the ghost and left the show,'' Scardino
says. ``After it had been running five years off-Broadway, I was
asked to open up the Broadway company.
   ``I was flattered. So I wrapped ankles, visited the throat
doctor and went on,'' says the director who started in show
business at the age of 12 as an actor.
   Throughout its long run in the 1970s, ``Godspell,'' a gentle,
free-spirited retelling of the last seven days of Jesus, kept
slowly changing.
   ``The show became a little bloated, and the simplicity
disappeared,'' Scardino says. ``Unlike a regular show where someone
directs it and the production stays that way, John-Michael (who
died in 1985) was basically the overseer of this troupe of lunatic
actors who had come out of an improvisatory style. He encouraged
the show to be flexible and free.''
   Scardino agreed to direct the revival only after discussions
with composer Schwartz.
   ``I wanted to stay true to the original intention of the show
and still have the freedom to bring it up to date,'' he says. ``I
wanted people to think they were watching the original, the show
they remembered, even though it isn't.''
   Besides changing the musical's prologue, Scardino updated a lot
of other material in the show, particularly the jokes and political
references.
   Now there are jokes about Jim and Tammy Bakker and the crisis in
evangelism. Ronald Reagan has also popped up, as has the ubiquitous
yuppie. A section of the show that was spoken now has turned into a
rap number.
   ``We've brought it up to the '80s,'' he says. ``Physically, it
looks the same as it did when it first opened, but the idiom has
been updated.''
   For the revival, Scardino hired young actors who had never done
``Godspell'' before. Most had never seen it. He has also used some
of their suggestions _ ``they are authentically young'' _ such as
incorporating a Pee Wee Herman step into the choreography. He has
taken some of their references and things that have come out of
their current frame of mind to create the show.
   ``The things I've learned by playing Jesus, I've tried to pass
along to Jeffrey Steefel who plays him in this show but without
being dictatorial about it,'' Scardino says. ``Everybody else in
the musical, I'll just give notes or suggestions. With him, I
unconsciously start to act it out or show him and that's wrong. He
is the actor.''
   The original performers in ``Godspell'' all came out of Carnegie
Tech, now Carnegie Mellon University. They had been together for
four years and had a strong background in an acting technique that
involved story theater, the telling of stories and the playing of
games.
   It's a technique not taught much lately, so Scardino asked for _
and got _ an extra week of rehearsal to do theater games such as
Blindman, trust exercises and circle games with the new actors.
They are exercises dedicated to creating an ensemble unit of actors
and break down the social barriers.
   ``It's the only show in which you have to be deprogrammed when
you leave it,'' Scardino laughs.
   The director feels the musical will find a new audience today,
even though it has only been a decade since the show was last seen
in New York, plus get many of the people who saw it before.
   ``I'm a '60s person,'' the 40-year-old Scardino says. ``We all
thought we were searching for new definitions. We thought we were
revolutionaries, either political or spiritual or whatever. But
there was a spiritual search alive and a rejection of material
values _ or at least we thought so. Then we entered the '80s and
we've come into yuppie materialism.''
   It was ``Godspell's'' naivete and honesty that attracted people
in the 1970s, Scardino says, adding that the musical had a fresh
perspective on something that had lost meaning for people _ the
Gospel.
   ``I think we are in a crisis of values now,'' Scardino says.
``Everybody seems to be involved now in another search for meaning
or a new search for spiritual values. It's the pendulum swinging,
although it hasn't swung yet. The kind of joy that `Godspell' has,
the kind of hope that `Godspell' gives, that is needed. And I think
people will come and find it as refreshing as they did before.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
