<1ST_LINE>s i BC-ChildrenofWar Adv19-2Takes   06-13 0846</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Children of War, Adv 19-2 Takes,0869</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Lasting Trauma for Central America's Children of War</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An accompanying item is BC-Children-Assistance, b0565.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pedro, a tiny 6-year-old with big brown
saucers of eyes, cries in fear when he sees soldiers and often
hides in the orphanage where he lives.
   Tomas, 16, is the most aggressive child at another children's
home and ``capable of breaking anything when he's angry,'' says the
home's director.
   Angel, a Salvadoran boy about 14, saw his mother killed in the
guerrilla war and ended up on the Guatemala City streets sniffing
paint thinner.
   On a wooded hillside in El Salvador, a slightly-built,
baby-faced boy who uses the nom de guerre ``William'' has an M-16
slung over his shoulder. Now 15, he says he has been a guerrilla
fighter for a year and a half.
   All are survivors and victims of Central America's armed
conflicts.
   ``The children who have seen violence, even if they haven't been
direct victims in terms of physical violence, will keep the trauma
of the effect of war for a long time. This can last for a
lifetime,'' said Agop Kayayan, representative at the Central
American headquarters in Guatemala City of UNICEF, the United
Nations Children's Fund.
   ``We're really talking about the way the next generation is
going to act or is going to think of the way things are done in
society.''
   Few statistics are available to show how many children have been
killed, wounded or orphaned by eight years of war between leftist
rebels and the U.S.-backed government in El Salvador, by the
fighting for the better part of 10 years in Nicaragua and by the
still-simmering 27-year conflict between leftist guerrillas and the
army in Guatemala.
   In Nicaragua, 40,000 children were orphaned _ the loss of one or
both parents _ in the 1978-79 Sandinista revolution that ended 42
years of Somoza family rule. An additional 11,361 children have
been orphaned in the more than six years of fighting between
U.S.-backed Contra rebels and Sandinista-government troops.
   Children form a large part, from 60 to 80 percent by some
estimates, of the more than 1 million people displaced in their own
countries. Thousands of others are among those who have fled to
neighboring countries, or to the United States, Canada or Europe.
   A Guatemalan court survey found more than 58,693 orphans as of
August 1986. But only 55 percent of Guatemalan towns responded to
the survey and the total number of orphans is estimated at 100,000
to 200,000.
   The Salvadoran government agency charged with children's welfare
has no figures on the number of orphans in El Salvador.
   Throughout the region, but particularly in Guatemala where half
the population is Indian, many orphans are taken in by relatives.
Others, like Angel, the Salvadoran boy now in Guatemala, fend for
themselves.
   Young teen-agers fight on both sides of the conflicts _ for
guerrillas or for governments.
   Lino Hernandez Trigueros, executive secretary of the Permanent
Human Rights Commission in Nicaragua, said the commission has found
12- and 13-year-olds with the military on the remote Caribbean
coast. Military service is required for those 17 to 25.
   Reporters have seen children as young as 13 in the Contra rebel
ranks.
   In the Salvadoran countryside, it is easy to spot children who
appear years shy of the 18-year draft age with the army, as well as
with the guerrillas, like ``William.''
   Where clashes are frequent, casings of spent bullets often
become the only toys children have play with.
   The trauma of living with war, in crowded refugee camps or in
constant flight, has many faces.
   ``This can be seeing security forces as people who are going to
kill or hurt rather than as security forces,'' said UNICEF's
Kayayan.
   Seeing families, relatives or neighbors killed can lead young
people to be violent themselves, he said. The effect multiplies
with the closeness of the relationship and the degree of violence.
   A drawing by a third-grade Guatemalan refugee girl at a camp in
southern Mexico shows soldiers shooting men tied to stakes.
Decapitated bodies lie between them.
   Orphanage personnel asked that children's names be changed for
this article to avoid reprisals against them.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PEDRO:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A woman at the orphanage where 6-year-old Pedro lives says his
hiding when he sees solders is understandable. He spent most of his
short life in Guatemala's highland forests, fleeing soldiers
searching for guerrilla supporters. His mother was killed.
   When soldiers came to his village late last year, Pedro fell to
the ground and covered himself with pine boughs. His father and the
group of women the boy was with escaped, but Pedro was discovered
and wound up in the orphanage.
   ``When he saw the little girls at the home he said he didn't
like women because they had abandoned him,'' the orphanage woman
said. When she took him to look for relatives among other displaced
people, she added, ``he wouldn't go in because he saw the
soldiers.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880613-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1411EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-ChildrenofWar Adv19-1stadd   06-13 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Children of War, Adv 19-1st add,0695</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>GUATEMALA CITY: the soldiers.''</HEAD>
<HEAD>TOMAS:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Sixteen-year-old Tomas has told the director of the orphanage
where he has lived for five years that soldiers broke his father's
fingers and tortured him in other ways ``to make him confess that
he was a guerrilla.''
   ``They shot him three times in the chest,'' the director said.
``He never saw his mother again. Some told him the town was
burned.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ANGEL:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Mark Connolly of Childhope, an international organization
helping street children, has known Angel since not long after he
reached the Guatemala City streets in 1984, stealing and already on
paint thinner at age 9.
   One day he began telling Connolly about nightmares he has of
seeing his mother killed at their home in El Salvador.
   ``He vividly recalled to me the killing of his father, mother
and two brothers,'' he said.
   The next day, soldiers found the boy asleep at home and brought
his little sister and him to a base where his brother was a soldier.
   ``Soldiers came back to the base one day and said his brother
had been killed. Then soldiers, friends of his or his brother's,
took them to the border and told them to go across,'' he said.
   Shortly after arriving in Guatemala City, he lost track of his
sister. One day, the director says, Angel wants to go back to El
Salvador to find a younger brother.
   He has been in and out of a home run by a religious group in the
provinces.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   In many children, the trauma is hidden.
   ``What you can say is that there have been many learning
difficulties, many difficulties in relating,'' said Nicole Dagnino,
president of Enfants Refugies du Monde, a private French
organization that works with refugee children in several countries.
   Parents who are refugees become depressed, have no jobs, lose
their traditional contact with the land. The child, in addition to
having to leave his home, loses his father image.
   ``They have lost all points of reference,'' Ms. Dagnino said.
   A woman who works with refugee orphans said she had ``several
children who go around setting fire to everything.''
   But while children in orphanages often fight with each other,
she said these don't.
   ``It is as if they protect each other,'' she said.
   Perhaps worse than the direct effects, says Kayayan, is the
money that military spending takes away from health, education and
other programs to help children and the destruction of those
facilities.
   Adding to the problem is economic crisis in the already-poor
region from both the wars and other factors.
   UNICEF says infant and child deaths are on the rise in the
region and nearly two out of three of the survivors suffer some
degree of malnutrition.
   A study by the Guatemala-based Nutrition Institute of Central
America and Panama found the nutrition in rural communities of
Guatemala had worsened significantly between 1985 and 1987, a
period after the most recent peak in fighting.
   ``In the war atmosphere of Nicaragua and El Salvador it is
impossible to collect data,'' the institute's Dr. Hernan Delgado
said. ``But it is reasonable to think that with the military and
economic situations, there is a worsening in the state of health.''
   About 40 percent of children under age 5 in the Central American
region are believed to suffer some form of malnutrition. The
average includes Costa Rica and Panama, where conditions
traditionally are better.
   In 1980, 64 percent of the population was below the poverty line
and 41 percent could not afford the minimum food basket.
   But Delgado said worsening nutrition levels or infant and child
mortality were ``like the tip of the iceberg,'' the culmination of
a series of changes such as more illness or reduced physical
activity.
   ``It may be that it is not as important as all the change that
occurs, what that implies in all the children who didn't die,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880613-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1415EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Children-Assistance Adv19   06-13 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Children-Assistance, Adv 19,0363</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Many Groups Seek to Help Central American Children of War</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Children of War, b0563-b0564</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many organizations, both local and
international, help Central American children in various ways. Here
are some of them:
   American Friends of Children _ Created by John Wetterer, a
former New York bank personnel executive from Massapequa, N.Y., who
went to Guatemala City to start a home for about 30 boys. He now
has about 250 in the home, popularly known as Mi Casa (My House);
300 in a school for boys unable to attend school otherwise, because
of poverty or home conditions, and 75 in another home that was
turned over to him.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Childhope _ An international voluntary organization that brings
together groups working to help street children and encourages
local leaders to take preventive action. Founded in New York by
representatives of the Christian Children's Fund, the World Council
of Churches, Covenant House and other organizations, its
headquarters is in Guatemala City.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Enfants Refugies du Monde _ A private French organization, it
sends volunteer teams to provide education and health care for
refugee children and to set up programs to improve living and
working conditions. It has worked in eight countries, including
Mexico and four Central American countries.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Guatemala Lions Club _ Its main project is the Children's
Community of San Juan Sacatepequez, a hospital for critically
malnourished children. In addition to medical attention, the
children also receive clothes and other care.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oscar Arnulfo Romero Community, El Salvador _ Known as COAR, it
cares for and educates 209 war orphans with assistance from Caritas
and Friends of COAR in Cleveland, Ohio. The children live in
family-type units while administrators search for their relatives
in refugee camps.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   S.O.S. villages in El Salvador _ Part of S.O.S. Kinderdorf
International, it has four villages with a total of 275 children in
the country. They live in units with a substitute mother and are
cared for and educated until they become independent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
