<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1417EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Africa-ToxicWaste Adv19-1stadd   06-13 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Africa-Toxic Waste, Adv 19-1st add,0775</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>NAIROBI: Third World countries.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Despite the public pronouncements, few expect any quick
resolution of the problem.
   ``Quite a lot of the business is going on somewhere in the
twilight,'' said Jan Huismans, director of the Geneva-based
International Register of Potentionally Toxic Chemicals, an arm of
UNEP. ``I think it is economics. I can't see any other benefit of
receiving this waste.''
   Money also is a factor for Western industries, which account for
the bulk of the 300 million metric tons of industrial wastes
produced annually worldwide.
   Stringent environmental laws in the West, like those imposed by
the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, demand on-site disposal
facilities that can cost as much as $30 million and take years to
build. And to ship toxic wastes from California _ which churns out
10 million metric tons of wastes a year _ across the United States
to a landfill in New Jersey costs about $800 a barrel.
   Industrialized countries also are under public pressure to keep
toxic landfills away from rapidly expanding residential areas.
   In return for $92.6 million, the Congo, a nation of 1.8 million
people, agreed to accept 1 million metric tons for storage or
incineration over eight years. The ``heavily polluted chemical
waste,'' as it was described, was to be shippped from the
Netherlands, Belguim, Luxembourg and West Germany.
   Van Santen, the Rottendam-based cargo firm hired to transport
the wastes, made no effort to conceal the deal.
   T.H. Looyschelder, director of Van Santen, said the firm saw a
double advantage of transporting toxic waste to Africa.
   ``Not only do we have a cheap way of disposing of waste, but the
Third World will be provided with money, knowhow and
infrastructure,'' he was quoted as saying.
   The company said similar negotiations were under way with Niger,
in north-central Africa.
   But Van Santen was forced to put the Congo deal on hold after a
spate of negative publicity.
   ``Before the transports to Africa would take place, we would
have taken samples and analyses of the chemicals involved to check
whether the transports would be within the regulations of the
various countries involved,'' Hans Hulswit, deputy director of Van
Santen, told the AP.
   ``But now that the press has painted the picture of us being
involved in illegal activities by imposing dangerous materials on
Third World countries against their will, we're bowing out.''
   Huismans, the U.N. official, said African countries aren't
prepared to handle the West's toxic wastes.
   ``In principal, there is nothing terribly wrong with dumping
toxic wastes in Africa providing the receiving countries can
properly handle the wastes,'' he said. ``Invariably, most of the
countries who accept the wastes are importing a problem that they
initially may not know is a problem.''
   Huismans, a toxicologist, said that most hazardous wastes
shipped to Africa are so vaguely described that it is impossible to
know from their names whether they are dangerous or not.
   Parts of the South Pacific and the Caribbean long have been
toxic wastes dumps. As those landfills became full, Africa became
the new dumping ground beginning five years ago.
   UNEP has drafted a Global Convention on the Control of
Transboundary Movements of Hazardous Wastes, which was discussed an
an international toxic waste conference sponsored by UNEP June 6-10
in Caracas, Venezuela. UNEP's executive director, Mostafa K. Tolba,
said it would be legally binding on signatory nations once approved
by the 50-nation group, probably next year.
   ``Most of the countries are not equipped to handle such
imports,'' Tolba said in a statement. ``That's why we must work to
get the international treaty into force to ensure adequate control
of movements of hazardous wastes crossing frontiers. ...
   ``We have received information on planned exports of millions of
metric tons of hazardous wastes from European and U.S. companies to
Third World countries such as Guinea Bissau, the Congo, Benin,
Ethiopia, Peru, Argentina, Venezuela.''
   Huismans urged preventative work on possible health hazards.
   ``I don't think we should wait until such proof is found,'' he
said. ``So far, it has been difficult to prove that any wastes have
led to serious effects on human health. But it takes time for these
things to develop.''
   Said Sey, the Gambian foreign minister:
   ``I think people have a concept that Africa is the jungle.
   ``If you cannot dump it in North America, just dump it in the
jungle because it is just trees and animals and those Africans
don't matter.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
