<1ST_LINE>s i BC-NATOChanges Adv19-1stadd   06-13 0797</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-NATO Changes, Adv 19-1st add,0818</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>BRUSSELS: be made.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A key turning point was Gorbachev's dramatic call in January
1986 for the global elimination of all nuclear weapons by the year
2000, including a first-phase scrapping of INF missiles in Europe
by 1990.
   Ten months later, at a meeting in Reykjavik, Iceland, he and
Reagan agreed in principle to eliminate all but 100 INF missiles on
each side. They also came close to agreeing in principle to scrap
all ballistic missiles, a idea that went far beyond the INF
proposals and triggered an avalanche of West European complaints
that Reagan had gone too far.
   Although the West Europeans at that point were pressing hard for
completion of an INF treaty, the Reykjavik talk of eliminating all
ballistic missiles caused a serious political crisis in NATO. The
Europeans felt they had not been adequately consulted by the Reagan
administration on an issue that directly affected Western Europe's
security.
   Shortly after that summit, Jacques Chirac, then premier of
France, called on the European allies to create a new security
charter to defend their interests.
   ``The scope of the proposals put forward by both sides at the
Reykjavik summit in October seemed to shake the very basis on which
our conception of U.S.-Soviet relations is founded,'' Chirac said.
   His remark carried with it the weight of broad agreement among
the West European allies that they should insist on playing a
bigger political role.
   ``One cannot remain forever a spectator to the American-Soviet
negotiations, even if they are positive,'' Prime Minister Filipe
Gonzalez of Spain told the French mewspaper Le Monde in an
interview published Feb. 11.
   This concern is rooted partly in the allies' belief that the
United States is losing some of its international political
predominance and that economic strains induced by years of huge
budget deficits may soon force it to pull some American troops out
of Western Europe.
   In the United States, a feeling has grown in recent years that
the Europeans are bearing too small a share of the burden of
Western defense.
   In June 1984 the U.S. Senate, by a 55-41 vote, defeated a
proposal to withdraw nearly one-third of the 326,000 U.S. troops
based in Europe unless the allies did more to improve non-nuclear
defenses.
   This triggered a new effort in NATO, spearheaded by Carrington
and former a U.S. ambassador to NATO, David Abshire, to cooperate
more on defense planning and in the development, production and
buying of armaments. A key result of this was the Conventional
Defense Improvements initiative approved at a NATO defense
ministers meeting in May 1985.
   Talk of strengthening the ``European pillar'' of NATO has been
around since President John F. Kennedy coined the term in 1962. But
it has taken on added urgency in recent years, partly due to U.S.
economic problems.
   A study by political leaders and defense experts from the United
States, Canada and eight European NATO countries, published in May,
called for a high-level alliance meeting early in 1989 to revise
the trans-Atlantic pact on which Western security has rested for 39
years.
   ``A fundamental change has occurred in the U.S.-European
relationship,'' the study concluded.
   It said the Europeans should take more of the economic and
political burdens of alliance leadership, and that the United
States should accustom itself to conducting NATO business on more
even terms with the Europeans.
   As perceptions about the military threat posed by the Soviet
Union have changed in recent years, trans-Atlantic friction has
grown over how to respond to security problems outside the NATO
area.
   The U.S. bombing of Libya in April 1986 brought this conflict to
a peak. Britain was the only NATO country to explicitly support the
U.S. bombing raid, which was described by Reagan as a defensive
response to Libyan backing for terrorist attacks on Americans in
Europe. The French and Spanish governments declined to permit U.S.
F-111 fighter-bombers to cross their airspace en route from Britain
to Libya and back.
   Carrington says this marked the low point of his four years at
NATO.
   ``It was quite nasty,'' he said. ``It brought to a head the
American perception that the Europeans were really not interested
in anything that happened outside the NATO area.''
   It also hardened a West European view of the Reagan
administration as a group of ``cowboys,'' Carrington said.
   The strains eased over time, helped by the decision of several
West European countries, including Italy, Belgium and the
Netherlands, to join the U.S. Navy in mine-clearing operations in
the Persian Gulf starting in 1987.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Burns specializes in the coverage of NATO
and the European Economic Community for The Associated Press from
his base in Brussels.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
