<1ST_LINE>s i BC-NATOChanges-Dates Adv19   06-13 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-NATO Changes-Dates, Adv 19,0402</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Key Dates in Changes within NATO since 1984</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-NATO Changes, b0569-b0570</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some key dates in affairs of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization since 1984:
   JUNE 1984 _ Lord Carrington takes over from Joseph Luns as NATO
secretary-general.
   JANUARY 1985 _ U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz and
Soviet Foreign Minister Andrei A. Gromyko meet in Geneva and set
the agenda for new superpower arms talks, covering medium- and
long-range nuclear weapons as well as space and defensive weapons.
   MARCH 1985 _ Mikhail S. Gorbachev is named general secretary of
the Soviet Communist Party, and as such the leader of the Soviet
Union. NATO defense ministers for the first time formally endorse
the U.S. Strategic Defense Initiative, or ``star wars'' plan.
   MAY 1985 _ Allied defense ministers approve the Conventional
Defense Improvements plan for strengthening non-nuclear forces.
   NOVEMBER 1985 _ President Reagan meets Gorbachev for the first
time in Geneva.
   JANUARY 1986 _ Gorbachev calls for the global elimination of
nuclear weapons by the end of the century.
   MARCH 1986 _ In a national referendum, Spaniards vote to stay in
NATO. It is the first time a member country has considered leaving.
   MAY 1986 _ NATO foreign ministers, meeting in Halifax, Nova
Scotia, urge ``bold new steps'' in East-West negotiations to reduce
troops and non-nuclear weaponry throughout Europe.
   OCTOBER 1986 _ Reagan and Gorabachev, meeting in Reykjavik,
Iceland, agree in principle to eliminate all medium-range nuclear
missiles.
   JUNE 1987 _ NATO foreign ministers endorse Gorbachev's offer to
widen the medium-range missile deal to include shorter-range
rockets. Later, U.S. Gen. Bernard W. Rogers, an opponent of the
deal, is dropped as Supreme Allied Commander Europe and replaced by
Gen. John R. Galvin.
   DECEMBER 1987 _ Reagan and Gorbachev sign the missile treaty at
their summit in Washington. West Germany's Manfred Woerner is
chosen to succeed Carrington as NATO secretary general when
Carrington leaves in June 1988.
   MARCH 1988 _ A NATO summit meeting reaffirms the basic
principles of the alliance, pledges to modernize U.S. nuclear
weapons in Western Europe and calls for major reductions in
non-nuclear forces.
   JUNE 1988 _ Reagan and Gorbachev, meeting in Moscow, put the
medium-range nuclear missile treaty into effect.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
