<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WeekendTV-Horsford Adv24-26   06-13 0816</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV-Horsford, Adv 24-26,0832</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24-26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, June 24-26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Anna Maria Horsford Shapes Thelma on NBC's `Amen'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1 of June 13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anna Maria Horsford has turned a supporting
role as Thelma, the unmarried, 39-year-old deacon's daughter on
``Amen,'' into one of the most popular characters on the NBC hit
comedy.
   Thelma, who's been engaged and jilted 18 times, has been
described as a ``vampy virgin.''
   Horsford said in an interview that she sees Thelma as a
reluctant spinster who, even at 39, is still holding on to her
virtue.
   ``It's always a challenge to a man to be first,'' she said.
``Don't ever assume that virtuous girls are uninteresting.''
   Horsford was born and raised in Harlem, the daughter of a
businessman, and attended New York's High School for the Performing
Arts. She said she began to draw up a history for Thelma as soon as
she was cast.
   ``She's unemployed, unmarried and living at home with her father
(played by Sherman Hemsley),'' she said. ``I wrote it all down.
Then I could see what's my attitude toward someone like that. My
first reaction was that she was spoiled by her father. She doesn't
do what she doesn't have to do.
   ``I looked for her endearing qualities, too. She'd been engaged
many times, so I looked back in my past at the girls who got the
ring but never got to the altar. I created a woman who is quiet,
strong, manipulative and secure in the sense that her life has been
consistent since childhood.''
   If Daddy spoils her, it's the handsome Rev. Reuben Gregory,
played by Clifton Davis, who puts her in a matrimonial mood. So
far, her love is unrequited.
   Before ``Amen,'' Horsford worked regularly in films, including
``St. Elmo's Fire,'' ``Heartburn,'' ``Class,'' ``Crackers,'' ``The
Fan'' and ``Street Smart,'' plus in a number of television movies.
   ``I've played a lot of strong women in films,'' she said.
``Sometimes I've been a policewoman and carried a gun. But I really
hate guns and abhor screen violence. My father was shot by a holdup
man when I was 4, and thereafter he wore a gun to work. I never
dated in high school. All the boys knew Daddy carried a gun.''
   She said in her screen roles she has tried to portray strength
through her presence. ``I think a character who can scare you with
his presence is much stronger than a person who needs a gun,'' she
said. ``I try to show that in my acting.''
   Because of the regularity of her work in movies, she said she
wasn't terribly worried about whether she would land the role in
the network series. She had tested for the role in New York, then
was called to Los Angeles to test opposite Hemsley.
   ``I came out on a Sunday, auditioned on Monday and was told
there'd probably be a decision on Tuesday. Well, there was no word
on Tuesday. Or Wednesday or Thursday. By then I was back in New
York. My agent called me at noon Friday and said, `Guess what? You
have the job.'''
   NBC had made a reservation for her on a 4 p.m. plane that day.
``I said, `Oh, no, is this the way Hollywood does it?' I flew back
to L.A. and went to work the next day.''
   Horsford said she has learned that in television you have to
come out ready, with all your lines memorized.
   ``I said I'm so grateful for every lesson, for every showcase
I've done,'' she said. ``You do a sitcom and you can use everything
you've learned. You don't have time to think of criticism because
it's so fast. I think what makes a hit show is an actor giving a
lot of his or her resource to a writer.
   ``A producer hires you hoping that you can deliver. But there's
no way a producer can anticipate how the audience will respond to
you. The writers pick up little pieces of you and your personality
and put it into the script. An actor's heartache is having a great
line but then losing it because it didn't work in rehearsal. In
television, if something doesn't work the first time there's no
second chance.''
   When she moved to Los Angeles two years ago to start work on
``Amen,'' she found herself facing another problem. She had to
learn to drive.
   ``I'm an expert now,'' she said. ``I went to driving school for
seven weeks. When I first came here I got very friendly with
everyone at Paramount Studios. You get humble and ask everybody for
a ride. I still have a soft spot in my heart, too, for all the men
who let me drive and sat in the passenger seat while I was
learning.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 24-26</NOTE>
