<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Dylan Reviewed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   .
   
   ``Down in the Groove'' (Columbia) _ Bob Dylan
   
   Columbia proclaims on the packaging of Bob Dylan's latest album
that he is a ``1988 Rock & Roll Hall of Fame Inductee.''
   Did they think someone out there would pick up the record and
say, ``I never heard of this guy, but look, he's in the Rock 'n'
Roll Hall of Fame? How bad can he be?''
   Most anyone browsing in the Dylan section is going to be aware
that his most recent ``Knocked Out Loaded'' was pretty mediocre and
that even the darkly brilliant ``Empire Burlesque'' that preceded
it was an acquired taste.
   Dylan needs a strong, accessible back-to-basics record. ``Down
in the Groove'' is it _ with an asterisk.
   Dylan wrote only four of the 10 songs, two of which were
co-written with the Grateful Dead's Robert Hunter. The Dylan songs
are superb, and covers suit him so well, they might as well be his.
The record is so strong because he hasn't insisted on filling it
with his own material, however weak.
   Instead, he offers unique Dylanesque treatments of standards
including, believe it or not, ``Shenandoah.'' He's also backed by
an all-star lineup of pals, including Eric Clapton, Mark Knopfler,
the Grateful Dead, Full Force, Paul Simonon of The Clash, Steve
Jones of the Sex Pistols, Ron Wood and Clydie and Bobby King.
   Perhaps the best cut on the album is ``Silvio,'' one of the
Dylan-Hunter collaborations, with Jerry Garcia, Bob Weir and Brent
Mydland singing backup.
   The other Dylan-Hunter tune, ``Ugliest Girl in the World,''
shows our man's sense of humor intact: ``The woman I love, she
gotta hook in her nose, her eyebrows meet and she wears second-hand
clothes, she speaks with a stutter and she walks with a hop, I
don't know why I love her, but I just can't stop.''
   ``Had a Dream About You Baby'' is fine hard rock, one of two
original songs Dylan wrote for his movie, ``Hearts of Fire,'' which
has not been released, though the soundtrack album is available.
   ``Down in the Groove'' opens with Wilbert Harrison's ``Let's
Stick Together.''
   ``When Did You Leave Heaven'' is a crooner's number, and Dylan's
strained wail is downright charming.
   ``Death Is Not the End'' is the other Dylan original, gospel
tinged with a Celtic dirge.
   He closes with the Stanley Brothers' haunting ballad of
alienation, ``Rank Strangers to Me'': ``I wandered again to my home
in the mountains, where in youth's early dawn I was happy and free.
I looked for my friends, but I never could find them. I found they
were all rank strangers to me.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
