<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--NavalObservatory Adv16   06-13 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Naval Observatory, Adv 16,0691</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, June 16, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Richmond Station's Lasers, Telescopes Guide the World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From an abandoned blimp base, scientists are
peering beyond the stars and studying how the earth moves.
   Their work guides ships at sea, satellites in space and even a
cab driver in Chicago, and could someday help predict earthquakes.
They also found that the generally stable Miami area is rising a
fraction of an inch a year.
   On the grounds of the U.S. Naval Observatory's Richmond station
south of here are optical and radio telescopes, a visiting German
laser system and soon a gravity meter, all designed to pinpoint
locations and distances.
   ``We're observing continental drift, changes in the earth's
crust and movements along fault lines, as well as the earth's spin
and wobble,'' says Alice Babcock, one of 10 civilians at the
station and its director. ``As far as I know, this network is the
only source of such measurements.''
   The station, which costs less than $500,000 a year to run, is
part of a NASA network used by the United States, Soviet Union and
other satellite-launching nations to program guidance systems and
pinpoint locations.
   The data is being fed into a growing worldwide satellite network
that will become the definitive source for navigators. It is not
only available to ships, planes, satellites and submarines, but to
motorists via computerized maps.
   ``I met a Chicago taxi driver who had a receiver mounted in his
cab _ he said it was quicker and more accurate than using a map,''
says Ms. Babcock. There are even hand-held receivers can pinpoint
location and headings for hikers, explorers and rescue teams.
   Richmond, set up in 1949 at a World War II blimp base, also has
the only backup to the Master Clock at the U.S. Naval Observatory
in Washington, a basis for accurate time measurement all over the
world. The cesium-fueled clocks at Richmond, which measure time by
the radioactive element's rate of decay, are checked constantly
against those in Washington to prevent errors.
   The exact time is shared with other points by bouncing the
information off satellites. Even at the speed of light, phone lines
are useless for comparing the readings because switching stations
can slow the signals.
   However most of the staff's time is spent looking upward. The
60-foot diameter radiotelescope seeks out quasars, small sources of
intense radio emissions billions of light-years away at the edge of
the visible universe.
   ``If one of them seems to be moving, we know it's really the
earth that's wobbling,'' says Ms. Babcock. The measurements are
constantly checked and rechecked to see how the earth and points on
its surface are changing.
   In addition, researchers from the Wettzell Station in West
Germany are using a mobile laser telescope to fire green light
beams at a two-foot orbiting LAGEOS satellite covered with 40
four-inch mirrors. The beam bounces 3,500 miles back to show up on
a screen in a trailer crammed with electronic equipment.
   ``You can do a lot of things with this information. It's a very
accurate position fix for a satellite, or for points on earth,''
says German scientist Walter Etling. Distances over 1,000 miles can
be calculated to within an inch or two using this method, he says.
   The Richmond scientists plan to install by year's end a gravity
meter, a metal ball suspended in a magnetic field that can measure
minute changes in mass below it. And Ms. Babcock hopes to install a
laser system that can bounce beams off mirrors left on the lunar
surface by U.S. and Soviet moonwalkers.
   The new systems may eventually have to replace the observatory's
optical telescope, which will become as useless as Washington's
when encroaching development lights up the night skies and makes
stargazing impossible.
   Ms. Babcock has no doubt ever more exotic measuring sticks will
be available. ``In this field, the technology is changing so fast
we never really get to a standard system.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880613-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--TreeHistory Adv16   06-13 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Tree History, Adv 16,0584</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, June 16, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Scientists Hope Tree Rings Will Answer Questions About Past</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts hope a boat found near a pharoah's
pyramid will answer questions about ancient Egypt, but they're not
studying the way it was built _ they're looking at the wood it's
made of.
   ``There are 2{ centuries of information in one piece of wood
from that boat,'' says Peter I. Kuniholm, a Cornell University
archaeologist and tree-ring expert who is studying pencil-like
cores drilled out of the planks of the 30-foot-long boat probably
buried more than 3,800 years ago in Dashur.
   It and three similar boats were buried near the pyramid complex
of Senwosret III so he could use them in the afterlife, says Diana
Craig Patch, the Carnegie Museum of Natural History Egyptologist.
   Industrialist Andrew Carnegie bought the boat in 1901 and
shipped it from Egypt to Pittsburgh. Two of the others are at the
Egyptian Museum in Cairo and the third is at the Field Museum of
Natural History in Chicago.
   Kuniholm hopes rings in the samples will pinpoint the boat's age
and create a framework to help date Egyptian objects and determine
when events occurred.
   Dendrochronology, the science of tree ring dating, was
established in 1930 when Andrew E. Douglass of the University of
Arizona studieaille said.
   ``You take living trees of a particular species in a particular
area, and you measure the pattern of wide and narrow rings,'' he
said. ``You can then go back to ancient timbers from buildings, for
example, and measure the ring patterns, and if they overlap in
time, you should be able to link those patterns together.
   ``You're basically piecing together this master pattern, which
is anchored at the present day.''
 
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880613-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary Adv16   06-13 0943</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary, Adv 16,0968</2ND_LINE>
