<NOTE>For release Thursday, June 16, and thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: This is the Explorations package for June 16 in summary form.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Chiropractic Struggles For Credibility Despite Court Victory</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   CHICAGO _ Those who have found relief through chiropractors'
spinal manipulation sing its praises, and physicians are reluctant
to criticize after the American Medical Association lost an
antitrust lawsuit, but chiropractic is still struggling for
credibility.
   ``We still meet lots of prejudices and unfair treatment,'' says
Steve Elliott, past director of the Texas Chiropractic Association.
   ``I see a lot of patients that deal with chiropractors, and
generally they are not accepted very well by the general medical
community, but they do help a lot of people,'' said Dr. Lawrence
Robbins, a neurologist specializing in headache treatments in the
Chicago suburb of Northbrook.
   The number of U.S. chiropractors grew from 13,000 in 1970 to
more than 30,000 in 1985, the last year for which figures are
available. Chiropractors differ from physicians in that they
perform no surgery and prescribe no drugs, preferring to let the
body heal itself after full nerve function is restored.
   Chiropractic, derived from the Greek for ``effective hand,'' is
based on the theory that disease may be caused by interference with
nerve function, which practitioners try to correct by manipulating
the spine and joints.
   There are now 15 U.S. chiropractic colleges accredited by the
Council on Chiropractic Education. Students must complete 4,200
classroom hours of medical education over four years, similar to
medical school.
   The curriculum includes anatomy, physiology, nutrition,
pathology, public health, clinical and laboratory diagnosis,
gynecology, obstetrics, pediatrics, X-ray technique and
interpretation, geriatrics, psychology and ethics.
   Far from the stereotype of the medical school dropout,
chiropractic students are more typically people who have already
established credentials in nursing, physical therapy, teaching and
dentistry, said Dr. William L. Ramsey, vice president for academic
affairs at Logan College of Chiropractic in St. Louis. ``Twenty-two
percent of students have master's degrees or better.''
   Chiropractic now is seeking credibility through scientific proof
of its effectiveness, said Steven Wolk of the Foundation for
Chiropractic Education and Research in Arlington, Va. The
foundation has earmarked $5 million over the next six years for
independent research.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Richmond Station's Lasers, Telescopes Guide the World</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From an abandoned blimp base, scientists are
peering beyond the stars and studying how the earth moves.
   Their work guides ships at sea, satellites in space and even a
cab driver in Chicago, and could someday help predict earthquakes.
They also found that the generally stable Miami area is rising a
fraction of an inch a year.
   On the grounds of the U.S. Naval Observatory's Richmond station
south of here are optical and radio telescopes, a visiting German
laser system and soon a gravity meter, all designed to pinpoint
locations and distances.
   ``We're observing continental drift, changes in the earth's
crust and movements along fault lines, as well as the earth's spin
and wobble,'' says Alice Babcock, one of 10 civilians at the
station and its director. ``As far as I know, this network is the
only source of such measurements.''
   The station, which costs less than $500,000 a year to run, is
part of a NASA network used by the United States, Soviet Union and
other satellite-launching nations to program guidance systems and
pinpoint locations.
   The data is being fed into a growing worldwide satellite network
that will become the definitive source for navigators. It is not
only available to ships, planes, satellites and submarines, but to
motorists via computerized maps and to hikers, explorers and rescue
teams via hand-held receivers.
   Richmond also has the only backup to the Master Clock at the
U.S. Naval Observatory in Washington, a basis for accurate time
measurement all over the world. The clocks at Richmond, which
measure time by the rate of decay of cesium, are checked constantly
against those in Washington.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Scientists Hope Tree Rings Will Answer Questions About Past</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts hope a boat found near a pharoah's
pyramid will answer questions about ancient Egypt, but they're not
studying the way it was built _ they're looking at the wood it's
made of.
   ``There are 2{ centuries of information in one piece of wood
from that boat,'' says Peter I. Kuniholm, a Cornell University
archaeologist and tree-ring expert who is studying pencil-like
cores drilled out of the planks of the 30-foot-long boat probably
buried more than 3,800 years ago in Dashur, Egypt.
   Kuniholm hopes rings in the samples will pinpoint the boat's age
and create a framework to help date Egyptian objects and determine
when events occurred.
   Dendrochronology, the science of tree ring dating, was
established in 1930 by Andrew E. Douglass of the University of
Arizona.
   Only in recent years, though, has enough wood been collected
from medieval ruins, ice layers, artifacts and other sources to
date objects more than 5,000 years old, said Michael G.L. Baillie
of Queen's University in Belfast, Ireland.
   The science increasingly is revealing more than just the age of
objects, including data about the weather or environment 5,000
years ago. The spacing of rings represents time intervals when
trees were alive and growing. The width of each ring reflects the
weather each growing season, and comparison of many samples from
one region gives a climate pattern.
   ``You take living trees of a particular species in a particular
area, and you measure the pattern of wide and narrow rings,''
Baillie said. You can then go back to ancient timbers from
buildings, for example, and measure the ring patterns, and if they
overlap in time, you should be able to link those patterns
together.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 16</NOTE>
