<HEAD>Stocks Down, Dollar Lower In Morning Tokyo Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning closing figure. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices dropped in morning trading Tuesday on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange, while the U.S. dollar fell slightly in
foreign exchange.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which rose to
its second highest level ever on Monday, lost 102.39 points to
finish the morning session at 27,934.15.
   On Monday, the market's main barometer closed at 28,036.54
points, just 35.48 points short of its record high registered last
Thursday.
   ``A wait-and-see position spread in morning trading'' among many
market participants prior to the release of U.S. monthly trade
figures for April, slated for later Tuesday in Washington, said
Minoru Maeda of Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   Maeda declined to say what Japanese investors expected the April
figures to reach.
   Kin Ogino of the securities firm Goldman Sachs said the stock
market dropped because of profit-taking following its recent ascent
and because of the upcoming U.S. figures.
   In foreign exchange, the dollar opened at 125.15 yen, down from
Monday's close of 125.19 yen, and traded between 125.05-125.18 yen
before closing the morning session at 125.07 yen.
</TEXT>
