<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of Transportation Jim
Burnley proposed a drug testing program for interstate drivers of
large trucks and passenger buses to make the nation's highways
safer.
   Burnley's announcement Friday follows similar proposals unveiled
in March for the aviation industry and in May for railroads.
   He cited a June 1987 test of 317 tractor-trailer drivers in
Tennessee that showed 15 percent of the drivers tested positive for
marijuana, cocaine or prescription stimulants.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission moved
toward tightening the requirements for deciding whether mutual
funds can describe themselves as ``no-load'' funds.
   In no-load funds, which many investors prefer, no sales fee is
charged. But, since 1980, no-load funds have been allowed to use
some of the money from investors to pay for certain sales and
promotional expenses.
   The commission voted 4-0 Friday to ask for comment on a proposal
that would tighten regulation of how these expenses are assessed
against mutual funds. It would also prohibit funds that assess
these hidden charges from describing themselves as no-load funds.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's leading exchange for platinum
futures, faced with a shortage of elbow room, has accepted an offer
to move its platinum trading pit to the floor of the world's
leading gold and silver exchange, officials said.
   The agreement between the Commodity Exchange, the premier market
for gold and silver futures, and the New York Mercantile Exchange
will require approval by the Commodity Futures Trading Commission,
officials said Friday.
</TEXT>
