<1ST_LINE>r f PM-VideoYearbooks     06-13 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Video Yearbooks,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yearbooks Now Filmed Instead of Printed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Still pictures and written words may capture
high school and college graduates' best memories but a video
yearbook is what's needed to really go beyond the sounds of
silence, students and industry executives say.
   ``There are a number of pitches we use,'' said Bob Levitan,
president of Durham, N.C.-based Yearbook Enterprises. ``It brings
those black and white photos to life by capturing the excitement
and emotion that a print yearbook can't always do.''
   Levitan said his company, like others in the field, don't try to
undercut sales of the traditional yearbook but offer the video as a
supplement.
   Videos cost between $20 and $40 depending on their length, which
can range from 30 minutes to 90 minutes.
   A yearbook, which must go to print midway through the second
half of the school year, cannot always include things like senior
prom and graduation.
   Yearbook Enterprises works with about 50 colleges and high
schools in teaching students how to use video equipment and buying
the rights to songs that young filmmakers want to use as background
music.
   ``It's educational,'' said Levitan, who filmed Duke University's
yearbook for two years before graduating in 1983. ``Students grew
up watching MTV. This is an opportunity to create with video.
They're creating their own MTV.''
   One student attracted by the idea was John Zager, an 18-year-old
senior at Lawrenceville Prep.
   He has coordinated filming and sales of his school's video
yearbook, which sells for $39.95, for the past two years. He said
sales expanded this year because more students became aware of a
video's knack to recapture the feeling of student plays and
homecoming football games.
   ``There's something about sitting down and watching events in
color,'' said Zager, of Wayne. ``It gives you an honest sense of
the school.''
   Princeton junior Caroline Havens, who worked on her school's
30-minute video, agreed.
   ``This is a more living type of yearbook,'' said the 20-year
junior from New London, Conn. ``We don't try to downplay
(traditional) yearbooks but this is a lot more lively.''
   The video yearbook companies take different approaches. At
Campus Camera, a New Jersey company co-founded by two former
cameramen from an Atlantic City television station, the philosophy
is ``leave the filmmaking to us.''
   ``Our quality of equipment is equivalent to a TV station,''
co-owner David Pashuck said. ``I wouldn't hand that over to a
student.''
   Pashuck said students also might tend to only film their
friends. Outside cameramen prevent that and guarantee a quality
product.
   And Pashuck and his partner have enjoyed their first year with
the two schools _ Mainland Regional High School in Linwood and
Mater Dei High School in Middletown _ that they've worked with.
   Pashuck said Campus Camera, like other video yearbook
enterprises, will grow in the years ahead by capitalizing on
people's expanding familiarity with video equipment.
   Steve Sullivan, the 30-year-old head of Dallas-based Video
Yearbook Inc., said the job brings smiles in addition to profits.
   ``I've been doing some of the shooting myself,'' Sullivan said.
``The excitement _ you forget about it once you get out of high
school. This is one way to keep it forever.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
