<HEAD>Stocks Go Up With Dollar</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, On the ..., with one graf to CORRECT
closing dollar figure. Picks up 8th graf pvs, The dollar ... A
version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange today rose to
their second highest level ever, and the U.S. dollar also
strengthened against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 151.66-point
loser on Friday, closed at 28,036.54, up 116.18 points, or 0.41
percent. It was 35.48 points short of its record high on Thursday,
when it closed at 28,072.02.
   Volume was a moderate 900 million shares, down sharply from
Friday's 2.2 billion.
   A stock analyst at a Tokyo brokerage, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said traders were awaiting the release in Washington on
Tuesday of U.S. trade figures for April.
   Little news was available to affect the Tokyo market, because
Sunday was a newspaper holiday in Japan and no papers appeared
today.
   Electricals, automobiles, precision machineries and drugs rose,
along with financial and foodstuff issues. Steels, textiles and
chemicals fell.
   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at
125.19 yen, up 0.34 yen from Friday's finish.
   ``The dollar was supported by favorable prospects for the U.S.
trade figures for April,'' said a foreign exchange dealer, also
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   But trading was sluggish, and the dollar moved in a narrow range
of 125.00-125.20 yen. Dealers were waiting for the trade data
before placing major orders, he said.
   An exchange dealer at another commercial bank said the dollar
rose on a weekend remark by the vice chairman of the U.S. Federal
Reserve Board. Manuel Johnson told reporters Saturday in West
Germany he thought ``there would be a certain tolerance for (the
dollar to rise).''
</TEXT>
