<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Ashland'sImage     06-13 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ashland's Image,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>For Ashland Oil, 1988 Has Been Good and Bad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHLAND, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Ashland Oil Inc., 1988 has been one
public relations disaster after another.
   First there was an oil spill. Then there were complaints about
pollution. Now a federal trial has gone against it.
   It all started Jan. 2 when a 4-million-gallon storage tank
collapsed near Pittsburgh, sending more than 700,000 gallons of
diesel fuel into the Monongahela and Ohio rivers in one of the
worst inland oil spills in U.S. history.
   Two weeks later, the company was fined $95,000 for violating air
pollution standards at its Catlettsburg refinery.
   State air quality officials received 80 complaints from nearby
residents during three weeks in February and March.
   In mid-March, a report by the federal Environmental Protection
Agency said Ashland had violated regulations at its hazardous-waste
dump near the refinery.
   But perhaps the biggest public relations problem of all hit
Friday, when a U.S. District Court jury in Covington ruled that the
company engaged in racketeering in 1980 when it made payments to
foreign government officials to obtain crude oil.
   The jury awarded nearly $70 million to former vice presidents
Bill McKay and Harry Williams, who said they had been fired for
refusing to take part in the payments and for telling U.S.
government agencies about the money.
   Ashland Oil, which is Kentucky's largest corporation and the
nation's largest independent oil refiner, said it would appeal.
Whether the awards are whittled down by higher courts remains to be
seen, but the company expects any payment to be covered by a $75
million policy with Home Insurance Co.
   Money aside, however, observers say Ashland has an image problem.
   ``The public perception is that something must be wrong if it
(the case) has gone this far,'' said Larry Lad, an assistant
professor of management at Indiana University.
   Louisville attorney Charles H. Zimmerman Jr. said some lawyers
following the case figured Ashland would win by persuading jurors
its past business practices were commonplace.
   Zimmerman said the jury's decision may reflect some anger among
consumers. ``There is the feeling that big business _ the Fortune
500 companies _ have gotten away with murder,'' he said.
   A public explanation might improve Ashland's image, suggested
Gerald Meyers, former chairman of American Motors Corp. and author
of ``When It Hits the Fan,'' a book on corporate crises.
   ``The way to lose in the court of public opinion is to hide
behind your lawyers,'' Meyers said.
   He said the burden of repairing the company's public image rests
with its current chairman, John Hall. ``Nobody is as believable as
the chief executive officer,'' Meyers said.
   That's a notion Hall reinforced in January, when he drew
national praise for publicly discussing the massive oil spill.
   Ashland spokesman Dan Lacy said Saturday that he thinks Hall
will make a statement, although it won't come until the company
files legal motions related to Friday's decision. Ashland has 10
days to do so.
   Lacy said the public relations problems have masked an otherwise
good financial year for the company.
   In the six months that ended March 31, Ashland earned $67
million, not including a one-time gain of $31 million, compared
with $22 million a year earlier. Revenue also rose, to $3.9 billion
from $3.2 billion in 1987.
   ``If you really want to know how the year has been for the
company, it has been very good,'' Lacy said. ``I think the
shareholders are pleased by the performance of the company.
   Ashland has interests in petroleum, coal, chemicals and
construction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880613-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 0940EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru f0021 06-13 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0021,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Generally Higher in Sluggish Trading, Gold Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-14 with one graf to tighten. Picks up 15 graf
pvs, In London ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against most major currencies in
early European trading today, and dealers said activity would
remain sluggish until Tuesday's release of the latest U.S. trade
figures.
   Gold prices fell in Europe from Friday's closing bids but were
up slightly from the late bid price in New York. Gold plunged
almost $7 an ounce in New York on Friday to $449 after European
markets closed, largely because of falling oil prices.
   Foreign exchange dealers in Frankfurt said the dollar received
support from a remark by U.S. Federal Reserve Board Vice Chairman
Manuel Johnson on Saturday. He said there is some room for the
currency to rise.
   But traders said the market will remain hard to move until
release of the U.S. April trade deficit. Frankfurt dealers
predicted the deficit would show a widening to $12.2 billion from
an adjusted $11.95 billion in March.
   ``Everyone's waiting for the figures,'' said a dealer at a large
Frankfurt bank.
   ``Very little business will be done today,'' predicted one
trader with a major Italian commercial bank in Milan. Both spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar closed at 125.19 yen, up from 124.85 late
Friday. Later, in London, it was quoted slightly higher at 125.12
yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Friday's
rates: 1.7221 West German marks, up from 1.7180; 1.4425 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4355 5.8220 French francs, up from 5.8040; 1.9133
Dutch guilders, down from 1.9280; 1,281.65 Italian lire, up from
1,278.50; and 1.22075 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2191.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.8250 to buy one pound, up from $1.8175.
   Bullion dealers said trading was also quiet pending Tuesday's
release of U.S. trade figures.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $451.10 a troy ounce and
at mid-morning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $450.50, both down from late Friday's bid of
$456.20.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $450.50, down from $458.00 late
Friday.
   Hong Kong financial markets were closed today to celebrate the
official birthday of Queen Elizabeth II.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.98 a troy
ounce, down from 7.17 late Friday.
