<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Texaco-Icahn 1stLd-Writethru f0009 06-13 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco-Icahn, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0009,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Icahn Says He Talked with Two Canadian Firms and Citibank About
Buying Texaco</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing throughout.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover strategist Carl C. Icahn says he
discussed a joint acquisition of Texaco Inc. with two Canadian oil
concerns and that Citibank verbally agreed to finance such a deal.
   The disclosures were contained in a weekend deposition of
Texaco's largest shareholder conducted by attorneys for the oil
giant, reported today by the Wall Street Journal.
   The deposition was part of escalating legal maneuvers between
Icahn and Texaco over his attempt to buy the company for $60 a
share, which values it at $14.6 billion.
   Icahn and Texaco have been engrossed in an acrimonious takeover
dispute since last month, the latest episode in the troubled oil
giant's attempt to normalize following its prolonged
bankruptcy-court ordeal.
   The investor, who owns 14.8 percent of Texaco stock, is
conducting a proxy fight for five seats on the company's board in
an effort to pressure management into letting shareholders vote on
his takeover offer. Results of the proxy contest will be disclosed
at the company's annual meeting this Friday.
   Icahn disclosed to Texaco lawyers that in the last two weeks he
held separate discussions toward a possible takeover partnership
with Gulf Canada Ltd. and Husky Oil Ltd. Icahn also said a Citibank
representative assured him that financing a Texaco takeover was
``eminently doable.''
   His disclosures could substantiate Texaco's claim that Icahn has
improperly failed to disclose the extent of his takeover talks with
other parties. Icahn has denied any wrongdoing.
   Other court documents unsealed at the request of the New York
Times indicate Icahn once tried to arrange the purchase of a large
stake in Texaco held by the investment firm Kohlberg, Kravis,
Roberts & Co. to Canadian investor Marc Belzberg, but the deal
never happened because of a price disagreement.
   Texaco attorneys say those documents suggest Icahn may have
improperly attempted to find allies for coordinated purchases of
Texaco stock as part of a broader plan to take over the company.
Icahn has denied such charges in the past.
   On Friday, Icahn said he was forming a new holding company to
act as his sole vehicle for acquisitions, including a bid for
Texaco. He said the holding company intended to raise up to $3.25
billion through an offering of stock and debt securities.
   The Icahn group of companies also will contribute equity to the
holding company, including its 36.1 million shares of Texaco and
its interests in Trans World Airlines Inc. and ACF, a leasing
company.
   Icahn began acquiring Texaco stock last year when the company
was mired in bankruptcy-court proceedings and its stock was trading
$20 lower than the current price of about $51 a share.
   Texaco sought federal bankruptcy protection in April 1987 when
it faced a record $10.53 billion judgment to Pennzoil Co. awarded
by a Texas jury that found Texaco improperly interfered with
Pennzoil's attempt to buy Getty Oil Co. Texaco settled with
Pennzoil two months ago by paying it $3 billion and has proposed a
post-bankruptcy recovery involving the sale of $5 billion in assets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
