<1ST_LINE>u f PM-OPEC 1stLd-Writethru f0023 06-13 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-OPEC, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0023,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Meet Informally To Discuss Production Quota</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBs 2nd graf pvs, The Organization ..., with one graf to
delete erroneous reference reference to proposed new limit. A
version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC ministers today met informally to
discuss whether to change their existing oil production quota, amid
speculation that the talks have stalled.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries on Sunday
adjourned its regular midyear conference to allow the 13-nation
cartel's oil ministers to informally discuss disagreements.
   The conference began Saturday and will resume Tuesday.
   The ministers have been considering whether to change an
existing agreement among 12 of the members that limits their oil
production to 15.06 million barrels a day.
   That quota, which was extended in December and expires June 30,
was aimed at supporting oil prices at $18 a barrel.
   Iraq has refused to sign the agreement because it wants an
output quota equal to that of Iran. Iraq, at war with Iran since
September 1980, was granted a quota of 1.54 million barrels a day
in a previous agreement. Iran's daily quota is 2.369 million
barrels.
   Some OPEC members want to cut production to push oil prices up,
while others want to increase output or at least hold it steady to
take advantage of an expected increase in demand later this year.
   But analysts believe OPEC is so deeply divided it will extend
the existing agreement for at least three months.
   ``We are working on compromise,'' Indonesian oil minister
Ginandjar Kartasasmita said today. ``There are agreements on most
of the issues.''
   He said he strongly believed the cartel would make a decision
either Tuesday or Wednesday.
   ``There will definitely be an agreement,'' added Saudi Arabian
oil minister Hisham Nazer.
   But ministerial sources from two countries also said Sunday that
the cartel _ expecting a stalemate _ was most likely to extend the
current production quota.
   ``There's a degree of disappointment and confusion,'' said Alan
Sinclair, an oil analyst at the London investment firm Smith New
Court Ltd.
   Adding to the confusion was the departure of two Arab oil
ministers, with one expected to return by Tuesday but the other
saying he might not.
   Mana Saeed Oteiba, the United Arab Emirates' oil minister, said
Sunday he was returning to his country for consultations with his
government and that he might or might not return. He gave no reason
for his sudden departure.
   Kuwaiti Oil Minister Ali Khalifa Sabah will leave today, but
will return in time for the Tuesday session, members of his
delegation said.
   Observers speculated that Sabah was going to London to appear
before the British government's Monopolies and Mergers Commission
about Kuwait's purchase of more than 20 percent of British
Petroleum Co. earlier this year.
   ``The fact that Oteiba must consult with his supeiors is very
reminiscent of a stall. It's awfully convenient, isn't it?'' said
Peter Gignoux, managing director of the international energy
department at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in London.
   Oil markets were disappointing today, with the spot price of
North Sea Brent Blend, the most widely traded international crude
oil, falling to 55 cents to $15.30 a barrel and then held steady on
the spot market.
   The 13 members of the cartel are Algeria, Ecuador, Gabon,
Indonesia, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia,
United Arab Emirates and Venezuela.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
