<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Mostly Lower In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened
mostly higher then turned mostly lower today as rainy weather
dampened bullish enthusiasm on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat futures were lower from the start, reflecting weekend
rains in the drought-stricken northern Plains, analysts said.
Reports of rain today in the western Corn Belt quickly put soybean
and corn traders on edge and prices for those commodities turned
lower as well.
   ``Some traders are very nervous about rain showing up (in the
central Midwest) in the next three days,'' said Victor Lespinasse,
a trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   He noted that the November soybean contract, for delivery of
new-crop beans, fluctuated within a 9-cent range in the session's
opening minutes. ``That shows you the amount of hesitancy and
uncertainty here,'' Lespinasse said.
   Oat futures continued to climb on the perception that dry
conditions have already destroyed part of the U.S. oat crop,
analysts said.
   In early trading, wheat was 3 cents to 6\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.68 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to
3\ cents lower with July at $2.56 a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 6
cents higher with July at $2.66 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to
16 cents lower with July at $8.70 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were lower while pork futures were mixed in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent to .70 cent lower with June at 71.90
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .50 cent lower with
August at 74.90 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent lower to .40 cent
higher with June at 51.30 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.27 cent lower to .10 cent higher with July at 49.80 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed mixed on Friday.
</TEXT>
