<DOCNO> AP880613-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Scotus-Securities 2ndLd-Writethru f0063 06-13 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Securities, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0063,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Allows Bank Subsidiaries To Deal In Some Securities</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS one graf after penultimate graf bgng ``But we are ...
'' to update with American Bankers Association comment; Also moved
on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today allowed banks to use
subsidiaries to engage in underwriting and dealing in some
securities.
   The court, over two dissenting votes, let stand a ruling that
such activity does not violate a 1933 law aimed primarily at
protecting the financial stability of banks by restricting them
from speculating in stocks and bonds.
   Justices Harry A. Blackmun and Sandra Day O'Connor voted to hear
arguments in the case, but four votes are needed to grant such
review.
   The 1933 federal law, the Glass-Steagall Act, was passed by
Congress in the wake of the stock market crash of 1929.
   The law placed various restrictions on banks, in large measure
to protect deposits from being squandered on Wall Street.
   In recent years, the wall of separation between commercial and
investment bank activities has been lowered.
   At issue in the case acted on today were rulings by the Federal
Reserve Board allowing some of the nation's leading banks to use
subsidiaries to underwrite and deal in municipal revenue bonds,
mortgage-related securities and commercial paper. The latter is a
form of IOU used by corporations to finance short-term debt.
   The Federal Reserve Board last year said bank subsidiaries may
underwrite and deal in such securities as long as they do not
exceed 5 to 10 percent of the subsidary's gross revenue.
   The board said that is in line with the Glass-Stegall Act's
requirement that banks may not affiliate with an organization
``engaged principally'' in underwriting or dealing in securities.
   The board's rulings were challenged by the Securities Industry
Association, a trade group of underwriters, brokers andd securities
dealers.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in February upheld the
Federal Reserve Board decisions, and the Reagan administration
urged the justices to leave intact the appeals court rulng.
   Justice Department lawyers said the Federal Reserve Board acted
properly, and that any change in banking regulations should be left
to Congress.
   The government noted that a moratorium Congress imposed on the
type of banking activities involved in the dispute expired in
March, and Congress has not renewed it. Moreover, legislation is
pending to repeal parts of the Glass-Steagall Act.
   Reacting to today's decision, Edward I. O'Brien, president of
the Securities Industry Association, said, ``We are disappointed
the Supreme Court decided not to hear our appeal to prevent banks,
through affiliates, from engaging in a wide range of securities.''
   ``But we are pleased the Federal Reserve itself has erected a
series of firewalls ... to prevent banks from taking excessive
risks within the securities arena which would further weaken banks
and thus endanger the nation's economy,'' O'Brien said.
   Charles Pistor, president of the American Bankers Association,
said, ``This is another hole in the anti-competitive Glass-Steagall
Act and another important victory for consumers. But, before large
numbers of bank customers will benefit, we need to repeal the
Glass-Steagall Act and allow all banks to offer securities
services.''
   The case is Securities Industry Association vs. Federal Reserve
System, 87-1513.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880613-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1402EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-USPoll     06-13 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-US Poll,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noboru Who? Poll Reveals Americans' Ignorance Of Japanese Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A poll released Monday found that only four of
1,500 Americans could name the Japanese prime minister, while 90
percent of 2,000 Japanese knew the U.S. president was named Ronald
Reagan.
   For the record, the Japanese leader is Noboru Takeshita, the
leader of Japan's dominant Liberal Democratic Party, who succeeded
Yasuhiro Nakasone as prime minister seven months ago after serving
as finance minister in Nakasone's cabinet.
   The poll was conducted jointly in May by the Tokyo Broadcasting
System and CBS. Most of the questions involved trade issues.
   Seventy-two percent of the Americans polled said they favored
protection for domestic agricultural markets, while about 60
percent of the 2,000 Japanese surveyed said the same about their
markets.
   Forty-three percent of Americans said Japan's barriers on
imports of U.S. beef and citrus fruit were improper, and only 14
percent considered them fair.
   Among Japanese respondents, 59 percent said the restrictions
were fair and 29 percent unfair.
   The network released the survey results on its news programs one
day before Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Michael Smith reopens
stalemated talks with Japanese officials over beef and orange
imports in Tokyo.
   Japan has said it will phase out beef import restrictions over a
three-year period, but needs a 70 percent tariff on U.S. beef to
keep prices in line with domestic levels. U.S. officials want a
substantially lower tariff.
   U.S. negotiators are also expected to urge Japan to liberalize
its citrus market in three years, instead of the five-year period
proposed by Tokyo.
   The margin of error in the poll was not specified.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
