<DOCNO> AP880613-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1414EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     06-13 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0447</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market held its ground in afternoon
trading today after recovering from an early bout of profit-taking.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up .89 points at
2,102.60 at mid-afternoon.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 91.86 million shares at 2 p.m.
on Wall Street. Gainers outnumbered losers by about 6 to 5 with 742
up, 614 down and 526 unchanged.
   ``The most revealing thing about this market is that ... we
can't drive it down,'' noted Gene Jay Seagle, vice president and
director of technical research at Gruntal Financial Inc.
   ``The ability of the Dow to hug the 2,100 level is a signal that
this market has started some kind of a summer rally, and I don't
think it's over,'' he said.
   The Dow started the week about eight points shy of its
post-crash high, and traders began the session by cashing in on the
previous weeks' gains. The initial downturn surprised some market
watchers who were counting on strength in the bond market to spill
over and support equities.
   The Dow had been off about 10 points before turning upward.
``Characteristically, in the absence of any negative news, the
market has been rallying,'' said Charles Jensen, chief technical
analyst at MKI Securities Corp.
   ``Every time it dips, there are bargain hunters out there flush
with cash'' who buy equities, he said.
   Many expect traders will be keeping a sharp eye on the
merchandise trade report for April, due to be released on Tuesday.
But traders are likely to be more interested in the trend than the
actual deficit figure.
   A flurry of other economic indicators is also due to be released
this week, including retail sales, industrial production, business
inventories, factory capacity and housing starts.
   With plenty of cash on the sidelines, some analysts speculated
that investors may be waiting for clearer signals about the economy
before jumping back into the market.
   Among actively traded issues, Texaco was off 1} at 50[. Carl C.
Icahn said he has held talks with Gulf Canada Ltd. and Husky Oil
Ltd. about the possibility of forming a joint venture to acquire
Texaco.
   IBM was up 1\ at 117\; Digital Equipment was up 1\ at 112];
Chrysler was up 1 at 24{; Union Carbide was up { at 21, and NCR was
up 2] at 66~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 0.20 at 153.09. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off 1.26 at 308.07.
</TEXT>
