<HEAD>London Shares Fall Amid Jitters over U.S. Trade Gap</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later trading activity; No
pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed lower on the London Stock
Exchange Monday amid a bout of jitters ahead of Tuesday's scheduled
release of U.S. trade figures for April.
   At the close of trading, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index was down 11.0 points, or 0.59 percent, at 1,838.8.
The low for the day was 1,833.3, while the high _ registered as the
market opened for trading _ was 1,848.9.
   Volume was a thin 316.2 million shares, down from Friday's 497.6
million shares.
   In New York, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was 0.53
points higher at 2,102.24 by the end of the London trading session,
having been down about 12 points earlier. However, London equities
were not able to shake off the negative influence of Wall Street.
   The U.S. April trade figures were expected to show a slight
widening of the trade deficit to $12.2 billion from the revised
$11.95 billion shortfall in March.
   One London analyst said that as share prices fell on Wall
Street, ``People in London started to think, `What do they know
that we don't know about the trade figures?'''
   The lack of decisive news from the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries meeting in Vienna, Austria, combined with lower
gold prices, depressed oil and mining stocks.
</TEXT>
