<HEAD>Bloomingdale's Announces 2 Percent Job Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bloomingdale's announced Monday it was laying
off 245 employees, or nearly 2 percent of its work force, as part
of the cuts ordered by Campeau Corp. at Federated Department Store
Inc. divisions.
   Bloomingdale's, with 14,000 employees, was the last Federated
department store division to announce layoffs. Eighty-six employees
were let go from Bloomingdale's organization offices, while 159
were cut from its stores and catalog operation.
   No sales positions were eliminated, Bloomingdale's said in a
statement.
   There had been reports Bloomingdale's expected to lay off 400
employees. The company said Monday some jobs were saved through
transfers and by the assignment of personnel to the chain's Chicago
store, which is scheduled to open in September.
   Campeau ordered cuts at all Federated divisions after it took
control of the retailer last month. Layoffs were earlier announced
among Federated's corporate staff and at the Abraham and Straus,
Burdine's, Goldsmith's, Lazarus and Rich's divisions.
   Industry observers have said the cuts were long overdue.
However, some Wall Street analysts said there may be adverse
effects on merchandise selection as a result of the layoffs.
</TEXT>
