<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Mostly Lower On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed
mostly lower Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts
for rain in the Midwest later this week.
   But corn futures finished slighly higher, reflecting uncertainty
about the amount of moisture that drought-ridden croplands are
likely to receive, analysts said.
   ``There is some rain coming in and the market, at least today,
felt it would be beneficial'' for the crops, said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Volume was markedly lighter than in last week's sessions, which
saw grain and soybean futures rise dramatically as traders bet on a
lengthy dry spell. Soybean futures rose last week to more than $9 a
bushel, a 4{-year high.
   Rain dampened wheat fields in the northern Plains on Sunday and
showers were reported moving eastward from the western edge of the
Corn Belt on Monday.
   ``There were a lot of traders on the sidelines, watching, hoping
and praying,'' Lespinasse said.
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents to 5 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.69{ a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 2{ cents higher with July at $2.59 a bushel; oats were
6 cents lower to 2 cents higher with July at $2.62 a bushel;
soybeans were 2{ cents to 8 cents lower with July at $8.78 a bushel.
  
</TEXT>
