<FILEID>AP-NR-06-13-88 1721EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Scotus-Vaccine-Reax     06-13 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Vaccine-Reax,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Industry Reacts to Supreme Courts' Vaccine Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MORAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Supreme Court ruling Monday on
vaccine liability likely affects only a small group of
pharmaceutical manufacturers, but may substantially change how the
government approves future inoculations, industry analysts said.
   The nation's high court said those harmed by a vaccine can sue
the government agencies that approved its use.
   ``This is very good for the vaccine companies, but there are not
that many of them,'' said Richard Vieter, a drug industry analyst
with Merrill Lynch Co. ``One might look ahead to vaccines such as
AIDS vaccines and other bio-tech applications, though.
   ``It seems the government will have to exert quite a bit more
care in the approval process to prevent placing the government in a
liability situation,'' Vieter said.
   The court, in a 9-0 vote, reinstated a suit by the parents of a
Pennsylvania boy who contracted polio after receiving a dose of a
federally approved vaccine manufactured by Lederle Laboratories of
Wayne, N.J., a subsidiary of American Cyanimid.
   Richard Stover, an analyst with Smith Barney in New York, said
the question of whether the government can be held liable for
approving drugs and vaccines that eventually harm someone has been
hotly debated for years.
   ``It should be very significant for that part of the industry
and Lederle in particular,'' he said.
   Martha Homma, a spokesman for Lederle, said the company's top
executives and legal department want to study the decision before
issuing a comment.
   Lederle shares the majority of the vaccine production business
in the United States with Merck Co. of Rahway, N.J., American Home
Products' Wyeth Division of New York and CDC Life Sciences Inc., a
Canadian company.
   Officials from American Home Products and Merck Co. also
declined to comment, though one Merck executive said ``it's about
time'' the government is held accountable for the approval process.
   Mark Grayson, a spokesman for the Pharmaceutical Manufacturers'
Association, said the group's legal department also wants to study
the decision before any statement is made.
   Justice Department lawyers argued before the court that if such
damage suits are allowed, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration,
which currently tests and licenses vaccines, may be forced into the
business of insuring them, jeopardizing the entire drug-approval
process.
   The polio vaccine Orimun, a form of Sabin oral vaccine, was
administered to 3-month-old Kevan Berkovitz in 1979. Three months
later, the child contracted polio and is now paralyzed, partially
deformed and can breathe only with the help of a machine.
   The vaccine was approved by the federal government in 1963. The
Berkovitz's suit was rejected by the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Philadelphia in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880613-0290 </DOCNO>
