<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-13 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Slightly Higher; Gold Rises After Falling in Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose slightly Monday, but brokers
said trading was extremely quiet prior to the release of monthly
U.S. trade figures and the Toronto economic summit.
   Gold prices also advanced slightly in restrained U.S. trading
after falling more than $7 an ounce in Europe. Republic National
Bank of New York quoted gold at $449.70 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m.
EDT, up from $449 late Friday.
   Foreign-exchange dealers attributed the sluggish trading partly
to their own reluctance to speculate about the dollar's movement
prior to the Commerce Department's report on the U.S. trade deficit
for April, due Tuesday morning.
   The trade numbers are a powerful influence on the dollar because
they have become the most visible symbol of the United States'
unrelenting appetite for imports, a sensitive political and
economic issue.
   The nation's deficit shrank to a three-year low of $9.7 billion
in March, surprising many traders and giving the dollar a
substantial boost. But some fear the March number was grossly low
and the April deficit could therefore be unexpectedly high, despite
a strengthening of U.S. exports in recent months.
   Estimates on the April deficit ranged from below $9 billion to
above $14.5 billion.
   ``Each number has exasperated traders because it is so
unpredictable,'' said Frank Watson, vice president and chief
corporate dealer in Swiss Bank Corp.'s New York office. ``But last
month's numbers were so good that the chances of a surprise seem
sort of big.''
   Varick Martin, vice president of foreign exchange at Union Bank
of Switzerland's office in New York, said another big restraint on
trading is the summit of leaders of seven industrialized
democracies, starting Sunday in Toronto.
   ``I can't expect anything to happen (to the dollar), even with
the trade numbers, until the Toronto summit is over,'' he said.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 125.19 Japanese yen, up slightly
from 124.85 yen late Friday. Later in London, the dollar was quoted
at 125.10 yen. By the time trading concluded in New York, the
dollar was worth 125.12 yen, higher than its 124.88 yen on Friday.
   The British pound fell in London to $1.8165 from $1.8175 late
Friday. Later in New York the pound was quoted at $1.8165, cheaper
than $1.8178 late Friday.
   Other late-dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday,
included: 1.7227 West German marks, up from 1.7211; 1.4407 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4391; 1.2207 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2199;
5.8195 French francs, up from 5.8135; and 1,280.25 Italian lire, up
from 1,278.88.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday,
included: 1.7241 West German marks, up from 1.7180; 1.4424 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4355; 5.7265 French francs, down from 5.8040;
1.9345 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9280; 1,281.75 Italian lire, up
from 1,278.50; 1.2203 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2191.
   Gold futures prices rose slightly in U.S. trading. On the
Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for immediate delivery
was quoted at $449.60 an ounce, up 50 cents from late Friday.
   Earlier in London gold fell to $449 from $456.20 late Friday. In
Zurich, Switzerland, gold closed at a bid price of $448.50, down
from $458 late Friday. The sharp drops were largely a response to a
plunge in U.S. gold prices late Friday because of falling oil
prices, after European markets had closed.
   Hong Kong markets were closed Monday for a holiday.
   Silver traded in London at a late bid price of $7.02 a troy
ounce, down from $7.17 late Friday. On the New York Comex, silver
was quoted at $7.025, up 4 cents.
</TEXT>
