<HEAD>J&J Announces Stock Buyback, Plan To Issue Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Johnson & Johnson said Monday it
would buy back up to $500 million worth of its stock and seek
permission to issue $500 million in debt, both for ``general
corporate purposes.''
   The stock buyback would account for about 6.4 million shares of
the drug and health care giant's 172.4 million common shares
outstanding.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Johnson & Johnson
jumped $1.62{ to close at $79.12{ a share.
   Spokesman Robert Kniffen said the company must file its plans
with the Securities and Exchange Commission to issue up to $500
million of debt or debt warrants.
   Analysts took the announcement in stride.
   ``They, like a lot of drug companies, have plenty of money and
not much to do with it,'' said Michael A. Martorelli, an analyst
with Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. in Philadelphia.
   He said the amount of the stock buy-back was not large in light
of Johnson & Johnson's financial base of about $900 million in cash
and securities.
</TEXT>
