<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Braniff     06-13 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Braniff,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prospective Owner Says It Plans to Expand Airline, No Layoffs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor group planning to acquire Braniff
Inc. for about $100 million said Monday that it intends to expand
the airline and will guarantee job security to Braniff employees
for at least three years.
   The announcement came three days after Braniff's majority owner,
the Pritzker family of Chicago, said it would sell its 64 percent
stake to an investor group formed by Paine Webber Group Inc.
   Braniff has struggled financially for years and lost an
estimated $100 million in the Prizkers' first year of ownership in
1983. It lost $9.02 million in 1987.
   Paine Webber said in a statement Monday that the investor group
it leads ``plans to expand Braniff and has no plans to reduce the
size of Braniff's aircraft fleet or to withdraw from any cities
presently served by the airline.''
   In addition, Paine Webber said the prospective new owners intend
to enter into agreements with Braniff's labor unions to protect
employee job security for at least three years.
   The statement also said the new owners intend to sell
unidentified airport leasing interests and rights to American
Airlines. A price wasn't disclosed.
   Braniff has a 35-aircraft fleet and operates mainly out of hubs
at Dallas and Kansas City.
</TEXT>
