<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AmericanBrands-E-II     06-13 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American Brands-E-II,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Brands To Sell E-II</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Brands Inc. announced Monday it
is selling its subsidiary E-II Holdings, acquired recently in a
takeover duel, to an affiliate of the privately held Riklis Family
Corp. for $950 million in cash and $250 million in securities.
   American Brands, based in Greenwich, said it will buy back seven
companies including five that it expects will accelerate
development of its emerging core businesses in hardware and home
products and office products.
   The company also said it planned to continue an ongoing program
to buy back its own stock.
   The E-II companies being retained by American Brands include
Aristokraft Inc., Waterloo Industries Inc., and Twentieth Century
Companies Inc. as well as Day-Timers Inc. and the Vogel Peterson
Co., previously acquired from E-II by American Brands' ACCO World
subsidiary.
   American Brands will also buy back from E-II two other
operations _ the Stiffel Co. and Aunt Nellie's Farm Kitchens Inc.
   American Brands said Riklis will pay about $950 million in cash
and $250 million in preferred stock for the remaining operations of
E-II Holdings. E-II also has $1.5 billion in subordinated debt.
   The purchase price for all the companies being retained by
American Brands _not including Stiffel and Aunt Nellie's, still in
negotiation _ is $645 million.
   American Brands acquired the outstanding common stock of
Chicago-based E-II in February for $17.05 per share in a deal worth
about $1.1 billion.
   The acquisition followed a brief but fierce battle in which
American Brands launched a bid to take over E-II after the
Chicago-based company said it might try to acquire American Brands
by gaining control of the company's board of directors through a
shareholder vote.
   The move employed successfully by American Brands is nicknamed
the ``Pac Man'' defense after a popular video game in which a
player tries to swallow his enemy before being eaten himself.
   Analysts were not surprised at Monday's announcement of American
Brands' intent to sell some E-II companies.
   ``They have said all along they wil sell portions of E-II,'' Roy
Burry, senior vice president of research at Kidder Peabody Co. said.
   Burry said the deal ``turned out well'' for American Brands and
the ``shareholders of E-II got rich because of the price they got
for their stock.''
   American Brands Chairman and Chief Executive officer William J.
Alley said the company expects the transactions ``to produce a
positive impact on earnings per share in 1988 and even better
returns next year.''
   The companies being sold with E-II include Culligan
International Co., Samsonite Corp., Samsonite Furniture Co., Home
Fashions Inc., Lowrey's Meat Specialities Inc., Beatreme Food
Ingredients Inc., Frozen Specialities Inc., Pet Specialities Inc.
and Martha White Foods Inc.
   Riklis also owns Rapid American Corp., McCrory Stores and
Faberge-Elizabeth Arden.
</TEXT>
