<2ND_LINE>AM-Airplane Order,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SAS Orders Up to 61 MD-80 Jets From McDonnell Douglas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonnell Douglas Corp. has received a
$1.5 billion order for 61 of its MD-80 series airplanes from
Scandinavian Airlines System, the aircraft maker announced Monday.
   The order includes firm commitments to buy 24 planes and an
option to buy 37 more. The $1.5 billion figure is for all 61
planes. McDonnell Douglas declined to put a value on firm orders
alone, spokesman Don Hansen said.
   Based on the estimated price of $22 million to $25 million which
industry sources put on the MD-80, the firm orders would be worth
around $900 million.
   SAS ordered four models of the MD-80, a twin-engine,
medium-range jetliner that seats up to 150 passengers. The order is
divided among MD-81, 82, 83 and 87 models. The planes are scheduled
for delivery in 1991 and 1992.
</TEXT>
