<1ST_LINE>u f AM-HungryMigrants 1stLd-Writethru f0251 06-13 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungry Migrants, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0251,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Work Arrives for Migrants as Strawberries Ripen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT to northwestern sted northeastern.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES E. BEGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of migrant workers are picking
strawberries after waiting weeks for crops to ripen and straining
the resources of social service agencies who provided them food and
shelter.
   Cool weather slowed the ripening of the strawberry crop, which
traditionally is ready for harvest by June 1. Officials said an
unusually heavy influx of 20,000 migrant workers, many from Mexico
and Central America, have been waiting for the work to begin.
   Warm weather over the weekend ripened many fields in the
northwestern portion of the state, and others are expected to be
ready for picking soon. Oregon is the nation's second-largest
strawberry producer after California.
   ``A lot of fields just turned red over the weekend because of
the good weather,'' Tom Graven, a division field supervisor for the
state Employment Division, said Monday.
   Roy Malensky, owner of Oregon Berry Processing Co. in Hillsboro,
west of Portland, said it was too early to say how many of the
migrants would be put to work because picking hasn't begun yet in
many fields.
   ``Last year it started with a bang and kept on going. This year
it's starting slowly and won't get into full flow till this
weekend,'' he said.
   Social service agencies have made repeated appeals for food and
blankets for the migrants, who hav been living with as many as 50
others in one room.
   The Salvation Army, one of several charitable organizations
helping feed and clothe the migrants, has distributed more than 277
tons of food and more than $100,000 worth of clothing, blankets and
items such as soap, detergent and cooking utensils.
   Once the harvest is in full swing, ``it will considerably
decrease the demands upon us,'' said Titus Herman, spokesman for
the Salvation Army in Portland.
   ``I know that many of them still have obligations to contractors
and in some cases to farmers for food,'' Titus said of the pickers.
``...Maybe for the next couple of weeks they still will be
technically without any money, but beyond that they will have money
and chances are the social services will be able to step out of the
situation, maybe not completely but considerably. We're already
seeing a decrease in demand.''
   The 1987 strawberry crop ripened early, and 20 percent of it was
left in the fields because of a picker shortage. Growers complained
that pickers were confused over the new immigration law and refused
to cross the border.
   The state still produced a bumper crop of 94 million pounds that
sold for a record $31.5 million.
   This year, migrants began arriving as early as April. Some say
they mistakenly were told they had to file immigration legalization
documents by May 4, the deadline for aliens not involved in
agricultural work.
   The agricultural workers have until Nov. 30 to file the papers.
After that, employers who hire illegal migrant workers will face
stiff penalties.
</TEXT>
