<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-DartGroup     06-13 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Dart Group,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dart Earnings Down More Than 50 Percent in First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANDOVER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dart Group Corp. announced Monday that its
earnings dropped by more than 50 percent in the first quarter from
a year earlier, largely because of two unsuccessful attempts to
take over other companies.
   For the first quarter ended April 30, the retailer's net income
was $10.7 million, or $5.89 a share, down from $28.5 million, or
$15.24 per share, in the same period in 1987.
   First-quarter revenue increased, on the other hand, to $96.6
million from $85.8 million a year earlier.
   During the first quarter of 1987, Dart made a greater profit on
the sale of stocks acquired in an unsuccessful attempt to take over
Supermarkets General Corp. than it did earlier this year, when it
sold stock purchased in a hostile takeover attempt of Stop & Shop
Cos., said Dart spokesman Stanley Rubinstein.
   Among its holdings, Dart Group owns Crown Books Corp. and Trak
Auto Corp.
</TEXT>
