<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DomePetroleum     06-13 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dome Petroleum,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Says It Offered to Top Bid for Dome</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: All dollar figures are U.S.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CALGARY, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cantario Petroleum Ltd. said Monday it
had proposed to top Amoco Canada's $4.18 billion bid for Dome
Petroleum Ltd., but a Dome executive said his company declined to
consider the proposal because it was conditional and Dome had
questions about the financing.
   Brian Little, a Dome executive, told reporters that Cantario's
proposal included a condition that Dome cancel its agreement to be
acquired by Amoco Canada Petroleum Co. before Cantario made its
formal offer.
   The previously-undisclosed proposal was revealed on the first
day of a fairness hearing before Justice Gregory Forsyth of the
Alberta Court of Queen's Bench. Forsyth is to decide whether to
allow Amoco to close the acquisition deal that Dome shareholders
approved last week.
   When Forsyth asked which parties objected to the deal, a lawyer
representing Toronto businessman Abdul Rehman told the judge that
his client, acting as an agent for Cantario, had proposed to pay
about $4.9 billion for Dome last June.
   Rehman was in the courtroom, but refused to answer reporters'
questions about Cantario or its bid.
   The lawyer, Garold Switzer, told Forsyth he would argue that the
Cantario bid should have been disclosed to shareholders before they
voted on Amoco's offer last week. Shareholders, who voted 88
percent in favor of accepting Amoco's offer, were not informed of
the offer.
   Little said the Cantario offer wasn't disclosed because ``we
didn't think there was anything to disclose.''
   Dome asked Cantario to remove the condition on its offer and was
ready to review it, Little said, but Cantario said its bid was
valid only if the Amoco deal ended.
   Little said Cantario told Dome it had a line of credit with a
major Canadian bank, but that the chairman of the bank denied the
line of credit existed. He said Dome went back to Cantario and was
told Cantario was trying to arrange credit with another bank but
never got back to Dome.
   When asked by reporters why Cantario hadn't gone public with its
bid before now, Switzer said his client had hoped one of the other
parties to the Amoco deal would succeed in blocking it.
</TEXT>
