<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BankBid     06-13 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Bid,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Of New York, Irving to Meet in Takeover Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top officials of Irving Bank Corp. and Bank of
New York Co. Inc. plan to meet Wednesday to see if they can resolve
their bitter takeover dispute, the companies disclosed Monday.
   Irving Bank, the target of a hostile $1.1 billion takeover bid
by Bank of New York, proposed the meeting after a state Supreme
Court justice, Herman Cahn, informally suggested the two sides
explore whether there was any way to conclude the dispute on a
friendly basis, Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady said.
   Cahn is hearing one of several suits that have been filed in the
case.
   The meeting is to include the chairman of each company as well
as two board members from each concern who are not employees of the
company.
   Brady cautioned that he did not expect Bank of New York to bring
any new proposals to the meeting, and indicated he did not believe
Irving's willingness to meet necessarily signaled the end of its
resistance to the hostile bid.
   Telephone calls to Irving after business hours on Monday were
not answered.
   In trading Monday on the New York Stock Exchange, Irving fell 25
cents a share to $64.75 while Bank of New York rose 12.5 cents a
share to $33.50.
   Irving Bank said in a letter to Bank of New York that it was
``ready to receive and consider any proposal Bank of New York
wishes to make.''
   It noted in the letter that ``if we were to merge, the senior
management of each would have to participate fully in structuring a
transaction.''
   Irving said it planned to be represented at the meeting by its
chairman, Joseph A. Rice; its president, Samuel F. Chevalier, and
two or more of its outside directors, among others.
   Bank of New York representatives will include Bank of New York's
chairman and chief executive, Carter Bacot, and two of its outside
directors, among others, said Brady.
   Bank of New York is making a tender offer of $15 in cash and
1.575 of its shares for each of Irving's 18.5 million shares
outstanding.
   Irving has rejected the offer, and opted for a friendly merger
with the state-run Banca Comerciale Italiana SpA, Italy's second
largest bank.
   The Banca Commerciale bid is part of a complex restructuring
plan that includes sale of Irving assets, several cost-cutting
measures and a special dividend. The proposal still requires
regulatory approval.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
