<2ND_LINE>AM-Kaiser-CEO,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Denver Accountant Named to Head Kaiser Steel Corp.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANCHO CUCAMONGA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kaiser Steel Corp., which is
reorganizing under protection of a federal bankruptcy court, said
Monday that Richard E. Stoddard, a Denver accountant and attorney,
has been named to the new position of chief executive.
   The appointment has been approved by the unsecured creditors of
the one-time industrial giant, and has been submitted for approval
to U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Denver, which is handling Kaiser's
Chapter 11 case.
   Stoddard, 37, managing director of the Denver law firm of Roath
& Brega, has worked in the past with employee- and retiree-owned
companies. Under Kaiser's reorganization plan, retirees would be
the biggest stockholder group through two trusts that deal with
retirement and medical benefits.
   Kaiser, which filed for Chapter 11 protection from its creditors
in February 1987, moved its headquarters from Fontana, site of its
closed plant, to nearby Rancho Cucamonga this month.
   The reorganization plan before the court calls for Kaiser to
develop a 900-acre industrial park on the site of the Fontana
plant, and to open a dump for municipal waste at its shuttered
Eagle Mountain iron ore mine in Riverside County.
   Kaiser Coal Co., a subsidiary with idled mines in Sunnyside,
Utah, and Raton, N.M., will file a separate reorganization plan.
</TEXT>
